<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0664 04-05 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Criticizes Jackson, Gore</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS grafs 3-6 with late appearance, arrival back in
Boston; edits 4th graf pvs for transition, pick up 5th graf pvs,
bgng: Polls indicate</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis cautiously criticized Jesse
Jackson's involvement in the Panamanian standoff and expressed
irritation with Sen. Albert Gore Jr. on Monday as he struggled to
pull out a victory in the critical Wisconsin primary.
   In a long, final day of campaigning around the state, Dukakis
repeatedly likened himself to John F. Kennedy, who scored an
important primary victory in Wisconsin in his 1960 presidential
campaign.
   Campaigning before students in Stevens Point, in his last
appearance of the night, he urged that those who support him try to
round up a little last-minute help.
   ``When you go home tonight, make a few phone calls, get a hold
of your neighbors. Believe me, your work will make
the...difference,'' Dukakis said.
   Arriving back in Boston Monday night, he was asked about his
prospects in Wisconsin.
   ``We've worked hard. It looks good. But you never know until the
votes come in,'' he said.
   Earlier, Dukakis recalled Kennedy's success in reversing a round
of steel industry price hikes in 1962, and said he would summon
Chrysler Corp. President Lee Iacocca to the White House ``fast''
and demand that he drop plans to close a plant in Kenosha.
   Polls indicate Dukakis and Jackson are locked in a tight race in
Wisconsin, just as they are running neck and neck nationally in the
chase for national convention delegates.
   The Massachusetts governor said it was a ``bad idea'' for his
Democratic presidential rival to suggest taking on the role of
mediator between the Reagan administration and Panamanian strongman
Manuel Noriega.
   But he softened his criticism when he said he thought Jackson
had acted out of good intentions, and again when he said he
understood that Jackson had issued a clarifying statement on the
subject. Jackson said he had asked Noriega to leave the country,
not offered to mediate.
   Even so, Dukakis said, ``I think it's a bad idea for a private
citizen to try to inject himself'' into the situation.
   Asked about Jackson's much-heralded trip to Syria in 1984 when
he won the release of captured Navy flyer Robert Goodman, Dukakis
replied, ``I think the principle is the same.''
   Dukakis was less charitable toward Gore, who rays the governor
has been ``absurdly timid'' in criticizing Jackson for fear of
offending black voters.
   Dukakis cut off one reporter who began to ask about the subject,
and said, ``Sen. Gore ought to start campainging for the
presidency.''
   He noted that he and Jackson disagree on the Middle East,
proposals for an oil import fee and other subjects.
   Asked later if he thought Gore were serious about winning the
party's nomination, Dukakis said, ``I don't know what he's serious
about.''
   Dukakis noted that Gore hasn't won any contests outside the
South except the Nevada caucuses.
   Dukakis' criticism of Jackson came at a time when aides said the
Wisconsin race appeared extremely tight.
   While a weekend poll in the Milwaukee Journal gave Dukakis an
eight-point lead over Jackson in Wisconsin, the Massachusetts
governor and his aides portrayed Tuesday's primary as a much closer
match-up.
   ``It's too close to call,'' said Will Robinson, deputy political
director for the campaign. ``We'll take any kind of win we can
get.''
   Dukakis told reporters, ``I don't have to win'' in Wisconsin.
``I just have to win a good plurality of delegates by June 9,'' the
end of the primary season.
   Wisconsin is regarded as a critical test of Dukakis' candidacy,
following losses in earlier industrial state contests in Michigan
and Illinois. He and Jackson are running neck and neck in the race
for delegates to the Democratic National Convention, and many party
leaders have expressed concern that Jackson, a black liberal
contender with roots in the civil rights movement, would lead
Democrats to a crushing defeat in the fall.
   Thus, a defeat in Wisconsin would seriously damage Dukakis'
chances for winning the nomination, and would almost certainly
rekindle talk of a draft-Mario Cuomo movement in the two weeks
remaining before the New York governor's home state primary on
April 19.
</TEXT>
