<HEAD>23,000 Turn out for White House Easter Egg Roll</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 23,000 children and their parents turned
the White House south lawn into a kiddie carnival, celebrating an
Easter Egg Roll that has been a tradition for 110 years.
   The children were entertained by an Uncle Sam on stilts, by tiny
actor Emmanuel Lewis of the ``Webster'' TV show, and by all sorts
of cartoon characters from the comic strip ``Peanuts.''
   Monday's crowd filled the White House's south grounds where
normally helicopters deliver VIPs, bands march and presidents speak.
   Vice President George Bush brought his wife, three children and
five of his 10 grandchildren. He seemed to have a good time
autographing wooden Easter eggs.
   The rolling was only a small part of the festivities. It
consisted of eight youngsters lining up and using wooden spoons to
urge their respective eggs toward the finish line. The winners each
got a brightly colored wooden egg. So did the losers.
   On the grounds also were hidden eggs autographed by hundreds of
movie stars ranging from Ann-Margret to Efrem Zimbalist Jr.
