<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidates-Labor     04-05 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Labor,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Labor Favorites Not Holding Up Well In Presidential Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One by one, the favorite presidential
candidates of some of the nation's union leaders are falling by the
wayside.
   Eight days ago it was Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, the
personal choice of United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber.
Gephardt finished a distant third in Michigan's caucuses and
withdrew last Monday.
   Today, in Wisconsin's primary, leaders of the United Steel
Workers union expect their preferred choice, Illinois Sen. Paul
Simon, to be weeded from the Democratic field.
   ``Quite sadly, tomorrow is going to show Simon to be yesterday's
tomatoes,'' Joel Vattendahl, director of USW's 14,000-member
District 32 headquartered in Milwaukee, said on the eve of the
primary.
   While the union was abiding by AFL-CIO guidelines to encourage
their members to support any candidate of their choice, Simon had
clearly become the choice by default of the USW's leaders.
   The first choice of USW President Lynn Williams had been New
York Gov. Mario Cuomo, whom he has served as an adviser on
industrial policy.
   Vattendahl now believes that Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
will edge out Jesse Jackson among the union's members in Wisconsin,
who are mostly foundry workers, with Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
also finishing ahead of Simon.
   ``I would have thought Simon would have caught on better; he's
been with us for 30 years and we've been with him,'' Vattendahl
said. ``But it's not happening that way.''
   Going into today's votes, Simon actually has more delegates to
the Democratic National Convention in July among union members than
any of the other candidates, all from his victory in the Illinois
primary March 15.
   The latest AFL-CIO tabulations show him with 20 elected labor
delegates, followed by Jackson with 15, Gore with 10, Dukakis with
six and Gephardt with two.
   The steelworkers were instrumental in persuading Simon to stay
in the race through the Illinois primary and had hoped he would do
well enough in Wisconsin to remain a candidate through the April 26
primary in Pennsylvania, where the union has its biggest political
strength.
   But Gary Hubbard, a USW spokesman, said Dukakis and Jackson have
been on the phone with steelworkers union members around the
country who had been supporting Simon, offering them delegate slots
for their support.
   ``So far it's being resisted,'' he added.
   Leaders of Wisconsin's biggest union, the 48,000 teachers who
belong to the National Education Association, also believe Dukakis
will edge out Jackson among their members today.
   Jackson, however, has endeared himself to Wisconsin union
members facing the greatest strife: 5,500 workers at a Kenosha
Chrysler plant to be closed next summer and striking meatpackers at
Cudahy and paper workers at DePere.
   ``Al Gore visited us and Dukakis showed up at the Labor Temple
in Green Bay,'' said Roger Murphry, one of 370 mostly white Paper
Workers on strike the past 10 months against International Paper
Co.'s De Pere mill.
   ``But they're just reading off the script Jesse wrote,'' Murphy
said.
   Mark Rosenbaum, president of United Food and Commercial Workers
Local P-40 in Cudahy, which is striking the Smithfield Foods'
meatpacking plant, has made trips to California to raise campaign
money on Jackson's behalf.
   ``The picket line is white, the strikebreakers are black,'' said
Allen Zack, a UFCW spokesman. ``The company orchestrated letters to
Jackson from scabs saying that he was selling them out. And he
replied: A scab is a scab. Our Cudahy people are big Jackson fans.''
   Jackson also has won the endorsement of UAW Local 72 in Kenosha,
which represents the Chrysler workers, after appearing with them in
protest rallies in January when the company announced its intention
to close the plant next summer.
   Both Gore and Dukakis in the past week have denounced Chrysler
Chairman Lee Iacocca in campaign appearances, but labor leaders
view those actions as too little and too late.
   ``The problem is people who are striking or are in trouble are
the ones who vote, and those who are working don't,'' said Joan
Baggett, political director for the bricklayers union and a Dukakis
supporter. ``That raises a real question about us getting a
November-electable candidate.''
</TEXT>
