<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Polls     04-05 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Polls,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pollsters Say Wisconsin Crucial in Jackson's Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's showing in today's Wisconsin
primary will be a key measure of his emergence as a candidate who
could have sufficient support to win the Democratic nomination and
the presidency, pollsters say.
   As Jackson has improved his ability to win votes, the poll
analysts noted Monday, the expectations for his campaign have
increased. If he has done well, they said, he now needs to do
better still.
   ``It may be a constantly moving target,'' said CBS News pollster
Keating Holland. ``The frontier is moving. Twenty percent of the
white Democratic vote and all the black vote is not going to win
the election in November.''
   Jackson gained co-frontrunner status when he upset Gov. Michael
Dukakis in the Michigan caucuses March 26. No polls were done there
to indicate the demographics of Jackson's support.
   Dukakis then beat Jackson in Connecticut's primary, where
Jackson got about 20 percent of the white vote. In Wisconsin, a
Milwaukee Journal poll last week put Jackson's white backing at 30
percent.
   ``In this state certainly he's a viable candidate,'' said Jeff
Browne, the Journal editor who ran the poll. Though it gave Dukakis
a slim lead, he said, it probably understated Jackson's support by
underestimating black turnout.
   Blacks have been the most reliable of Jackson's supporters
throughout the primary season, voting for him with near-unanimity.
At the same time, ``You have to have white voters to be a viable
candidate,'' said Mary Klett, poll analyst for NBC News. ``There
are some white voters going his way. But it will have to be much
larger before he could get the nomination.''
   Wisconsin and the New York primary April 19 are crucial to
indicate that vote-getting ability, Klett said. ``What happens in
Wisconsin is going to be pivotal in New York,'' she said. Jackson,
she suggested, ``has to win one of those states or both.''
   ``I wouldn't put a number on it; it's the number of Democrats
that are voting for him,'' Klett said. ``When he gets most of them
voting for him, that's when he becomes viable.''
   There are other measures as well. In Wisconsin, the Journal poll
last week showed Vice President George Bush leading Jackson in a
hypothetical general election race by 50 percent to 36 percent.
   ``That strikes me as extremely close for Jackson in this state,
considering how well known Bush is and how well liked (President)
Reagan is,'' Browne said. He noted that Dukakis and Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. both fared even better in matchups against Bush.
   Another issue in gauging Jackson's strength is in the nature of
the white votes he is attracting. Exit polls in Connecticut said he
did best with liberals and lost the blue-collar vote _ critical in
the general election _ by 2-1. An analysis of the Michigan caucus
results also indicated that Jackson was not particularly strong in
blue-collar precincts, Holland said.
   Still another measure is the share of voters who have a
favorable opinion of Jackson. Although his rating has improved, the
last national survey by CBS News and The New York Times, done March
19-22, said more white Democrats had an unfavorable opinion of him
_ 39 percent _ than the 31 percent favorable. Holland said. Among
all white voters it was 46 percent unfavorable to 22 percent
favorable, he said.
   ``You say to yourself, very few white Republicans are going to
vote for him. You then write off half the Democrats as well, and
you're not looking at much of an electoral base,'' said Holland.
``You can see why people will be putting increasing hurdles in
front of him.''
   ``He is increasing his white vote,'' the CBS analyst said. ``If
that's the case it may be acceptable to say, Let's see how far you
can go with this. Can you reach the point where you can win in
November? Twenty percent is not there. I would guess it's not 30
percent.''
   I.A. Lewis, chief of polling for the Los Angeles Times, said he
retained his view that Jackson is able but unlikely to win the
nomination and unable to win in November. He cited Jackson's
liberal positions as well as ``an element of racism that exists in
America today.''
   Nonetheless, `There's already been a profound change. Jackson
has been to a certain extent legitimized by his very impressive
victories,'' said Lewis. In turn, he said, whatever the outcome,
``Jackson is legitimizing blacks as legitimate presidential
contenders.''
</TEXT>
