<DOCNO> AP880405-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Money     04-05 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Money,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Brings In $2 Million Plus in March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's once-impoverished presidential
campaign is showing new fund-raising strength, collecting an
impressive $2.2 million in donations during March _ more than he
raised during all of last year.
   The sum, coming mostly in contributions of $50 or less,
represents a dramatic upswing for what Jackson frequently boasts is
the ``poor campaign with the rich message.''
   Bob Farmer, finance chairman for the Democratic field's
consistent fund-raising leader, Michael Dukakis, was laudatory when
told Monday about Jackson's money.
   ``That's a tremendous achievement for Rev. Jackson,'' he said.
``Anybody that can raise $2 million in a month is a hero to me.''
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, collected donations
totaling more than $2.5 million during March, Farmer said. Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee raised about $1.5 million during
March, his campaign said last week.
   Jackson has been picking up most of his money in small
contributions through an aggressive direct-mail and telemarketing
program. The program banked $1 million during March, said Jackson's
mail consultant, Mal Warwick of Berkeley, Calif. He said the
returns are the most impressive of any campaign he has ever
conducted in 10 years of fund-raising.
   Farmer said Dukakis has gotten contributions averaging $135 each
over the past 90 days.
   During all of 1987, Jackson raised just under $2 million, while
Dukakis raised $10.8 million.
   ``He has emerged as a significant player and that's reflected in
his financial performance,'' Farmer said of Jackson. ``You're
beginning to see this as a two-man race and the fund raising is the
first benchmark of success.''
   He said Jackson ``should be very proud'' of his mail returns.
   Jackson campaign spokeswoman Pam Smith said Jackson's March
receipts surprised even campaign manager Gerald Austin, who had
projected contributions of about $1 million. In all, Jackson
collected $3 million, including about $800,000 in federal matching
funds. Dukakis took in about $3.4 million, including $875,000 in
federal matching funds.
   Jackson's fund-raising boost is timely as the expensive New York
primary approaches on April 19.
   ``They're really banking for New York,'' Smith said, noting that
television ad time in New York City is particularly expensive. By
contrast, she said, the campaign spent a total of $100,000 on
today's Wisconsin primary, with about half going to TV ads.
   Jackson generally relies on a grassroots network of volunteers,
eliminating the large payroll common to more wealthy campaigns.
   Warwick said Jackson's mail returns ``have picked up since Super
Tuesday,'' when Jackson polled first in popular vote and second in
delegates across 20 state primaries and caucuses on March 8.
   In addition to the direct mail campaign, Smith said Jackson
raised about $140,000 during a two-day fund-raising swing through
California, where national campaign chairman Willie Brown put on a
series of fund-raising events.
   Jackson also collected about $120,000 at events in Michigan
prior to the March 26 caucuses where he won a landslide victory.
   Dukakis got about half his March donations from three days of
big-ticket fund-raising events in Washington, New York and Boston,
Farmer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
