<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pena-Contras     04-05 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pena-Contras,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Adviser Details Effort To Sell Weapons To Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An adviser to House Speaker Jim Wright says he
contacted Oliver North associate Richard Miller nearly two years
ago in a bid to broker a weapons deal for the Contras but did not
know he was tapping into the North private aid network.
   In a deposition taken by congressional Iran-Contra investigators
and released Monday, Richard Pena said that he only met North once
briefly and that Miller ``may have mentioned'' North.
   He said he had a sense that Miller, a public relations man with
ties to the Contras, might be able to get a weapons offer to them
and so Pena asked him about the possibility in the spring of 1986.
   Wright, a Texas Democrat and longstanding opponent of U.S.
military aid to the Contras, has said he had no idea his friend and
adviser was trying to sell them weapons.
   Pena, a former Foreign Affairs Committee staff member, has
traveled to Central America as Wright's observer and emissary in
the evolving peace process between the U.S.-backed Contras and the
leftist Nicaraguan government.
   North is charged in the Iran-Contra affair on a variety of
counts stemming from his clandestine operation to supply the
Contras. Miller named North as a co-conspirator when Miller pleaded
guilty to illegally using a tax-exempt foundation for the
non-exempt purpose of raising money to arm the Contras.
   Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., the vice chairman of the House
Iran-Contra investigating committee, said last week that he does
not recall if the committee staff ever told him about Pena's
connection or that Pena had given a deposition. Pena was not called
as a witness by the committee.
   At the time of the contact with Miller, the House had approved
$100 million in new aid for the rebels after a cutoff that had left
the Contras supplied only through North's secret operation.
   Pena was trying to see that some of that money be used to
purchase items such as grenades and bombs from a Chilean arms
manufacturer.
   Pena told the investigators he knew only that Miller had a
public relations involvement with the rebels, but he sensed there
was ``something there'' that could lead to an arms deal.
   Investigators asked him why he would go to the head of a
Washington public relations firm rather than just dealing directly
with the Contras from the start.
   ``He seemed to have had a very good working relationship with
them,'' Pena said. ``He told me that he would talk to the right
people in the administration.''
   But Pena subsequently took the arms proposal directly to the
Contras, according to documents referred to in his deposition. He
gave Contra official Bosco Matamoros a list of weapons available
from the Chilean company, Industrias Cardoen, on Aug. 12, 1986.
   On Aug. 15, Pena wrote a letter to a front company in the Cayman
Islands that Miller had set up to handle his Contra transactons
with North, and to which he had told Pena to address the proposal.
   Pena included the weapons list with his letter.
   ``I passed it on to Col. North,'' Miller said in his deposition.
``Mr. Pena asked me to pass it on to whoever the appropriate person
was.''
   Pena said nothing ever came of the offer.
   Asked if he had any personal contact with North, Pena said he
had met him many years ago at an Organization of American States
reception.
   Pena, who works for a Washington public relations firm, has not
returned several messages left at his office in the past 11 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
