<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PowerFluctuation 1stLd-Writethru a0816 04-05 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Power Fluctuation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0816,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Fluctuates In Three Western States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with minor radioactive leak,
phenomenon extending into South Dakota. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``In
Wyoming.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power fluctuation caused lights to
flicker and dim Monday in Colorado, Wyoming, Montana and parts of
South Dakota, and was blamed for a minor radioactive gas leak,
officials said.
   Dennis Eyre, administrative manager for the Western Systems
Coordinating Council based here, said utility employees in the
affected states were working to discover the cause.
   In portions of Wyoming, power went completely out for a brief
period, but in most of the affected areas power levels were only
reduced, he said.
   The trouble occurred at 2:18 p.m. MDT, he said. There were no
reports of serious problems resulting from the power dips, he said.
   Colorado officials said the fluctuation caused a radioactive gas
leak and temporarily closed the Fort St. Vrain Nuclear Generating
Station near Platteville.
   Mark Severts, spokesman for Public Service Co. of Colorado in
Denver, said the leak posed no danger to the public or plant
workers. He said it was less than one-thousandth of the
concentration the utility is authorized to release on a scheduled
basis.
   In Wyoming, Rick Kaysen, customer service manager for Cheyenne
Light, Fuel and Power Co., attributed the fluctuation to problems
at a Grizzly, Ore., substation that idled three generating stations
in Colorado.
   Eyre said he had heard nothing about the Oregon substation.
   ``There is a lot of speculation going around. We'd rather not
speculate,'' Eyre said.
   The Western Systems Coordinating Council is one of nine regional
councils that coordinate power distribution in the United States
and parts of Canada and Mexico. The regional councils were created
after a 1965 East Coast power outage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MinnesotaDelegates     04-05 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minnesota Delegates,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Split Decision In Minnesota Likely For Jackson, Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson and Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis are virtually tied in the race for delegates from
Minnesota, where a plurality of state convention delegates have
moved into the uncommitted column.
   Dukakis, whose campaign estimated last month that he would win
more than twice as many national convention delegates as Jackson in
Minnesota, was clinging to a one-vote lead among delegates elected
to the state convention.
   With returns from county conventions, accounting for 75 percent
of the 1,262 delegates elected to the state convention, Dukakis was
supported by 219 while Jackson had 218 and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon
had 78. Another 423 state convention delegates were uncommitted.
   If these results held up at the state and congressional district
conventions, where Minnesota Democrats pick 78 of their national
convention delegates in May and June, Jackson would win 19 national
delegates, Dukakis would receive 18, Simon would gain one and 40
would be uncommitted.
   ``I don't know if anything has really happened,'' said Tad
Devine, who oversees national delegate selection for the Dukakis
campaign. ``I've always viewed this as an evolving process.
   ``We view this as a very active delegate-selection process, and
we'll be trying in the weeks ahead to win as many delegates as we
can from Minnesota,'' he said in a telephone interview from Boston.
   Minnesotans began their delegate-selection process on Feb. 23
with precinct caucuses but because of a conflict with national
party rules, the results of those caucuses were never clearly
reported.
   Minnesota Secretary of State Joan Growe tried to produce a count
on caucus night, but the results were incomplete and in some places
were tallied incorrectly.
   The state party itself tried to produce a count two weeks later
based on a paper ballot filled out at the caucuses, but so many of
the ballots were disallowed that those results too became
unreliable.
   Based on Growe's results, the Dukakis campaign earlier had
projected that Dukakis would end up with 27 of the 78 Minnesota
National Convention delegates that are elected through the process
that begins with the precinct caucuses. According to the Dukakis
campaign's initial tally, Jackson and Simon would have received 13
delegates each, Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt would have received
one, and 24 delegates would have been uncommitted.
   The Dukakis campaign shut down its campaign office in Minnesota
following the precinct caucuses. Devine said Dukakis campaign
workers will be returning to Minnesota after the Tuesday's primary
in Wisconsin.
   ``Our plans are, as soon as we're through with Wisconsin, a
number of people working there will be freed up to work on our
efforts in Minnesota, and I expect we will put a lot of effort into
that state,'' he said.
   ``In terms of the effort we would like to make there, it's most
effective to work in the latter stages of the caucus process, in
terms of getting out your supporters,'' Devine said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Dole-Dirksen Bjt   04-05 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole-Dirksen, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0418 to restore cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Bush Defeat Could Hand Dole New Platform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Vice President George Bush stumbles on his
way to the White House this November, erstwhile rival Bob Dole
could wind up as the nation's top GOP spokesman.
   The Senate minority leader under a Democratic administration
could find himself playing the lead in a 1980s version of the 1960s
Ev and Charlie Show.
   It might well be called the Bob and Bob show, with Dole being
joined by House Minority Leader Bob Michel of Illinois to counter a
Democratic president's programs and present alternatives to them.
   The Ev of Ev and Charlie was Senate Minority leader Everett
McKinley Dirksen of Illinois.
   Dirksen teamed with House Minority Leader Charles Halleck of
Indiana in a regular series of televised news conferences, Dirksen
became the undisputed ``Mr. Republican'' of his era.
   Dole, crowded out of the 1988 Republican field by Bush, has
returned to his leadership position in the Senate, serving notice
he intends to prod the GOP into opening its arms to a wider
constituency.
   Republicans should, Dole says, address issues of concern to the
homeless and the poor and embrace programs to deal with narcotics,
day care, education, long-term health care, Medicaid and Medicare.
   ``We must, above all, give more Americans a reason to come our
way and at the same time strengthen the commitment of our
staunchest supporters,'' Dole said last week.
   With a sense of humor that can be dark and biting, Dole will
have his own distinct style and image if he emerges as national
spokesman for the GOP.
   Dirksen was ``full of fun and thunder,'' said Dirksen biographer
Neil McNeil.
   McNeil, in his 1970 ``Dirksen: Portrait of a Public Man,'' said
the Senate minority leader became a television superstar despite a
complete lack of the veneer said to be essential to a politician in
the age of television.
   ``His tousled hair, long his trademark, was an easily
recognizable ensign,'' McNeil wrote. ``His deep-throated husky
voice, his flamboyant manners and his often astonishing use of a
rococo vocabulary all tickled the viewing millions.''
   Washington Post cartoonist Herblock caricatured Dirksen as a
melancholy clown, Halleck as a buffoon and straight man.
   Halleck resented the Ev and Charlie tag. He took his
partisanship seriously.
   But Dirksen said he liked the name, said it reminded him of such
other all-American duos as corned beef and cabbage and ham and eggs.
   Some Republicans said they thought the two stood in poor
contrast to John F. Kennedy, the nation's new, youthful and
handsome Democratic president.
   One complained about Dirksen's ``fuzzy hair'' and Halleck's
``big red nose.''
   ``None of this troubled Dirksen,'' McNeil wrote, ``for even as
the criticisms were being made, he and Halleck were getting
television and press coverage to make the opposition's case against
the Kennedy administration. In time, he sensed, the criticism would
wane and he would be better off for the national notoriety he was
now receiving.''
   Dirksen and Halleck used the Ev and Charlie routine to showcase
criticism of the Kennedy domestic program.
   ``It may be called the New Frontier, but the Kennedy program is
the old New Deal taken out of an old warming oven,'' Dirksen said.
   He scored the administration for ``deficit spending, increased
government controls, increases in the government payroll, more
welfare statism and that inevitable price which we must pay the
piper, more taxes.''
   By mid 1962 the Ev and Charlie show was fully launched and
obviously effective in stating the Republican case. The ridicule
evaporated.
   No Republican leader since has had anything quite resembling his
disheveled flair, rumpled charm and widespread appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
