<DOCNO> AP880405-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham-Perspective     04-05 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham-Perspective,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impeachment Conviction Places Mecham In Infamous Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With his ouster, Evan Mecham joined a
short but ignominious list of convicted governors, among them a
chief executive whoused the National Guard to surround his Capitol
and one who declared martial law.
   Monday's vote by the state Senate to sustain the two articles of
impeachment made Mecham the first U.S. governor to be impeached and
removed from office in 59 years.
   Legal scholars say impeachment was devised in England, where
Parliament used it as a way to flex its muscle against kings and
ministers. Impeachment was brought to America in colonial days as a
way to protect democracy.
   ``It's basically, `You're fired.' Impeachment is a way to get
out of office those officials that violate the public trust,'' said
University of Arizona law professor Robert Glennon.
   Had he been acquitted, Mecham would have joined the likes of
Thomas Jefferson and Huey Long, the flamboyant ``Kingfish'' of
Louisiana, among governors who were impeached by legislators but
not convicted.
   Instead, he became one of seven chief executives who have been
removed from office, including the first governor of Nebraska and a
pair of governors in Oklahoma.
   Gov. David Butler of Nebraska was removed in 1871 for
misappropriating school funds, but the impeachment proceedings
subsequently were expunged from the legislative record and in 1888
he was elected to another term as governor.
   Gov. John C. Walton of Oklahoma was removed in 1923 after he
declared martial law and ordered the National Guard to disband a
grand jury that was investigating him.
   Gov. Henry S. Johnston, also of Oklahoma, used equally strong
tactics to try to prevent an investigation of him. Johnston ordered
the National Guard to surround the Capitol to prevent the
Legislature from assembling to conduct the probe. Johnston, who was
removed in 1929, was the last governor ousted from office by
legislators before Mecham.
   Also on the list is Gov. William W. Holden of North Carolina,
who was removed in 1871 after he unconstitutionally suspended the
right of habeas corpus and sent militia to quell violence by the Ku
Klux Klan, which was accused of murders aimed at frightening blacks
into not voting.
   In Arizona, the governor need only commit ``high crimes,
misdemeanors, or malfeasance'' to face impeachment. Mecham,
convicted of obstruction of justice and misusing funds, is the
first Arizona governor to be impeached.
   Jefferson was impeached by Virginia' colonial Assembly in 1781.
Among the charges was that he had fled with unseemly haste when
British troops attacked the capital. Although the Assembly soon
backed down, Jefferson insisted on a trial and won vindication.
   Long was impeached on charges of misusing state funds in 1929.
The case was dropped when 15 senators _ enough to block conviction
_ announced their support for the governor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-NATOFlights     04-05 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-NATO Flights,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute In West Germany Over NATO Low-Level Flights</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two jet warplane crashes near
West German nuclear power plants have increased criticism of NATO
pilot-training practices, and one newspaper's coverage of the issue
has angered the U.S. Air Force.
   Tens of thousands of West German protesters joined traditional
Easter peace marches and vigils that began Saturday and lasted
through Monday.
   This year the demonstrators not only called for scrapping
nuclear arms, but they also protested the two air crashes that
occurred near atomic power plants just over 24 hours of each other
last week.
   The Association for General Aviation, a West German organization
of private pilots, joined the protesters in demanding that NATO
keep its warplanes away from nuclear power plants.
   ``The chance of the Chernobyl nuclear accident was more than
likely very slim, but it happened anyway,'' Michael Schultz,
spokesman for the group, pointed out in a radio interview.
   The respected Wickert Institute polled West Germans and found
that 15 percent want NATO to halt its low-level military training
flights over this nation. Two-thirds of the 1,710 people polled
said such flights were necessary but the number should be reduced,
the Tuebingen-based institute said Saturday.
   A French Mirage jet fighter crashed on March 30 one mile from a
nuclear power plant in the southern state of Bavaria, killing the
pilot.
   ``We escaped the worst imaginable accident by only a
split-second,'' Herbert Weinzierl, head of the Bavarian Federation
for Nature Protection, said after the crash.
   One day later, a U.S. Air Force F-16 fighter jet crashed in the
southern town of Forst, demolishing three houses and killing a
resident and the pilot. The accident occurred nine miles east of
another nuclear power plant.
   Federal officials say nuclear power plants are sufficiently
protected from even a direct hit by falling warplanes, but
protesters say such assurances are based only on theory.
   West German newspapers have given intense coverage to the debate
of the possible threat from jet warplane crashes.
   On Sunday, the mass-circulation Bild am Sonntag newspaper
printed a front-page article headlined ``This Junk Flies Over Our
Heads,'' accompanied by what it said was pictures of a patched-up
U.S. Air Force F-16.
   The newspaper quoted an unidentified U.S. employee at Sembach
Air Base, located near the southwest city of Kaiserslautern, as
saying poor maintenance and a shortage of spare parts made U.S.
F-16 planes unsafe.
   The report said 110,000 low-level military practice flights were
conducted over West Germany annually by seven NATO-member air
forces, including the United States.
   A U.S. Air Force spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said U.S. military officials were upset over what he described as
Bild's ``highly inaccurate report.'' He said he could not verify
how many low-level flights were made over West Germany.
   The spokesman said the Americans would coordinate a response to
the Bild article because the United States is but one of several
countries involved in low-level training flights here. He declined
to elaborate.
   Other NATO nations that regularly train in West Germany airspace
include Canada, France, the Netherlands, Britain, West Germany and
Norway.
   Another spokesman told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview from U.S. Air Force European headquarters at Ramstein Air
Base that the photograph in Bild was not of an F-16.
   ``The Bild picture shows a non-operational F-4 which has been
parked near the (perimeter) fence on Sembach for some time,'' said
spokesman Douglas Moore.
   ``It's not an F-16 and doesn't even have a motor. It's only used
by technicians to practice fuselage-patching so they will be
proficient in getting a damaged airplane back in the air in
wartime,'' Moore said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
