<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0401 04-05 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0401,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Down Slightly In Tokyo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing figures; pickup 3d
pvs, `Institutional investors ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar, which fell briefly to a
three-month low against the Japanese yen Monday, regained some of
its strength Tuesday in Tokyo, while stock prices dipped slightly.
   The dollar closed at 124.43 yen, up 0.58 yen from Monday's close
of 123.85 yen. It had opened the day at 124.38 yen and traded
between 124.30-124.75 yen. On Monday, the dollar opened at at
123.70 yen, its lowest opening level since Jan. 5 when it started
trading at 123 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 53.17 points Monday, shed 19.94
points, ending the day at 26,315.35.
   ``Institutional investors and life insurance companies who had
been selling the dollar have turned to buying,'' said a dealer at a
major commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said an apparent sentiment among investors that the dollar
would no longer decline had made participants ``adjust their
positions.''
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
issues, up 53.17 points on Monday, slipped 45.08 points, to close
the morning session at 26,290.21.
   Hiromi Yoneyama of Wako Securities said there was strong buying
sentiment in the stock market, despite the drop in the key Nikkei
indicator.
   ``Profit-taking of steel and shipbuilding issues brought the
stock average down,'' Yoneyama said. ``But the market appears to be
in a positive mood prompted by the stronger dollar.''
</TEXT>
