<HEAD>Britain Promises Inquiry Into Schoolboy Deaths In Alps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education authorities today promised to conduct an
inquiry into an accident in the Austrian Alps that killed four
British schoolboys.
   The boys slid to their deaths over a precipice while walking on
a 6,500-foot mountain near Untersberg in the Salzburg district on
Monday. Two other schoolboys saved themselves by clinging to a tree.
   The six, from Altwood School in Maidenhead near London, were in
a group of 45 on a two-week sightseeing trip of Europe. They were
supervised by four teachers.
   Police said the boys got left behind by the main party. Brian
Lee, one of the supervisors, said in a radio interview that six
strayed from a path.
   Austrian police identified the dead boys as Andrew Powell-Lee,
15, Andrew Watts, 14, Michael Taylor, 13, and Daniel Howton, 14.
   Graham Williams, deputy director of education for Berkshire
county where Maidenhead is located, said the inquiry would begin
with the school being asked for a full report.
</TEXT>
