<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wisconsin Vote Tuesday May Top 1.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-way Democratic presidential primary
plus hotly contested local elections and race track referendums
were expected to lure 1.5 million voters to the Wisconsin polls
today, election officials said.
   Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson, front-runners in delegate
count for the Democratic nomination, were each seeking to gain
momentum with a victory, while Sens. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., and
Paul Simon, D-Ill., were hoping for significant boosts for their
candidacies.
   With Vice President George Bush a virtual shoo-in for the
Republican nomination, leaders of both parties talked of possible
defections to the Democratic column.
   Wisconsin's open primary law permits voters, regardless of
party, to vote for the candidates of their choice, creating what
some call ``mischief'' voting.
   A tight mayoral race in Milwaukee for the right to succeed Henry
Maier, retiring after 28 years in office, figured to boost the
voter turnout in the state's largest city.
   An estimated 1,591,000, or 45 percent of the state's 3,536,000
eligible voters, were expected to go to the polls, the State
Elections board said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kansas Senator Says VP Talk Is Only Game in Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum isn't spurning talk
that she could be George Bush's vice presidential running mate _
but she's also not taking it too seriously.
   ``You know, there are going to be 500 (possible) tickets between
now and August,'' the Kansas Republican said in a Washington
interview with The Kansas City Star.
   ``Part of the game will be for (Bush) to keep throwing out a lot
of names and speculation on who will be the vice presidential
nominee. That's the only game in town right now,'' she said. ``It's
presumptuous to think you'd even be asked.''
   Mrs. Kassebaum, who is in Japan this week, was suggested for the
vice presidential race eight years ago by Sen. S.I. Hayakawa of
California to heal rifts in the GOP on the abortion and the Equal
Rights Amendment issues. She said at the time that she did not have
the necessary experience and rejected the idea.
   ``My staff keeps saying, `Don't say no,''' she told the Star.
And she has followed their advice.
   Campaign aides to Vice President Bush, the front-runner in the
Republican presidential nomination, say they are not developing a
list of vice presidential possibilities.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Draft-Cuomo Group Sues for Place on Calif. Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of Mario Cuomo are suing in an
attempt to force elections officials to place the New York
governor's name on California's June 7 Democratic presidential
primary ballot.
   The suit, filed Monday, against Secretary of State March Fong Eu
by the Draft Cuomo for President Committee was scheduled for a
hearing Friday before Presiding Judge Cecily Bond of the Sacramento
County Superior Court.
   Eu has refused to list Cuomo among ``generally recognized''
candidates who are automatically placed on California's
presidential ballot because he has stated publicly he is not a
candidate. And she rejected the draft Cuomo committee petitions
last week on grounds they didn't contain enough voter signatures or
meet other requirements.
   Attorney Gerald Hill, state co-chairman of the draft Cuomo
committee, said his group is acting completely independent of Cuomo
``as a true draft effort.''
   Hill said his suit challenges the constitutionality of the state
law Eu cited in rejecting his draft petitions, which he said
contained the signatures of an estimated 17,000 to 20,000
California voters.
   Eu's office said she would have no comment on the suit until it
is thoroughly reviewed, but that she stood by her rejection of the
Cuomo petitions, which not only didn't contain the required number
of signatures, but also didn't come, as specified in the law, from
a group authorized by Cuomo.
</TEXT>
