<HEAD>Democratic Presidential Hopefuls Put Safety First on Shoreham
Question</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopefuls Jesse Jackson
and Sen. Paul Simon oppose opening the Shoreham nuclear power plant
on Long Island, while Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore would support legislation to allow a
federal agency to determine whether the area around the plant could
be evacuated safely, according to New York Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan.
   Moynihan said Monday he learned the candidates' positions
regarding the plant in their responses to a letter dated March 31
in which he asked each his position on legislation he had
introduced.
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency has said Long Island
could not be safely evacuated without the cooperation of state and
local officials, who have refused to participate in such planning.
However, in a controversial flip-flop, the NRC changed its own
rules last year to allow the commission to assume that state and
local officials would cooperate during an actual nuclear emergency.
   Moynihan introduced legislation last year to require the NRC to
abide by FEMA's decision. The bill was defeated in committee.
</TEXT>
