<HEAD>Gore Predicts Last-Minute Surge In Wisconsin From Undecided Voters</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 6th graf with Gore far behind front-runners in
Colorado</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WISCONSIN RAPIDS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender
Albert Gore Jr. predicted he would get a boost in today's Wisconsin
primary from the undecided vote swinging his way.
   Public opinion surveys showed Gore and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon
trailing Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson of
Chicago in the primary, in which 81 Democratic delegates are at
stake.
   But Gore predicted he will get a bigger share of the Wisconsin
vote than polls indicated.
   ``It's now clear to me, after the conversations with voters of
the last few days, and on the basis of the telephone calls to
undecided voters ... that the undecided vote here in Wisconsin is
shifting decisively in our favor,'' he said.
   Gore, who did well in last month's Super Tuesday contests, is in
need of a Northern win. And a victory here would give him a boost
going into the New York primary on April 19.
   Gore trailed far behind the two front-runners in Monday's
Colorado caucuses.
   Speaking to supporters Monday in this community troubled by
business shutdowns and layoffs, Gore said corporations must be
encouraged to invest their profits in expansion that creates jobs,
and that an employer should be required to give adequate notice to
his workers when planning to close shop.
   ``I was an original co-sponsor of the legislation to require a
different approach to plant closings, to have notification of plant
closings and projected layoffs,'' Gore said.
   ``This would give working men and women an opportunity to make
other plans and to get job training, and would also provide them
the opportunity to work with management to try to salvage a plant
before it closes,'' he said.
   A day earlier, Gore said Dukakis has been ``absolutely timid''
about criticizing Jackson.
   ``Michael Dukakis gives the impression of being scared to death
... That is the opposite of the bold leadership,'' Gore said as he
campaigned in Wisconsin.
   The Tennessee senator criticized both rivals for their lack of
experience in national affairs.
   Neither Dukakis nor Jackson ``has had as much as a single day in
national government'' to prepare themselves for the presidency,
Gore said.
   Gore said it was likely the Democratic National Convention would
meet in Atlanta with no candidate possessing enough delegate
strength to win the nomination.
   ``It likely will go more than one ballot,'' he said. ``It's
going to be a long, hard contest.''
</TEXT>
