<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine-Year-Old California Boy Becomes World's Youngest Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old California boy has been
recognized by the National Aeronautics Association as the world's
youngest pilot.
   ``Tony (Aliengena) is representative of the renewed interest of
young people in aviation,'' said NAA Vice President Milt Brown.
   ``The number of youngsters actually flying has risen
dramatically over the past few years. And Tony is one of four
individuals under the age of 16 to set records recently.''
   Brown gave Tony his certificate at the National Air and Space
Museum Monday afternoon.
   The San Juan Capitstrano boy became the youngest pilot Saturday
when he completed his transcontinental journey by landing his
father's Cessna at Hanscom Air Field in Bedford, Mass., breaking
the record set last August by 10-year-old Christopher Lee Marshall
of Oceano, Calif, officials said.
   Tony, who is known as ``Buzz,'' became the youngest pilot to fly
solo on March 13, when he flew an ultralight for a minute and 45
seconds at age 9 years 295 days. He broke the record for the
youngest pilot set by Cody A. Locke, who flew on Feb. 23, 1983 at
age 9 years 316 days.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Many Imported Aerosol Cans Contained Banned Propellant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-three percent of imported aerosol
cosmetics contained chlorofluorocarbon compounds banned as
propellants by the United States 10 years ago, according to the
Customs Service.
   The non-compliance rate is below some spot checks in the past,
according to Don Cousins, chief of the technical branch in the
Office of Technical Services in the Customs Service. The figure has
been as high as 60 percent, he said Monday.
   Customs has never before undertaken anything like the current
checks in ``Operation Ozone,'' which spokesman Dennis Shimkoski
said constituted ``pretty near 100 percent'' of all pending imports.
   The service checked 442 samples of aerosol products since Feb.
15, said Shimkoski. Of those, 188 contained the offending compounds.
   More than 60 different products were represented in the samples.
Shimkoski said most were perfumes made in France, but deodorants,
baby powders and shaving creams also were found.
   The United States banned almost all use of chlorofluorocarbon,
or CFC, compounds as aerosol propellants in 1978 out of concern
that they might be attacking the ozone layer 15 to 25 miles high
that shields the Earth from the harmful ultraviolet rays of the
sun.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Brazil Gets $109 Million to Fight AIDS, Other Diseases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank is lending Brazil $109 million
to fight AIDS and three other diseases in the northeastern part of
the country.
   It was the first time that the bank, which is owned by 151
countries, has lent money for AIDS in Latin America. Last December
the fight against acquired immune deficiency syndrome in the
African republic of Burundi was helped by financing from the fund.
   Brazil has 2,100 AIDS patients. Only the United States and
France have reported more.
   The loan, announced Monday, is being made to Brazil's Northeast
Endemic Disease Control project and will be used against
schistosomiasis, leishmaniasis and Chagas' disease, particularly
widespread among poor people in the area.
   Total cost of the project is put at $218 million. The loan is
for 15 years, including a three-year grace period during which only
interest need be paid. The World Bank charges a variable rate
beginning at 7.72 percent annually.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Call for Broad Political Amnesty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One hundred members of Congress are advising
South Korean President Roh Tae-woo to follow through on his promise
to institute a broad political amnesty.
   ``We are most concerned by reports that as many as 1,000 persons
remain in prison for political related offenses,'' said the members
in a leter to Roh Monday.
   ``While we welcome the Feb. 26 amnesty and the reported release
of 125 political prisoners, we believe that many persons who have
neither advocated nor engaged in violence remain in custody,'' the
legislators said.
   Among the signers were Sens. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., and Paul
Simon, D-Ill., who are both seeking the Democratic presidential
nomination, and Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee.
   The list of political prisoners released the day after Roh was
inaugurated Feb. 25 included only two of the 26 people who had been
declared ``prisoners of conscience'' by the private group Amnesty
International, the legislators said.
