<2ND_LINE>AM-Colorado Caucuses, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0495,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Pulls Ahead Of Jackson In Colorado Caucuses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs new results, comment from state party
chairman; pick up 7th graf pvs, bgng: Republicans also xxx. The
Colorado Democratic party has suspended counting for the night;
will stand for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael Dukakis
edged ahead of rival Jesse Jackson in Colorado's precinct caucuses
early Tuesday, after a night of furious see-saw battling.
Meanwhile, Republicans pointed to Vice President George Bush as
their heavy favorite.
   With 1,234 of Colorado's 2,784 precincts reporting, or 44
percent, Dukakis had 45 percent to Jackson's 40 percent. Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore had just 4 percent, and Sen. Paul Simon did not
garner enough votes at Monday night's caucuses to register any
support.
   Dukakis had moved to an early lead in preliminary sample
results, but that evaporated when returns from Denver began coming
in. Later, however, he moved ahead again.
   Democratic state chairman Buie Seawell, a Dukakis supporter,
said early Tuesday that Jackson had done ``one hell of a job in a
state that is not Jackson country.''
   In Colorado, Dukakis and Jackson were fighting it out for 45
national convention delegates and bragging rights to a victory on
the eve of the Wisconsin primary.
   The Colorado Democratic caucuses took on added importance
because of the tight race for delegates that has developed between
Jackson and Dukakis, with Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. trailing.
   Republicans also held caucuses to begin the process of selecting
36 delegates to the Republican National Convention.
   Republican straw poll results suggested Bush was winning
overwhelmingly. The GOP expected Bush to capture most of the
Republian support here despite weekend appearances in Colorado by
former television evangelist Pat Robertson.
   Sigrid Freese, a state Democratic spokeswoman, expected only
15,000 to 20,000 of Colorado's 570,301 registered Democrats to
attend the caucuses. ``It depends on how good the NCAA championship
basketball game is,'' she said of the Monday night game.
   At one caucus _ in Precinct 31, in Grand Junction _ the
21-member caucus solved that problem by recessing for 35 minutes to
watch the game.
   The two Democratic front-runners campaigned in Colorado over the
weekend, and both campaigns aired TV ads in hopes of attracting
supporters to the caucuses in one-time candidate Gary Hart's home
state.
   Seawell predicted Dukakis could land 15 to 20 delegates and
Jackson 15, with the remaining delegates either uncommitted or
backing Gore, who was expected to attract support outside
metropolitan Denver.
   Jackson presented himself as the candidate of hope and invoked
the memory of Martin Luther King Jr., whose was assassinated 20
years ago. ``Hope has been unleashed,'' Jackson told a crowd of
church-goers Sunday.
   Dukakis, endorsed by Seawell and Gov. Roy Romer, visited Denver
on Saturday, continuing to sound his theme that he is ``a doer''
and ``not just a talker'' but avoiding direct criticism of Jackson.
   Some political observers said the key to winning Democratic
delegates was in the Hispanic community, where Dukakis, with his
command of the Spanish language, and Jackson, with his appeal to
minorities, both hoped to fare well.
   Seawell says the outcome of future contests in California, New
Mexico and Arizona, which have large Hispanic populations, may
depend on which candidate can win Hispanic voters here.
   Hispanics make up about 12 percent of the registered voters
statewide.
   Blacks, expected to support Jackson, comprise 4 percent of
registered Democrats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham-Future Bjt   04-05 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham-Future, Bjt,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Faces Cloudy Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His governorship gone, his ailing auto
dealership sold, Evan Mecham faces a future in which one of the few
certainties is his role as defendant in a criminal trial.
   But for Arizona, the future looks brighter without the shadow of
Mecham's embarrassing impeachment trial hanging over the state,
said Rose Mofford, who became governor with Mecham's removal.
   ``Today we have reached the end of some difficult times in
Arizona,'' Mrs. Mofford, a Democrat, said Monday. ``I know the
decision made by the Senate today was not reached lightly. It is
time to put all that behind us and move forward.''
   ``Today none of us are Republicans, none of us are Democrats,''
she said. ``We are all Arizonans. Let us go forward together as
Arizonans.''
   The impeached first-term Republican was stripped of his office
Monday when the Senate convicted him of trying to thwart an
investigation of an alleged death threat and misusing the
governor's protocol fund.
   The end of the trial did not heal the divisions that arose
during Mecham's turbulent 15 months in office. Predictably, the
verdict was praised by Mecham opponents and condemned by supporters.
   Some legislators received police protection Monday night after
getting threatening phone calls that were prompted by the vote,
said Department of Public Safety spokesman Allan Schmidt.
   ``They've been all types of intimidating-type threatening
statements ranging from voter response to the ultimate,'' Schmidt
said.
   Mecham's future troubles could include a maximum 22-year prison
sentence if he is convicted on charges of concealing a $350,000
campaign loan.
   He faces trial April 21 in Maricopa County Superior Court on six
felony counts of fraud, perjury and filing false documents. His
brother Willard, who was his 1986 campaign treasurer, faces three
similar counts.
   The Senate threw out an impeachment count based on the $350,000
loan issue.
   Although the Senate did not bar Mecham from holding public
office again, his lawyer, Jerris Leonard, indicated after the
impeachment vote that Mecham may decide to bow out of politics.
   ``I think there is doubt,'' he said of whether Mecham would try
to appeal his case to voters in a recall election May 17.
   It was not clear whether the ousted governor could remain on the
recall ballot given him impeachment conviction. The matter probably
will be decided by the courts, said Attorney General Bob Corbin.
   Leonard said, ``I think the decision of where we go from now is
dependent on whether or not the governor himself wants to stay in
politics and that's something that he's got to decide overnight.''
   After Monday's conviction, Mecham left the Senate chamber
smiling. Asked what he planned next, he said, ``We'll decide
tomorrow or the next day ... We're keeping all our options open.''
   After he was impeached by the House of Representatives on Feb.
5, the 63-year-old Mecham hinted he might give up politics. ``If I
can be of service, fine,'' he said. ``If not, I'd enjoy private
life. The best person doesn't always win. Politics is not my
favorite pastime.''
   Mecham ran for governor five times before being elected in 1986.
   Although Mecham's son, Dennis, testified last week that their
Mecham Pontiac dealership in suburban Glendale was thriving, he
announced a day later that they'd been forced to sell it for $4
million because of dwindling sales.
   Dennis Mecham said bad publicity surrounding his father's
political battles had driven customers away.
   The dealership was sold last week.
</TEXT>
