<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 5thLd-Writethru a0499 04-05 1102</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0499,1,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Jackson Locked In Colorado Battle As Wisconsin Primary
Day Dawns</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 4 grafs Colorado results, Dukakis ahead of
Jackson, counting over for the night. Should stand for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael Dukakis carved out a
narrow lead over rival Jesse Jackson early Tuesday as votes were
counted in Colorado's caucuses. Each of the front-runners had hoped
for a solid win to provide ``bounce'' going into Tuesday's
Wisconsin primary, but there was no clear winner when counting was
called off for the night.
   With 1,234 of 2,784 precincts reporting, or 44 percent, Dukakis
had 46 percent to Jackson's 40 percent. Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
Jr. lagged far behind, with 4 percent, and Sen. Paul Simon wasn't
registering any support from the Monday night caucuses.
   Late Monday, preliminary returns from a party sampling of 130
precincts gave Dukakis a 2-1 lead over Jackson. But when Denver
precincts began weighing in with tallies early Tuesday morning,
Dukakis' lead disappeared in a Jackson surge. Then Dukakis battled
his way back.
   The Democratic party quit counting for the night at about 4:30
a.m. EDT. The results were still too incomplete to determine
conclusively how many national convention delegates each candidate
won.
   Meanwhile, Jackson came under fire for his contact with
Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Earlier, Dukakis called Jackson's involvement in the Panama
situation a ``bad idea.''
   Gore also criticized Jackson's correspondence with Noriega, but
he blasted Dukakis for being ``absolutely timid'' of Jackson.
   The Massachusetts governor dismissed Gore and his comments: ``I
don't know what he's serious about.''
   Jackson, Dukakis and Gore were joined by Simon campaigning
across Wisconsin on Monday. Simon is trailing badly in his effort
to win here and keep his campaign alive, while Gore needs a good
showing in the state to boost his faltering effort.
   Simon urged voters in Milwaukee to send a message Tuesday.
``We're not going to follow the pollsters; we're going to elect the
man best qualified to be president,'' he said, quipping: ``Al Gore
agrees with that too.''
   Dukakis' aides emphasized how close the race is in Wisconsin,
but Tom Loftus, speaker of the Wisconsin state assembly and a
Dukakis backer, said the Massachusetts governor ``is going to win
by enough _ three, four or five points.''
   Jackson and Dukakis, the front-runners in both states, awaited
the slow dribble of results from the 2,784 precinct caucuses in
Colorado that will divide 45 national convention delegates.
   The Republicans were holding caucuses Monday night in Colorado
as well as the Democrats. With Vice President George Bush already
having locked up the nomination, Pat Robertson's effort to win some
of the state's 36 GOP delegates was a symbolic gesture.
   Jackson and Dukakis are the front-runners in the AP delegate
count. Before the Colorado results were known, Dukakis had 653.55
votes and Jackson 646.55. Gore had 381.8 and Simon 169.5. A total
of 468.6 were uncommitted. At the Atlanta in July, 2,082 votes are
needed to win.
   Jackson again released his letter, along with a reply from
Noriega on Monday. In his letter, the Panamanian dictator rejects
Jackson's plea in a March 22 letter to leave the country.
   ``I remain convinced that it is in the best interests of the
Panamanian people for Gen. Noriega to leave. Today I reiterate my
public moral appeal for him to depart,'' Jackson said.
   But Jackson's involvement in the turbulent Panamanian situation
drew criticism from the State Department and from Dukakis and Gore.
   ``In our view proliferation of channels is a tactic that Noriega
likes to use to buy time,'' said State spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   However, Jackson said he had talked Monday afternoon by
telephone with high-ranking State Department officials _ John C.
Whitehead, the deputy secretary of state, and Michael H. Armacost,
undersecretary of state for political affairs _ and said they
offered no disagreement with his appeal for Noriega to leave.
   Dukakis told reporters in Milwaukee that ``I think it's a bad
idea for a private citizen to try to inject himself'' into a
delicate international situation. But the Massachusetts governor
added he thought Jackson had acted out of good intentions.
   Gore said Jackson had met with other foreign leaders _ such as
PLO chief Yasser Arafat and Libyan strongman Moammar Gadhafi.
Jackson campaign spokesman Eric Easter, though, said Jackson had
never met with the Libyan leader.
   ``He didn't help matters in his meetings with Arafat and
Gadhafi,'' Gore said in Madison. ``I seriously doubt if he would
help in Panama.''
   Simon, for his part, would not join the chorus of criticism of
Jackson. ``I don't criticize someone who is not on the inside, so
to speak, on how he feels he'd handle these things,'' he said.
   Gore saved his strongest criticism for Dukakis for not hitting
Jackson harder.
   ``Michael Dukakis gives the impression of being scared to
death'' to criticize Jackson and appears ``absolutely timid,'' Gore
said. ``That is the opposite of the bold leadership'' the nation
needs.
   Gore told the New York Times that Dukakis' actions are ``a
subtle form of racism.''
   Dukakis was clearly irritated by Gore.
   ``Sen. Gore ought to start camaigning for the presidency,''
Dukakis said, cutting off a reporter who sought to question him on
the issue.
   Gore lumped Dukakis and Jackson together, saying neither ``has
had as much as a single day in national government'' that would
prepare them to be president.
   That criticism of Jackson was echoed by Sen. Sam Nunn, the
Georgia Democrat who declined to enter the 1988 Democratic
presidential race.
   ``I just don't think he has the experience, and I just disagree
with him on some basic foreign policy and defense questions,'' Nunn
told reporters in Georgia.
   Nunn said Jackson should not view opposition within the party as
racist. ``I don't think it should be deemed an insult or racist,''
he said.
   And he said Jackson can't win the White House: ``If nominated, I
don't think there'd be much chance of winning.''
   That view was echoed by former President Nixon.
   ``If he is nominated, it goes without saying he cannot win. But
everyone is overplaying the fact that he would be a liability
because he is black,'' Nixon told The Washington Times. ``That is
simply not true. Jackson would be a liability because his views are
radical.''
   There was good news on the fund-raising front for Jackson, who
shocked even his own campaign by raising more than $2 million in
March. Jackson, who has run a low-budget campaign until now, will
spend the money on advertising in New York's crucial April 19
primary.
</TEXT>
