<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ParnellParole     04-05 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Parnell Parole,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Kidnapper Could Be `Marked Man' As Parole Ends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted kidnapper Kenneth Parnell will be
a ``marked man'' if he decides to return to Mendocino County, where
he was arrested for holding two boys captive eight years ago, a
county official said.
   ``Let him go to some other state. Let him stay away from this
county. There's still hard feelings here,'' Mendocino County
Supervisor John Cimolino. State Department of Corrections spokesman
Bob Gore said Parnell is to be discharged from parole today, but
that his office was not aware of any protest over the action.
   Parnell, 56, was paroled to Alameda County in the San Francisco
Bay area after serving five years in prison for kidnapping Steven
Stayner, then 7, from Merced on Dec. 4, 1972, and Timothy White,
then 5, from Ukiah on Valentine's Day in 1980. Both boys were
abducted while walking home from school.
   Although Stayner said Parnell regularly sexually abused him,
charges of child abuse against Parnell were dismissed in 1981 when
a state appeals court said the statute of limitations had expired.
   Word of Parnell's release angered Stayner, who said he can't
forgive him. During the trial, Stayner testified that Parnell
ordered him to call him ``Dad,'' renamed him Dennis Parnell and
told people Stayner was his son throughout the eight years they
roamed northern California, living in trailer parks and motels.
   A psychologist testified during Parnell's trial that Stayner had
been brainwashed by Parnell and for years was unable to attempt
escape.
   Stayner, now a 23-year-old college student and father of two,
said Parnell remains a threat to children.
   ``I pity him for the sickness he has. I wouldn't trust him
around any child of any age,'' said Stayner, who hopes to become a
police officer.
   Stayner said he escaped from Parnell on March 1, 1980, and
hitchiked 40 miles with White to seek help from Ukiah police to
save the boy from sexual abuse. Parnell had kidnapped White two
weeks earlier and held him in a one-room cabin in a remote area
west of Ukiah.
   When Parnell was released from prison in 1985, former Mendocino
County District Attorney Joseph Allen expressed concern. ``There's
no doubt in my mind he will do it again,'' Allen said.
   Mike Echols, a Colorado-based author who wrote an NBC_TV
mini-steries about the Parnell case, said Parnell told him six
months ago that he planned to move to Mendocino when his parole
expired.
   His parole conditions had required him to stay in Alameda
County, attend weekly therapy sessions and stay away from children.
He also was prohibited from traveling through Mendocino or Merced
counties.
   ``He's a free man, of course,'' Cimolino said. ``We're powerless
to do anything about where he goes. But if he comes to Ukiah, I
think he'll be a marked man.''
   Echols said Parnell, a former hotel clerk and drifter, has lived
in a Berkeley boarding house since 1985, working as a short-order
cook and dishwasher between bouts of unemployment.
   ``People have yet to forget what took place,'' said A.G.
Rochester, Mendocino County's undersheriff. ``And yet ... unless he
breaks a law, there's not much we can do about it.''
   The county opposed Parnell's three-year parole to that area
when, because of good behavior and work credits, he was released
from prison after serving five years of his concurrent eight-year,
eight-month sentences for his two kidnapping convictions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
