<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeabodyAwards     04-05 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peabody Awards,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PBS Takes 7 Prestigious Broadcasting Awards; NBC, Affiliates Get
4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable News Network was cited as ``the channel
of record for breaking news'' in winning a 1987 Peabody Award for
the best in broadcasting, while Public Broadcasting System programs
garnered seven awards.
   NBC won two awards Monday _ including one for the hit show
``L.A. Law'' _ and NBC-owned affiliates won two others. Home Box
Office won two of the 29 awards given for 1987.
   The new Star Trek series, `Star Trek: The Next Generation,'' won
an award for its episode, ``The Big Good-Bye.''
   The Peabody winners were selected by a 15-member national jury,
assembled by the University of Georgia, from more than 800 entries.
   The Atlanta-based CNN received a Peabody for its coverage of
breaking news stories in 1987. The judges cited specifically CNN's
coverage of the October stock market crash and recognized the
network as ``the channel of record for breaking news of national
and global significance.''
   The PBS series, ``Eyes On The Prize: America's Civil Rights
Years'' was produced by Blackside Inc. of Boston and chronicled the
story of the U.S. civil rights movement from the 1950s to the
present.
   ``L.A. Law,'' the dramatic series set in a Los Angeles law firm,
was hailed by the judges for its ``intelligent scripts, crisp
direction and fine acting ... what entertainment television should
strive to be.''
   The winners will receive their awards at a May 4 luncheon
sponsored by the Broadcast Pioneers in New York.
   The list of winners:
   _ABC Radio News, New York; ``Earnest Will: Americans in the
Gulf.''
   _WSM Radio, Nashville, Tenn.; ``Of Violence and Victims.''
   _KPAL Radio, North Little Rock, Ark.; overall programming in the
nation's only full-time children's radio format.
   _Mutual Broadcasting System, Arlington, Va.; ``Charities That
Give and Take.''
   _``Star Trek: The Next Generation _ The Big Good-Bye,''
Paramount Pictures Corp., Los Angeles.
   _National Public Radio, Washington; ``Weekend Edition''
presentation of ``Ryan Martin.''
   _WCPO-TV, Cincinnati; ``Drake Hospital Investigation.''
   _KNBC-TV, Los Angeles, an NBC station; ``Some Place Like Home.''
   _MacNeil@Lehrer Newshour, New York, aired on PBS; ``Japan
Series.''
   _WRC-TV, Washington, an NBC station; ``Deadly Mistakes.''
   _WCVB-TV, Boston, ``Inside Bridgewater.''
   _Cable News Network, Atlanta; live coverage of breaking news.
   _Hallmark Hall of Fame and CBS-TV; ``Foxfire'' and ``Pack of
Lies.''
   _``LBJ: The Early Years,'' NBC-TV, Louis Rudolph Films, Brice
Productions, Fries Entertainment.
   _``Corridos! Tales of Passion and Revolution,'' aired on PBS;
KQED, San Francisco.
   _``Mandela,'' Home Box Office, Titus Productions, Polymuse Inc.
   _``L.A. Law,'' NBC-TV, 20th Century Fox Television.
   _``NATURE: A Season in the Sun,'' aired on PBS; WNET@Thirteen,
New York.
   _CKVU-TV, Vancouver, British Columbia; ``AIDS and You.''
   _WXXI-TV, Rochester, N.Y.; ``Safe Haven.''
   _``Eyes on the Prize: America's Civil Rights Years,'' aired on
PBS; Blackside Inc., Boston.
   _``NOVA: Spy Machines,'' aired on PBS; WGBH-TV, Boston, and
KCET, Los Angeles.
   _``America Undercover: Drunk and Deadly,'' Home Box Office,
Niemack Productions Inc.
   _The Center for New America Media Inc., New York; ``American
Tongues.''
   _``One Village in China'' presentation of ``Small Happiness:
Women of a Chinese Village,'' PBS, Long Bow Group Inc., New York.
   _``Shoah,'' PBS, WNET@Thirteen, New York.
   _WSMV-TV, Nashville, Tenn.; ``4 The Family.''
   Two personal awards were presented:
   _Kevin Brownlow and David Gill, for ``Hollywood,'' ``Unknown
Chaplin'' and ``Buster Keaton: A Hard Act To Follow,'' produced
with Thames Television and D.L. Taffner Ltd., cited for film
archives research and restoration.
   _Karl Haas, Cleveland, for ``Adventures in Good Music,'' his
second Peabody for fighting for classical music's place on
contemporary radio.
