<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis     04-05 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Ahead in Colorado Caucuses, Awaits Today's Wisconsin Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, fresh from a flurry of
campaigning in Wisconsin, was optimistic about the outcome of
today's Democratic presidential primary in that state as he
returned to his home base.
   ``We worked hard,'' Dukakis said shortly after his chartered jet
landed at Logan International Airport just before midnight Monday.
   ``It looks good,'' he said of his Wisconsin campaign, ``but you
never know until the votes come in.''
   Early today, Dukakis and Jesse Jackson were still dueling
furiously for a first-place finish in Monday night's Colorado
caucuses. Early returns put Dukakis well ahead, but the race
narrowed dramatically in the wee hours of the morning as Denver
returns began coming in.
   When the Democratic party finished counting for the night,
Dukakis held a 46 percent to 40 percent lead over Jackson, but
fewer than half the precincts were in, and counting was not to
resume until late this afternoon.
   Before he left Wisconsin Monday, Dukakis promised in a speech in
Stevens Point that he would avoid criticism of rival Jackson.
   ``I've been in politics for 25 years and this is the first time
I've been attacked for not attacking somebody else,'' Dukakis said
at the University of Wisconsin-Stevens Point before a crowd of
2,000.
   That was in reference to another Democratic contender, Tennessee
Sen. lbert Gore Jr., repeatedly blasting Dukakis for being too
``timid'' about taking on Jackson.
   Dukakis also said he believes that either he or Jackson will
have a ``substantial lead'' in delegates by the end of the primary
season in June.
   In his final Wisconsin appearance before heading home, Dukakis
told supporters that every vote counts.
   ``When you go home tonight, make a few phone calls, get a hold
of your neighbors. Believe me, your work will make the ...
difference,'' Dukakis said.
   ``This is a very tight race. It's a very competitive race,'' he
said.
   After Dukakis left the state, Wisconsin Assembly Speaker Tom
Loftus told a reporter he believed Dukakis would come out the
winner in today's presidential preference primary.
   ``The independent, the (Sen. Paul) Simon voters are turning his
way,'' said Loftus.
   Simon, of Illinois, has trailed far behind front-runners Dukakis
and Jackson in pre-election polls, as has Gore.
</TEXT>
