<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolhouseDoor     04-05 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Schoolhouse Door,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Opening Doors To Mark `Stand In Schoolhouse Door'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several players in a national
desegregation drama will return to the University of Alabama to
mark the 25th anniversary of the day then-Gov. George C. Wallace
tried to block the entrance of two black students.
   To commemorate the event June 11 _ a milestone in the civil
rights struggle _ the university will host a three-day symposium
called ``Opening Doors,'' featuring some of the nation's leading
scholars on race relations.
   The university ``felt the best way to recognize this event was
through a symposium that focuses not only on the history of race
relations, the stand in the door, but also the present and future
of race relations,'' said Professor E. Culpepper Clark, who is
writing a book on that era.
   Clark and Harry Knopke, a university official helping to arrange
the symposium, said they believe the school was an unwilling pawn
in power plays between Wallace and the administration of President
John Kennedy.
   ``The university had a very substantive, productive plan for
integrating,'' Knopke said. ``In the late 1950s and early 1960s the
administration and others were looking seriously at ways to
integrate. There was a plan already in place for doing that when
Wallace started speaking.
   ``The university was just in the middle of it.''
   Among those who have agreed to take part in the symposium, which
will end June 11, is Nicholas Katzenbach, who as assistant attorney
general faced off with Wallace in the doorway of Foster Auditorium,
a few hours before students Vivian Malone and Jimmy Hood walked in
to register.
   Also agreeing to take part are Miss Malone, now Mrs. Mack Jones
of Atlanta; Frank Rose, president of the university at the time;
then-Dean John L. Blackburn, and George LeMaistre, a prominent
Tuscaloosa businessman who organized community support for the
school's desegregation.
   ``We wanted to bring back some of the individuals who were
involved in the Wallace stand to share their perspectives,'' Knopke
said. ``We want to make something positive out of it, something
productive and informative.''
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., was invited to represent his slain
brothers, the president and Robert Kennedy, who was attorney
general in 1963, but he said he had another commitment.
   Knopke said he doubted that Wallace, who has been in poor
health, will be able to attend, but that documentary footage of the
governor's stand will be shown.
   Wallace has said he made his stand to reduce the possibility of
violence at the university, although critics said it increased
tensions.
   An array of scholars will present papers dealing with race
relations today and what can be expected in the future, Clark said.
   ``There is always in the minds of Alabamians the fact that 25
years later we are far different than in 1963, yet we still
sometimes get in our minds that we're frozen in 1963,'' he said.
``What happened then is history and we're a far different people
than we were then.''
   The school-door standoff, Clark said, ``was a test of wills
between Wallace and the Kennedy administration, the state of
Alabama and federal authorities.'' Wallace, he said, has since
acknowledged that he made ``a terrible public relations mistake.''
   Clark said the university, with 10 percent black enrollment
today, ``is so long past all that in the actual workings of this
institution and carrying out its mission that sometimes we have to
pinch ourselves to see if that were really us and if it were, what
does it have to do with us now.''
   That, he said, is the purpose of the symposium.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
