<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeportationHearing     04-05 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deportation Hearing,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Opens Case Against Man Accused of Collaborating With
Nazis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is trying to deport a Latvian
accused of collaborating with the Nazis in a case described by one
federal official as so strong ``I would not want to be defending
it.''
   Konrads Kalejs came to United States in 1959 saying he was a
farmer in Latvia. What he failed to disclose, the government
maintains, is that he belonged to a pro-Nazi police unit in World
War II that killed Jews by the thousands.
   ``Its main task was essentially rounding people up, guarding
them and killing them,'' said Raul Hilberg, a political science
professor at the University of Vermont and an expert on the
Holocaust.
   Hilberg was the government's main witness Monday as the
Immigration and Naturalization Service opened deportation hearings.
   The government said it has evidence that Kalejs was a commander
in the Latvian Security Auxiliary Police, whose leader was
convicted in 1979 of the murders of at least 13,000 people from
1941-44.
   In 1985 the Justice Department filed for Kalejs' deportation,
saying he lied on his entrance visa and would not have been
admitted to this country if officials had known about his past.
   The government's case is expected to last several weeks. During
that time, attorneys plan to summon witnesses who survived the
Latvian death camps and present documents detailing the actions of
Kalejs and the unit.
   Kalejs, 74, of Winnetka had little to say during proceedings
Monday. He stared straight ahead as Hilberg testified, occasionally
chewing gum and whispering to his attorney, Ivars Berzins.
   As he stepped onto an elevator, Kalejs was asked for comment and
replied, ``Good morning. That's all my comment.''
   Berzins also refused to discuss the case.
   ``This is one of the strongest cases I have witnessed,'' said
Bruce J. Einhorn, deputy litigation director of the Justice
Department's Nazi-hunting arm. ``This case involves some very
powerful evidence. I would not want to be defending it.''
   During the first day of testimony before Immigration Judge
Anthony D. Petrone, government attorney Aron Golberg asked Hilberg
to describe the German invasion of Latvia and the formation of the
police unit in charge of killing Jews.
   Hilberg, the author of the book ``The Destruction of the
European Jews,'' said the Latvian Security Auxiliary Police was
formed shortly after German troops seized control of the country
from the Soviets.
   The security police was comprised mostly of Latvians who admired
Adolf Hitler and welcomed the German invasion.
   ``Some of them wanted action, wanted to be associated with
power,'' he said. ``There was also promise here of compensation.''
   Asked if members volunteered, Hilberg replied, ``Absolutely.''
   ``Anyone with scruples would obviously not volunteer without
realizing what was going on,'' he said.
   Kalejs was denied bond when the deportation charge was filed in
spring 1985, but he was later released on $750,000 bond.
   Kalejs, a citizen of Australia, would have the choice of country
if he is deported, Einhorn said. If a country refused to admit him,
the government would make a recommendation.
   Kalejs owns property in Illinois, St. Petersburg, Fla., and Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., according to the INS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
