<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Fires Three Missiles Into Iran; Iranians Bombard Basra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq today fired missiles into two
Iranian cities, killing or wounding dozens of people, and Iran
shelled the Iraqi city of Basra.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said 15 civilians were
killed in a predawn missile explosion today in a residential
district of Iran's holy city of Qom located 100 miles south of
Tehran.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said dozens more were killed
or wounded in two more missile attacks, one on Qom and the other on
Isfahan, several hours later. It said exact casualty figures were
not immeditely available.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia, said
Iraqi gunners fired two missiles into Qom and one into Isfahan,
capital of the ancient Persian empire, to avenge Iranian attacks on
Iraqi cities.
   Iraq said dozens of civilians were killed or wounded in Iranian
artillery shelling on the southern city of Basra in an attack that
began Monday night and continued into today. No specific casualty
figures were given.
   On Monday, Iran said its artillerymen shelled defensive
positions in the Kurdistan mountains of northeast Iraq, where
Revolutionary Guards have captured a large area around strategic
Lake Darbandikhan in a 3-week-old offensive.
   Iran said guards and Kurdish guerrillas repulsed counterattacks
by two Iraqi brigades in the battle zone, killing or wounding 150
men.
   The Iraqis threatened Monday to level Iran's cities in revenge
for the northern offensive.
</TEXT>
