<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ActivistKilled     04-05 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Activist Killed,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Compromise To Create Second Judgeship in Robeson County</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers agreed to support a second
Superior Court judgeship for racially tense Robeson County,
eliminating the need for a special legislative session sought by
supporters of a slain Indian judicial candidate.
   Monday's agreement came during a three-hour meeting in Lumberton
between Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan, Robeson County legislators and members
of the campaign committee of Julian Pierce, who was killed March 26
in what police called a domestic dispute.
   If approved by the General Assembly in its June session,
Republican Gov. Jim Martin could appoint a new Superior Court judge
from Robeson County.
   Martin said he supported the agreement and pledged he would
appoint a minority, and probably an Indian.
   Pierce's supporters had pressured the governor to call a special
legislative session to amend state law to allow another minority
candidate to run for the present judgeship. Filing for the
judgeship closed in February, and state law does not allow a
replacement for a candidate who dies more than 30 days after the
filing period ends.
   The judgeship was one of nine established last year in areas
with predominantly black or Indian populations in an effort to
increase the number of minority judges.
   Rep. Sidney Locks, a black Robeson County leader who was part of
Monday's negotiations, was unenthusiastic about the compromise.
``But we were trying to find some way to diffuse the kinds of
problems we currently have in Robeson County,'' he said.
   Jordan, one of the state's most powerful Democrats, said the
agreement could help ease racial tensions in Robeson County.
   ``I think it certainly can do wonders, at least for the feelings
they have about the justice system,'' he said.
   The proposal also would virtually assure that Joe Freeman Britt,
Robeson County's district attorney, will be elected Superior Court
judge this fall. Pierce, a Lumbee Indian leader in Robeson County,
was Britt's only opposition for the special judgeship created last
year. Britt is white.
   Also on Monday, about 600 people gathered in the place where
Pierce started his campaign for judge three months ago to pledge to
continue his struggle for change.
   ``We must keep the faith. We must not let tragedy keep us down.
We must press on,'' said the Rev. Ben Chavis.
   Many Lumbees and blacks in the county say they are discriminated
against and that they are not represented adequately in local
political offices. The county's population is 37 percent Indian, 37
percent white and 26 percent black.
   The tension was dramatized Feb. 1, when two armed Tuscarora
Indians burst into The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton and took
at least 17 people hostage. No one was injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
