<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia     04-05 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivor: Hooded Gunmen Killed 33 at Easter Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hooded gunmen in army uniforms
surrounded and fired on about 500 people at an Easter festival in a
village plaza, killing 33 and wounding eight, a survivor said.
   ``The one in charge shouted `Kill everyone you can!''' said the
survivor, Segundo Benitez, in an interview Monday with the
Colombian radio chain Caracol.
   Benitez said he counted the dead and wounded in the Sunday
massacre in the small village of Mejor Esquina in northern
Colombia, 280 miles northwest of Bogota, the capital.
   He said a brother, two nephews and a cousin of his were among
the dead. Benitez said there were 10 to 15 attackers.
   ``They just shot at everybody, at those who were dancing and
those who tried to run away. They made a lot of the people lie down
on the ground and then shot them in the head,'' he said.
   Benitez said men, women, old people and children were among the
victims.
   Right-wing death squads in Colombia often wear hoods and army
uniforms.
   The village of 600, in Cordoba state, was celebrating the end of
Holy Week. Enrique Llorente Lopez, the mayor of the nearby town of
Buenavista, said earlier that about 10 men arrived in vehicles
Sunday night at Mejor Esquina. He had heard that 28 people were
killed.
   Cordoba Gov. Jose Miguel Amin said in a broadcast interview with
Caracol that the police told him they did not know who attacked the
townspeople.
   There are more than a dozen right-wing death squads in Colombia.
   Mejor Esquina is in the heart of a mountainous area where a
left-wing guerrilla group, the People's Liberation Army, has been
organizing lately.
   Sunday's attack was the second massacre in Colombia in a month.
   On March 4, a right-wing death squad fired on sleeping workers
at a ranch in northwest Colombia and killed 20 of them.
   Death squads have killed more than 600 people in Colombia in the
last three years.
</TEXT>
