<HEAD>22 Britons Aboard Hijacked Plane, Says Foreign Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Kuwait-Hijack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-two Britons are among the 96 passengers
aboard a Kuwaiti Airways jet which hijackers threatened to blow up
in Iran, the Foreign Office said today.
   A Foreign Office spokesman said he knew of no special reason why
such a high proportion of the passengers were British.
   The spokesman, who in accordance with British practice spoke on
condition he was not identified, said the British Embassy in Kuwait
has a list of the Britons on board. The Foreign Office, however,
did not release the list.
   The Boeing 747 was hijacked today and forced to land in
northeast Tehran, where the hijackers threatened to blow it up if
Iranian authorities approached at Mashhad airport, Iran's official
Islamic Republic News Agency said.
