<DOCNO> AP880405-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeditionTrial     04-05 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sedition Trial,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates Complicated Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Jury to resume deliberations at 10:30 a.m. CDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal trial of three white
supremacist leaders and six other men accused of plotting to
overthrow the U.S. government through violence has gone to the jury.
   ``It's all in Yahweh's hands,'' Sheila Beam, wife of supremacist
leader Louis Beam Jr., said after the jury began deliberations
Monday. ``If the truth is known, they'll be acquitted.'' Yahweh is
a Hebrew name for God.
   The jury was to resume deliberations today.
   The case involves 13 defendants, nine of whom are charged with
seditious conspiracy, or conspiring to overthrow the government. A
conviction carries a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison.
   In addition, five of the defendants are accused of conspiring to
kill federal officials and two are charged with interstate
transportation of stolen money. The maximum penalty for murder
conspiracy is life in prison. The stiffest punishment for
transporting stolen money is 10 years.
   Five of the defendants are in prison for other crimes.
   In addition to Beam, 41, of Houston, the supremacist leaders are
Robert E. Miles, 63, of Cohoctah, Mich., and Richard G. Butler, 70
of Hayden Lake, Idaho.
   Miles, pastor of the Mountain Church of Jesus Christ, is the
author of a newsletter that attacked Jews and the federal
government. Butler is the founder of the white supremacist group
Aryan Nations.
   Beam is a former Ku Klux Klan recruiter who left the Klan in
1981 and became a representative for the Aryan Nations.
   The government alleged that the defendants agreed to try to
bring down the government by force during an Aryan Nations congress
in 1983.
   The government contended that some of the defendants went on to
commit a series of robberies to finance their activities. The
robberies netted about $4.1 million, of which about $1 million is
unaccounted for, the government said.
   In closing arguments Monday, U.S. Attorney J. Michael Fitzhugh
said Butler, Beam and Miles came up with the idea for overthrowing
the government.
   Fitzhugh said the sedition defendants maintained they hoped to
bring about a white supremacist nation through a peaceful move to
the Pacific Northwest.
   But, he said, if that was the case, why did:
   _Defendant David Lane say in a taped conversation that he needed
to bomb some major telephone facility?
   _Defendant Bruce Pierce become a member of The Order, a violent
group that committed armed robberies, by taking an oath declaring a
``full state of war''?
   _The Covenant, The Sword and The Arm of The Lord _ an
Arkansas-based supremacist group _ collect an arsenal of automatic
weapons, silencers, grenades and other explosives and embark on
robberies, bombings and murders?
   During the trial, the defense attacked the credibility of
government witnesses.
   But Fitzhugh told jurors, ``Plots made in hell don't have angels
as partners.''
   Attorney N.C. Deday LaRene, representing Miles, said in his
closing argument Monday that the government's key witness, James
Ellison, ``had serious delusions.'' Ellison belonged to the
Arkansas group.
   LaRene said Ellison made up the story about a conspiracy hatched
at Hayden Lake because he lost an appeal of his racketeering
conviction and was looking for a way out of prison.
   The defense attorney said that in three earlier reports about
supremacist activities, Ellison never mentioned that alleged
meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
