<HEAD>Hail, Thunderstorms Over Southeast but Fair Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hail the size of golfballs pounded parts of North Carolina as
the state and neighboring Virginia bore the brunt of stormy weather
in a day of mostly mild, springlike conditions across the nation.
   Dry, spring weather was expected today for much of the nation,
along with above-normal temperatures.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended along a cold front over
southeastern Virginia and northeastern North Carolina, where
golfball-sized hail pelted Robersonville and Hertford while
Jamesville was struck by ice the size of half dollars.
   Meanwhile, showers were scattered over Maine, Nebraska and South
Dakota.
   Scattered drizzle and patchy, dense fog blanketed portions of
Michigan, western New York state, northern New England and the
middle Texas coastal areas. A dense fog advisory was in effect over
the Texas coastal bend.
   Rain was forecast for western Washington later tonight, and a
snow advisory was issued for the Cascades and Olympics ranges where
3 to 6 inches of snow was expected.
   Winds subsided across southeast Idaho on Monday night after
earlier wind gusts of up to 50 mph were clocked at Resburg, Idaho
Falls and Pocatello.
   The coldest temperatures were in the northwestern U.S., with
late-night readings mostly in the 20s and 30s across the northern
and central Rockies into the western Dakotas; temperatures were in
the 70s over much of southern Texas, south Florida and the desert
southwest.
   Today's forecast called for abundant sunshine around most of the
nation, except across the Midwest and the Pacific Northwest;
showers and thunderstorms scattered over southern and central
Florida and from the middle Mississippi Valley across Wisconsin and
parts of lower Michigan; rain over eastern South Dakota across
southern Minnesota; scattered showers from eastern North Dakota
into upper Michigan; and rain across western Washington state and
northwest Oregon.
   Highs were expected in the 60s or 70s across much of the nation;
in the 50s over Wyoming and the northern quarter of the U.S; in the
80s over the southern third of the country and over southern
sections of the Ohio valley; in the 90s over portions of the desert
southwest and southwest Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 12
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 76 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 61 fair; Boston 55 foggy; Buffalo 42 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C., 62 fair; Cincinnati 52 fair; Cleveland 47 fair;
Miami 74 cloudy; New York 51 fair; Philadelphia 55 fair; Pittsburgh
50 fair; Portland, Maine, 50 foggy; Washington 60 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 44 cloudy; Chicago 60 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
72 fair; Denver 46 windy; Des Moines 59 fair; Indianapolis 54 fair;
Kansas City 60 partly cloudy; Nashville 55 fair; New Orleans 66
fair; St. Louis 68 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 61 partly cloudy; Anchorage 31 cloudy; Las
Vegas 65 fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 75 fair; Salt Lake City
38 fair; San Diego 60 partly cloudy; San Francisco 50 fair; Seattle
41 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 46 cloudy; Toronto 46 partly cloudy.
