<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     04-05 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Witness: Contractor Tried to Sell to Iran, Iraq and Saudi
Arabia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ex-Wedtech Corp. executive claims the defense
contractor sought help from a Saudi Arabian prince and friends of
Attorney General Edwin Meese 3rd in an attempt to sell military
equipment to Middle Eastern countries.
   But negotiations to sell bridge pontoons and other supplies to
Iran, Iraq and Saudi Arabia eventually fell through, former Wedtech
Vice Chairman Mario Moreno testified Monday.
   Moreno, one of four former Wedtech officials testifying at the
racketeering trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi and six others in exchange
for leniency, was asked about the scandal-plagued company's Middle
East dealings in his 14th day on the witness stand.
   The jury was not present during the questioning and U.S.
District Judge Constance Baker Motley later ruled the topic
inadmissible because, she said, it didn't provide any evidence that
a crime had been committed but would unduly prejudice the jury.
   Biaggi and the six others are charged with turning the
now-bankrupt Wedtech into a racketeering enterprise that paid out
millions of dollars in bribes.
   Once a small machine shop in the Bronx, Wedtech grew into a
multimillion-dollar manufacturer through a program that set aside
federal contracts without competitive bidding for minority-owned
companies.
   Prosecutors allege Biaggi and others helped Wedtech falsely
portray itself as a minority concern eligible for the no-bid
program.
   Moreno denied that Wedtech had acted on behalf of the U.S.
government in the Middle East.
   ``No, we were acting as Wedtech,'' said Moreno, one of four
ex-Wedtech executives to plead guilty to state and federal
corruption charges. ``We believed we could do it legally.''
   ``You knew you could never legally have gotten an export license
(to sell military equipment)?'' asked defense attorney Dominic
Amorosa.
   ``It crossed my mind,'' said Moreno, who did not elaborate.
   Asked if E. Robert Wallach, Meese's close friend and former
business associate, had said he could help obtain export licenses,
Moreno replied, ``It never got to that point.''
   Moreno previously testified that Wedtech paid Wallach $800,000
for his ``influence with Ed Meese.'' Meese has not been accused of
wrongdoing in the case.
   The witness said company officials spoke with Wallach ``on two
or three occasions'' about foreign deals.
   Moreno also said a former Meese financial adviser, W. Franklyn
Chinn, was ``a conduit in trying to sell arms to Iraq.''
   Chinn's lawyer, Cristina Arguedas, when called for comment,
said, ``I've never heard this allegation before, and I continue to
deny that Frank Chinn has engaged in any illegal conduct.''
   Both Wallach and Chinn are under federal indictment, accused of
extracting payoffs from Wedtech for allegedly influencing Meese and
other officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0652EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     04-05 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Calls U.S. Aid Illegal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega called an aid
package the U.S. Congress approved last week for the Contra rebels
illegal.
   His comments came Monday, one day before the third round of
talks between military leaders for the leftist government and the
Contra rebels aimed at working out the technical details of the
60-day cease-fire that began Friday.
   In another development, reports reaching Managua indicated that
some fighting between Sandinistas and Contras has occurred despite
the truce.
   ``We cannot accept any type of aid to the Contras because it
would be legitimizing the interventionist policy of the United
States,'' Ortega told reporters. ``It is illegal because the United
States has no right to decide what type of government Nicaragua
ought to have.''
   Under a 60-day cease-fire agreement signed March 23 in the
southern border town of Sapoa, the Contras agreed to accept only
humanitarian aid from a neutral organization, such as the
International Red Cross.
   The Sandinistas said they would grant freedom of expression and
amnesty to political prisoners and will allow rebel leaders to take
part in national talks. In today's technical talks, also to be held
in Sapoa, Sandinista and Contra representatives will hammer out
technical details of the truce.
   President Reagan on Friday signed the aid package for the rebels
and victims of the fighting that has battered Nicaragua for more
than six years.
   Only $17.7 million of the $48 million package was directed to
the rebels, and the aid package contains no provision for weapons.
   Despite the cease-fire, Radio Liberation, an underground rebel
station, quoted Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros on Monday as
saying that Sandinista troops had been firing on rebels.
   A transcript of the broadcast also quoted Contra leader Adolfo
Calero as saying the Sandinistas continued bombing civilian towns
in the rural north.
   The pro-government newspaper, El Nuevo Diario, reported that
Contra forces attacked a Sandinista army patrol Saturday, killing
two soldiers and injuring three near the town of Condega, about 120
miles north of Managua.
   The Defense Ministry said there were no reports of cease-fire
violations.
   The cease-fire was arranged to give both sides time to work out
a permanent truce in the war, which has killed more than 40,000
people.
   Under the peace plan, the rebels are to gather in cease-fire
zones during the first two weeks of April. Two days of meetings
last week ended with both sides agreeing only to set up five
cease-fire zones. They failed to work out the size of the areas or
security for the Contras.
   The peace agreement does not mention disarming the rebels, and
the Contras claim they will never surrender their weapons.
   The Sandinistas met the first step of the agreement by releasing
100 political prisoners March 27. The remaining 3,300 political
prisoners are to be released gradually as the terms of the pact are
met.
   The Contras charge the Sandinistas only released 10 political
prisoners that they requested. They say the others served only a
few weeks or were common criminals.
   The Sandinistas came to power in a revolution that ousted the
late President Anastasio Somoza in July 1979. The United States
supported the Sandinistas initially, but in 1981 began financing
the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
