<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz-Egypt     04-05 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Egypt,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egyptian Paper Criticizes Palestinian Leaders For Boycotting
Shultz</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading government-owned newspaper today
criticized Palestinian leaders in the Israeli-occupied territories
for boycotting Secretary of State George P. Shultz's efforts for
Middle East peace.
   ``We would have preferred if they (Palestinian leaders) revised
their continued boycott and tried to give a chance for a dialogue
with the American side,'' an editorial in the daily Al-Akhbar said.
   The newspaper said Shultz began talks with Palestinians last
month when he met in Washington with American professors Edward
Said and Ibrahim Abu Lughud, who belong to the legislative arm of
the Palestine Liberation Organization movement to establish a
Palestinian state on Israeli territory.
   It said Shultz's shuttle visits ``to the parties of the
Arab-Israeli conflict (are) ... indications of the seriousness of
(President) Reagan's administration to reach a final settlemenmt of
the region's problem.''
   ``It is true that the American initiative does not meet all the
desires of the Arab side in general and the Palestinians in
particular, but this does not mean it is devoid of any positive
elements that could be built on and promoted during the dialogue,''
the newspaper said.
   It said the initiative has for the first time recognized the
right of the Palestinians for self-rule and called this a ``turning
point in Washington's policy.''
   The U.S. plan calls for three years of self-rule, but not
statehood, for the 1.5 million Palestinians living in the occupied
territories. Negotiations on an overall settlement would open in
December.
   Israel captured the Gaza Strip from Egypt and the West Bank from
Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war. For the last four months
anti-occupation rioting by Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip has killed more than 135 Arabs.
</TEXT>
