<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     04-05 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hereafter Laugher `Beetlejuice' Marches Ahead of `Biloxi Blues'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Keaton's portrayal of a manic ghost in
``Beetlejuice'' had enough magic to take the top box office
position from ``Biloxi Blues,'' while ``Bright Lights, Big City''
took third place.
   The Easter weekend box office take was also a spring bonanza for
studios suffering through the winter moviegoing doldrums.
``Beetlejuice'' rung in more than $8 million for the No. 1 position.
   In doing so, it knocked ``Biloxi Blues,'' Neil Simon's nostalgic
look at 1945 Army life, down a notch. The Simon yarn, starring
Matthew Broderick as a boot camp private, made its debut at No.1 a
week earlier. Its $6 million take put it in second place.
   In third was ``Bright Lights, Big City,'' starring wholesome
``Family Ties'' TV star Michael J. Fox as a pathetic drug user in a
self-destructive relationship with a young model. It raked in $5
million in its first week of release.
   Movies geared toward youngsters made the best showing because of
the Easter week vacation from school, giving box offices a needed
boost after a lackluster winter season.
   ``It was a good overall gross, and `Beetlejuice' enjoyed the
biggest opening of the year, benefiting of course from the spring
break,'' said John Krier of Exhibitor Relations Co., which tracks
studio box office performance.
   The Disney studios, leading the box office derby for months with
the blockbuster hits ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' and ``Three Men and
a Baby,'' snagged three spots in the Top 10 this week.
   The studio's reissue of ``The Fox And The Hound'' took in $4
million for a two-week gross of almost $12 million and the No. 4
spot in the turnstile race.
   The frightful coming of the Apocalypse in ``The Seventh Sign,''
starring Demi Moore, was fifth with $3.76 million, and the college
football recruiting farce ``Johnny Be Good'' was sixth with $2.9
million.
   Moviegoers shelled out $2.8 million to catch Robin William's
Oscar-nominated performance as an irreverent Saigon disc jockey in
``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' putting it in seventh place.
   ``Police Academy 5: Assignment Miami Beach'' was eighth with a
$2.2 million take, ``A New Life'' was ninth with $1.5 million and
Disney's ``D.O.A.'' was 10th with $1.4 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Beetlejuice,'' Warner Bros., $8.03 million, 1,000 screens,
$3,030 per screen, $10.45 million, one week (released Wednesday),
n-a.
   2. ``Biloxi Blues,'' Universal, $6.01 million, 1,329 screens,
$4,525 per screen, $16.37 million, two weeks, $16 million.
   3. ``Bright Lights, Big City,'' MGM-UA, $5.12 million, 1,196
screens, $4,286 per screen, $5.12 million, n-a.
   4. ``The Fox And The Hound,'' Disney, $4.01 million, 1,567
screens, $2,561 per screen, $11.49 million, two weeks (re-release),
$4.8 million.
   5. ``The Seventh Sign,'' Tristar, $3.76 million, 1,256 screens,
$3,000 per screen, $3.76 million, one week, n-a.
   6. ``Johnny Be Good,'' Orion, $2.94 million, 1,194 screens,
$2,440 per screen, $10.26 million, two weeks, $8 million.
   7. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney, $2.80 million, 1,412
screens, $1,986 per screen, $105.38 million, 15 weeks, $21 million.
   8. ``Police Academy 5: Assignment Miami Beach,'' Warner Bros.,
$2.29 million, 1,633 screens, $1,404 per screen, $14.82 million,
three weeks, $9 million.
   9. ``A New Life,'' Paramount, $1.57 million, 796 screens, $1,982
per screen, $5.05 million, two weeks, $18 million.
   10. ``D.O.A.,'' Disney, $1.44 million, 869 screens, $1,661 per
screen, $10.02 million, three weeks, $12 million.
