<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     04-05 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Jews,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Emigration At Seven-Year High In March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities allowed 944 Jews to emigrate
last month, the highest monthly figure since July 1981, a
resettlement agency said today.
   It was the second straight monthly increase in emigration, the
Intergovernmental Committee for Migration reported. The agency said
723 Jews left the Soviet Union in February and 658 emigrated in
January.
   Last year, 8,011 Jews were allowed to leave the Soviet Union,
the highest number since 1981. There were only 943 such emigres in
1986.
   In March, 176 of the Soviet Jews arriving at a transit center in
Vienna, Austria, went to Israel, agency spokeswoman Regina Boucault
said.
   Recent emigration has remained far below the resettlement
program's peak in 1979, when 51,330 Jews were allowed to leave the
Soviet Union.
   More than 250,000 Jews have emigrated since the program began in
1971. In the early years, most emigres went to Israel. Recently,
most emigres have chosen to settle elsewhere.
</TEXT>
