<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Florida-Taxes     04-05 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida-Taxes,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wary Florida Lawmakers Say They Won't Talk Taxes This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burnt by a controversial services tax
last year, state lawmakers and Gov. Bob Martinez say they won't be
talking taxes during the 1988 legislative session opening today.
   Martinez came under heavy fire for his original support and
later flip-flop on the services tax, which would have raised $1
billion by taxing lawyers, lawn care, accounting and other
services. The unusual 5 percent levy was repealed in December after
much argument.
   The controversy was fueled by the state's plan to tax services
such as advertising across state lines. Publishers, broadcasters
and the hotel industry raised an outcry, and many groups threatened
to cancel Florida conventions before Martinez backed off and pushed
for alternatives.
   ``It'll be very helpful to talk about problems and not have that
all-consuming issue,'' Martinez said Monday.
   The first-term Republican won't have to look far for other
concerns. Shackled by budget and political restraints, Florida's
leaders face overcrowded prisons, congested highways and schools,
and an environment buckling under the pressure of 1,000 new
residents each day.
   ``It will be a real competition for funds this year,'' said
Education Commissioner Betty Castor, who wants nearly $1 billion in
additional appropriations to meet her department's needs in the
face of 67,000 new students in 1988-89.
   The state relies heavily on its sales tax on goods, which the
Legislature increased by one percentage point to 6 percent after it
repealed the services tax.
   Martinez said he hasn't found any of his GOP colleagues or
conservative Democrats in favor of new taxes this year.
   ``Maybe it's one of those situations where it's going to have to
get a lot worse before it gets better,'' Senate President John
Vogt, a Democrat, said Monday at the Florida TaxWatch annual
meeting. Vogt said his travels around the state have convinced him
that citizens don't want new taxes regardless of the ramifications
of not raising more revenue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
