<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Legislator Opposed To Sikh Militants Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sikh militants today killed a
senior member of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's Congress Party in
northern India after he organized protests against Sikh violence,
the United News of India reported.
   The news agency said Vilayati Ram Katyal and his bodyguard were
killed by three suspected Sikh militants in the town of Kanpur, 235
miles southeast of New Delhi. Katyal, 53, was a member of the Uttar
Pradesh state legislature.
   UNI said he was targeted by the militants for organizing a
strike in Kanpur to protest of killings in nearby Punjab state,
where the militants are most active.
   In Punjab, three Sikhs were killed in separate attacks Monday
night, UNI said. The killings raise to 659 the number of people
killed in Punjab this year in the Sikh guerrilla war for a separate
homeland. Most of the victims have been moderate Hindus or Sikhs
opposed to demands for a separate Sikh state.
   The Kanpur attack was the first by Sikh gunmen outside Punjab
state this year. Last year, 29 people were killed in New Delhi in
attacks blamed on the militants.
   Sikhs form just 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are
in a majority in Punjab. Sikh militants have been fighting for a
separate state since 1983, claiming discrimination by the majority
Hindu community, which forms 80 percent of the population.
