<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0733EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PosnerSentence     04-05 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Posner Sentence,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legality Of Millionaire's Tax-Fraud Sentence Challenged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MILT SOSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors have challenged the legality of
millionaire Victor Posner's sentence on tax-fraud charges, which
involves a $3 million contribution to the homeless instead of a
prison term.
   ``Laudable as the project envisioned by this court may be, we
submit it would disserve and cause disrespect for our system of
justice, and only emphasize that the rich can trade money for
liberty while the poor cannot,'' U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner said in
a motion filed Monday.
   ``Sadly, we are compelled to observe that this sentence is
illegal,'' the prosecutor said of the unusual punishment imposed
Feb. 12 by U.S. District Judge Eugene Spellman. ``The law does not
allow an exchange of money for jail time even for the benefit of a
badly needed societal purpose.''
   Spellman said Monday he would have no comment on the motion and
was awaiting a response by Posner's attorneys.
   After Posner pleaded no contest to 10 tax fraud counts for
inflating the value of land donated to Miami Christian College,
Spellman ordered the industrialist to perform a $3 million project
to aid the homeless in south Florida and to pay $4 million in back
taxes, penalties and interest.
   Spellman, who also ruled Posner could not take a tax deduction
for the donation to the homeless and could not file for voluntary
bankruptcy, acknowledged when he imposed the sentence that its
legality might be questioned.
   ``If for some reason (the sentence) is ever challenged, this
court will, in fact, incarcerate Victor Posner,'' he said in
February.
   Kellner's five-page motion noted that Spellman said Posner would
go to prison if any of the sentencing conditions were violated but
``did not indicate what (the) sentence would otherwise have been.''
   In his motion, Kellner said he was ``duty-bound to call to this
court's attention the fact that this court does not have the power
to order a criminal defendant to make charitable contributions as a
condition of probation.''
   A hearing on Posner's plan for distribution of the $3 million
was set for Wednesday before Spellman.
</TEXT>
