<HEAD>Soldier Gets 3{ Years For Meeting PLO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli army soldier who met with the PLO in
Europe was sentenced to 3{ years in prison for desertion and
assisting the enemy, a military official said today.
   A military tribunal found the soldier had not harmed Israel's
security, the official said. But the court saw the soldier's
contacts with the PLO as ``very grave'' and therefore sentenced him
to five years, 1{ years of which were suspended.
   Israel views the Palestine Liberation Organization as a
terrorist group. The maximum sentence in Israel for assisting the
enemy is 25 years.
   The soldier, whose name and rank were kept secret, deserted last
summer and went to Cyprus and then Europe, where he initiated
contacts with a member of Fatah, the main wing of the PLO headed by
Yasser Arafat, the military official said.
   The soldier later cut off contacts with the group, Israel army
radio said. He was missing from Israel for 42 days, the Haaretz
newspaper said.
   The soldier appealed his conviction to a military appeals court
but was denied, the military official said.
