<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Inland     04-05 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Inland,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inland Delegates Object To Favoring Coastal Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of China's inland provinces indicated
today they are scrambling for development strategies of their own
now that the central government's emphasis is on building up the
coastal areas.
   Delegates from one western region suggested the first joint
ventures in China with the Soviet Union since a bitter 1960
political split.
   ``If the coastal policies are only looking to exports, how are
we in the west going to modernize?'' wondered Huang Baozhang, vice
chairman of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, at a meeting of
the region's delegates to the National People's Congress.
   The congress, China's legislature, began a 20-day annual session
March 25. Foreign reporters were allowed today for the second time
to sit in on delegate discussion groups in the Great Hall of the
People.
   Many inland officials oppose the state's new strategy of
developing the coast into an export-producing center, fearing their
already backward regions will stay mired in poverty while the coast
becomes rich.
   However, coastal development is a pet project of Communist Party
chief Zhao Ziyang.
   Huang said his solution for Xinjiang was to increase inland
trade across the border with the Soviet Union, making Xinjiang into
an export center of its own.
   Xinjiang's chairman, Tomur Dawamat, invited the Soviets to enter
into joint ventures in his region. The Soviets have not had joint
ventures in China since the 1960 political split between the two
Communist giants. Moscow then called home thousands of technicians
and industrial experts who had been helping rebuild China's economy
from the devastation of World War II.
   Although political differences remain strong, China and the
Soviet Union have concluded several trade agreements in recent
years, and an unofficial cross-border trade flourishes in Xinjiang
and other remote regions. Last month, the two countries announced
plans to turn a hotel in Moscow into a joint venture.
   ``We and the Soviet people have the same hope, although we have
great political differences,'' Huang said. ``The people of both
countries hope to carry out many economic exchanges. We need some
Soviet products and they need some of ours. Both nations could
benefit.''
   Delegates from Heilongjiang province, which borders the Soviet
Union in northeast China, pressed similar proposals and won support
from Zheng Tuobin, minister of foreign economic relations and trade.
   The state-run Xinhua News Agency quoted Zheng as saying trade
with the Soviet Union and other East bloc countries will increase
rapidly, and that provinces will be allowed to make some trade
arrangements directly without going through the central government.
</TEXT>
