<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FriedlandTrial     04-05 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Friedland Trial,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Files Motion To Supress Evidence In Friedland Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for a former state senator claimed
he was suffering from the effects of being drugged and tortured
when he made statements to authorities on his return to this
country from foreign custody.
   David Friedland, who disappeared just before he was to go to
prison on a kickback conviction and spent two years on the lam, was
treated so badly by authorities in the Maldive Islands that he
began hallucinating the night before he was turned over to U.S.
officials, the attorneys say.
   ``Mr. Friedland hallucinated that the prophet Mohammed told him
to convert and he would be released,'' said a motion filed by the
lawyers last week.
   The motion, filed Thursday before Chief U.S. District Judge John
F. Gerry, seeks to suppress statements Friedland made to U.S.
agents en route from the Indian Ocean islands to the United States
in December 1987.
   Friedland does not remember being read his rights or waiving his
rights to an attorney during the flight, the motion said. It also
said the U.S. agents manipulated Friedland to obtain the statements.
   Defense attorneys also filed motions last week to dismiss 35 of
the 90 counts in a federal indictment charging Friedland with
masterminding a $20 million swindle of a pension fund.
   Friedland, 50, is scheduled to go on trial Sept. 7 on charges he
set up a bogus mortgage company in Florida to bilk the pension fund
of Teamsters Local 701 in North Brunswick.
   Court documents do not indicate the nature of the statements
Friedland allegedly made to U.S. Deputy Marshal Blair Deem and
Special Agent Thomas G. Sommero during the flight.
   First Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Chertoff declined comment
on the statements Monday but said they may be made public during a
May 13 pretrial hearing before Gerry.
   Friedland faked his death in a bogus scuba-diving accident in
September 1985, weeks before he was to be sentenced for a 1980
kickback conviction involving the same pension fund. An indictment
alleges Friedland, a disbarred attorney, engineered the second scam
while working as a government informant.
   In 26 months on the lam, Friedland traveled through Europe, Asia
and Africa before settling in the Maldives, where he ran a
scuba-diving business for 18 months using an alias.
   By the time he was placed in the custody of that country's
National Security Force on Dec. 12, Friedland had been named the
most wanted fugitive by the U.S. Marshal's office.
   While in foreign custody, Friedland was kept in a room with a
board for a mattress and an overflowing toilet, fed spoiled food,
injected with drugs and beaten when he tried to sleep, his
attorneys say.
   Officials there also gave him daily injections of Talacen, a
mild narcotic, and Valium, an anti-anxiety drug, laced his tea with
hallucinogenics, and gave him other drugs, the motion said.
   After 12 days in custody, ``due to complete lack of sleep,
substantial drug consumption, exhaustion and pain, Mr. Friedland
was mentally and physically exhausted,'' the motion said.
   While in this condition, Friedland was handed over to the U.S.
agents who escorted him back to the United States.
   Defense attorneys Peter Willis and John Yacovelle did not return
calls Monday.
   Attempts to contact Maldiven officials were unsuccessful. Calls
to the Maldiven consulate in New York were not returned.
   Friedland faces a maximum sentence of seven years in prison for
his disappearance and up to 150 years in prison if convicted of
charges stemming from the second pension fund case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
