<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Carter-Hostages     04-05 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carter-Hostages,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter Says He Never Heard of Plan to Swap Military Parts for
Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter says he never
heard of a plan to swap military parts for the 52 Americans held
hostage in Iran during the last year of his term.
   ``No one that I have talked to had heard of it,'' he added at a
news conference Monday night following a speech at Fresno State
University.
   Newly declassified documents revealed in a House Judiciary
subcommittee investigation showed the Carter administration
considered offering $10 million in military spare parts to Iran for
the hostages captured in November 1979 during an attack on the U.S.
Embassy in Tehran.
   Carter advisers scuttled the plan after determining arms dealer
Houshang Lavi didn't have the backing of then-Iranian president
Abolhassan Bani-Sadr, according to documents obtained by the Miami
Herald.
   One CIA memo said Lavi offered to make a hostage exchange and
handed over a seven-page list of F-14 parts. The CIA officer who
wrote the memo recommended against pursuing the deal.
   Carter said he never saw any of the memos and that the plan was
``never seriously considered.''
   The documents include CIA memos to Carter's National Security
Council chief David Aaron and State Department memos by then-Deputy
Assistant Secretary Harold Saunders.
   The papers surfaced during a hearing being held by Rep. John
Coyers, D-Mich., into attempts by the Reagan administration to
trade arms with Iran for hostages seized by Iran-backed Shiite
Moslems in Lebanon.
   During his speech, Carter said the United States doesn't always
use its power as it should to promote human rights.
   ``When there is a silence from Washington, there is a worldwide
silence,'' he said. ``What the oppressed fear most is a silence
from Washington.''
   Carter, whose policy as president was to publicly criticize
nations that abused human rights, told the crowd that the Reagan
administration has been ``on the wrong side of human rights issues
in almost every case.''
   He urged that the next president develop a foreign policy that
would ``alleviate suffering by the use of American influence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
