<2ND_LINE>PM-Austria-Hikers,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Teen-Agers Killed on Austrian Peak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two English teen-agers clung to bushes
while four hiking companions slid and fell hundreds of feet to
their deaths on a snowy Alpine mountain, police said today.
   The four died Monday after the group strayed off a hiking trail
for horseplay on the side of the 6,500-foot peak near Salzburg,
according to police.
   The six hikers left Untersberg on Monday on a set path but
wandered off to slide on the snow, according to air rescue official
Norbert Huber.
   Four of them lost control, dropped 330 feet into a gully, and
then fell over a rocky cliff, said Salzburg police spokesman Alois
Wintersteller.
   Authorities identified the victims as Andrew Powell-Lee, 15;
Andrew Watts, 14; Michael Taylor, 13; and Daniel Howton, 14.
   The survivors were identified as Thomas Plumridge, 14; and
Richard Davis, 15.
   The group came to Austria with other pupils of Altwood Church of
England school at Maidenhead, west of London.
   The Austria Press Agency said the group was likely to leave
Austria for home today, abandoning earlier plans to travel on to
Switzerland from Salzburg.
</TEXT>
