<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangViolence     04-05 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Supports Whatever Action Needed to `Take Back Streets'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officers shot to death a man they said was a
suspect in a gang-related drive-by killing and two men were wounded
in still another drive-by incident as violent gang confrontations
continued, police said.
   Monday's fatal shooting took place on the same day Police Chief
Darryl Gates unveiled plans to have 1,000 officers work four hours
of overtime each to fight gang warfare, and Mayor Tom Bradley said
he would support whatever measures are needed to take back control
of the city's streets.
   Police said a 19-year-old man, whose name was withheld pending
notification of relatives, was shot to death when he allegedly
reached for his waistband as two officers attempted to take him
into custody.
   The officers believed the man was reaching for a handgun, but no
gun was found, Lt. William Hall, who heads the Police Department's
officer-involved shooting unit, said Monday. He would not say if
Officers Harold Moberly, 33, and Larry Maillet, 31, were under
investigation.
   Police said the man was suspected of participating in a drive-by
shooting earlier Monday in which a 27-year-old man, whose name also
was withheld, was killed by a shotgun blast while standing with a
group of people on the city's gang-ridden southwest side.
   Gennaire Harris, 19, who was with the man killed by the
officers, was arrested for investigation of murder, Hall said.
   Two other young men were listed in stable condition at area
hospitals today after being shot Monday night in another
gang-related drive-by shooting, police said. The gunmen escaped.
   Meanwhile, the Police Department will ask for $150,000 to
$200,000 from the City Council this week to pay for overtime
salaries, Gates said at a news conference Monday.
   ``We are determined to take back the streets of Los Angeles and
restore them to the decent, law-abiding citizens of this
community,'' Bradley said in support. ``Whatever that takes, I am
prepared to back the Police Department and the chief of police in
that effort.''
   Gang violence has long been a problem, but a drive-by shooting
on Good Friday that killed one person and wounded a dozen,
including a 4-year-old boy, triggered new calls for action.
   The assault may have been the city's worst in terms of the
number of victims, police said. Five people were killed and five
others injured in a gang shooting outside a home in October 1984.
   A police task force converged on gang areas Saturday night and
early Sunday, arresting 175 people for investigation of a variety
of alleged offenses and interrogating 619 people, 500 of them
believed to be gang members.
   In nine sweeps since February, 1,203 people have been arrested,
of which 996 were gang members, Gates said.
   Gates declined to say which day the expanded force would be
deployed, saying he didn't want to tip his hand to the gangs.
   ``We'll do it long enough that they get the message,'' Gates
said.
   Gates also proposed the use of wiretaps against gangs, which
Bradley said he supported.
   Gates said he did not believe the city needed the National
Guard's help now, but he added, ``maybe sometime down the road it
will become necessary.'' Los Angeles County Supervisor Kenneth Hahn
has called on Gov. George Deukmejian to dispatch the Guard.
   In a separate move, the mayor Monday also proposed a plan for
spending $2.8 million to hire unarmed rangers and improve
facilities at 66 parks, mostly in the inner city, where gangs have
forced out park users.
</TEXT>
