<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Moses     04-05 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Moses,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newborn Baby Rescued From Bag on South African River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWCASTLE, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fisherman rescued a newborn
from a plastic trash bag floating on a river after hearing the baby
crying, police said today.
   The baby, whom police called ``Moses,'' was wrapped in newspaper
with his umbilical cord still attached when he was found Monday,
according to police.
   He was in satisfactory condition today at Newcastle hospital
about 180 miles southeast of Johannesburg.
   The air in the sealed bag had kept it afloat and saved the life
of the baby, born about an hour before it was rescued, according to
police Lt. Pieter van Straaten.
   Officials said the child had a light complexion, brown hair, and
could be Indian or mixed-race.
   Jan Bekker, 27, and Anton Venter, 19, were fishing on the shore
of the Ncandu River on the outskirts of Newcastle when they saw the
trash bag floating downstream. They heard cries but thought at
first they came from the opposite bank, the South African Press
Association reported.
   When the bag got stuck in reeds near shore about 30 yards from
the fishermen, they realized the cries were coming from inside, the
news agency said.
   Venter, a bank clerk with an artificial leg, took off his
clothes and swam across the swiftly flowing river, opened the bag
and found the baby, van Straaten said.
   The news agency said Venter tied off the umbilical cord with
catgut and cut it. The two men then rushed the child to the
hospital.
   The agency quoted police as saying the baby could have been
dropped into the river from a bridge along the main
Johannesburg-Newcastle Highway.
</TEXT>
