<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomeShooting     04-05 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Home Shooting,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Charged With Murder in Killing of Man Outside His
Bedroom Window</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old high school student who
shot through a window and killed a man he thought was breaking into
his bedroom has been charged with murder.
   James Ronald Sutton remained in Spartanburg County Jail for the
second night Monday without bond. City authorities had recommended
a low bond, but a circuit judge was not in town Monday to set bond,
as required in a murder charge.
   Sutton, a 10th grader at Spartanburg High School with no
previous record, called police late Sunday night to report he had
shot a man he believed was trying to break into his house,
Spartanburg Police Lt. Charles Wolfe said.
   Sutton told police a man came to the house while he was asleep
and rang the doorbell for about four minutes at 11:40 p.m., but the
youth did not answer, Wolfe said.
   A short time later, Sutton told police he heard the screen being
taken off his bedroom window. He then loaded a 20-gauge shotgun,
looked through the window and saw someone, Wolfe said.
   Sutton then sat on the bed and fired a shot through the window,
Wolfe said.
   ``He said he was very afraid,'' the officer said.
   Coroner Jim Burnett identified the dead man as Freddie Edward
Dawkins Jr., 22, of Spartanburg. Dawkins, who was unarmed, was shot
once through the neck, Burnett said.
   Police records showed Dawkins had several prior convictions and
a charge of common law robbery filed in October was pending when he
was killed.
   Sutton's arrest angered his mother, Irene Jones, who said
Monday: ``I feel they shouldn't have arrested him like that and
charged him with murder. He was frightened. He was afraid in his
bedroom.''
   She said the charges against her son contrasted with the
treatment given an 11-year-old youth in Switzer, 10 miles south of
Spartanburg, who shot and killed two intruders in the family home
last month. Officials in that case didn't charge the youth.
   Wolfe wouldn't comment on the Switzer case except to say the
intruders in that case were inside the home.
   ``We charged him (Sutton) for technical reasons,'' Wolfe said.
``Any time a life is taken, the normal procedure is to charge
somebody, even if it's a police officer who did the shooting.''
   Wolfe said the action would allow the courts to clear the youth
of any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
