<2ND_LINE>PM-Honesty Pays,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Finds $10,400 in Bag, Accepts $100 Reward, Reluctantly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A machinist with three children in college found
and returned a bag containing $10,400 in cash and checks and
accepted a $100 reward only with great reluctance.
   ``It was a miracle that Joe Washko happened along,'' said Larry
Hyzer, a manager of Southgate Auto Parts. One of the store's
workers, Bill Sovia, lost the satchel Thursday en route to a bank.
   ``Not many people would have done what he did,'' Hyzer said.
``He wouldn't even take $100 until I begged him to.''
   Washko, 55, of the Detroit suburb of Lincoln Park, said he saw
the pouch on his way to a store and thought it was a child's school
bag.
   ``It was something seeing all those hundreds and fifties, but
there was never any question in my mind on what to do with it,'' he
said. Washko identified the owner through checks in the bag.
   Washko said he would put the reward toward his children's
educations.
   ``The look on the manager's face made my family and me feel
pretty wonderful,'' he said. ``We knew he had a rough afternoon.''
