<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Secrets     04-05 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Secrets,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Art Dealer Held on Spying Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court today ordered a 43-year-old art dealer
held on espionage charges after a prosecutor said he was caught
contacting a foreign power on radio equipment in his north London
apartment.
   Erwin van Haarlem, who has a Dutch passport but says he is
Czechoslovak, was ordered held until his next court appearance May
3 after the brief hearing under tight security at Bow Street
Magistrate's Court.
   Van Haarlem was charged under section seven of Britain's
Official Secrets Act, which deals with the prosecution of people
suspected of preparing to set up a spying operation.
   The allegation was that he ``recorded and ciphered information
and was in possession of equipment to decipher that information,''
police said. No further details were given.
   Prosecutor Michael Bibby said van Haarlem was arrested while
``making direct contact with a foreign power and that transmitting
equipment was found in his possession.''
   Police, after keeping watch on the apartment, arrested van
Haarlem on Saturday. They removed boxes and bags of files and other
materials from the apartment where he lived alone.
   British press reports said van Haarlem was suspected of being a
Czechoslovak secret agent working for the Soviet Union.
   London's Daily Express said Monday that van Haarlem was
suspected of being part of a Soviet-run international spy ring
seeking secrets of underwater weapons development and submarines,
in which Britain is a world leader.
   The Daily Express said the Soviets wanted to know how NATO
tracked Soviet submarines heading into the Atlantic Ocean from
their base at Kola near Murmansk on the Barents Sea.
   Marconi, a British electronics company, plays a major role in
the development of submarine technology.
   In court, the prosecutor told magistrate Ronald Bartle that van
Haarlem claimed to be Czechoslovak despite having a Dutch passport,
and police said his nationality was ``not absolutely clear.''
   Van Haarlem sat impassively during the three-minute hearing. He
was not asked to plead and did not seek bail.
   British newspapers reported that MI5, Britain's counterespionage
secret service, ordered van Haarlem's arrest after investigating
more than six months, including by plainclothes police.
   Neighbors said a team of five men and a woman had occupied an
apartment overlooking van Haarlem's for more than six months and
had been seen carrying in what looked like electronic equipment.
   The Times daily newspaper today quoted two former high-ranking
Czechoslovak officials who have defected to the West as saying that
improved diplomatic relations had enabled Czechoslovaks spying for
the Soviet Union to penetrate high-level British circles.
   The report quoted former Czechoslovak News Agency head Antonin
Buzek and Josef Frolik, a former major in the Czechoslovak secret
police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
