<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Simon     04-05 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Simon,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Future Hinges on Wisconsin Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois said today he will
look at the Wisconsin primary results and decide whether to
continue his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Simon aides said many options already have been discussed,
including suspending the campaign rather than quitting in order to
hold onto the national convention delegate he has won.
   ``We're going to do well tonight. If we don't do well, we have
to make a re-evaluation,'' Simon told reporters outside an
unemployment office in downtown Milwaukee. ``We'll take one step at
a time.''
   Pre-primary polls put Simon a distant fourth in the Democratic
primary race here, where Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and
Jesse Jackson were the front-runners. Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee is in third place in the polls.
   Simon spokesman Terry Michael said that Simon would have no
statement on the Wisconsin results tonight or Wednesday. If Simon
makes a statement on his campaign, it will come on Thursday,
Michael said.
   The Chicago Sun-Times reports in today's editions that Simon
would suspend his campaign, but not withdraw, in order to hold onto
his delegates. A key to such a decision would be the 47 at-large
delegates Simon has won in the state, but which will not be
selected until the state convention in May.
   If Simon withdraws before the convention, Jackson, the
second-place finisher in Illinois, would win all 60 at-large
delegates, not just the 13 he is currently allocated.
   ``Anybody can see that's an option,'' said Michael, even as he
firmly denied it was the course Simon had chosen to take.
   Simon has won only one contest, his homestate primary on March
15. He skipped the Super Tuesday primaries to focus on Illinois and
then said he would make a major effort in Wisconsin to revive his
campaign.
   But Simon failed to catch on in Wisconsin, although he has
campaigned hard around the state. His aides talked privately only
of coming in third, ahead of Gore, a finish far short of anything
strong enough to keep Simon in the race.
</TEXT>
