<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PowerFluctuation 1stLd-Writethru a0603 04-05 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Power Fluctuation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Fluctuation Affects Four States
^Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th, `Dennis Eyre ...,' with added
comment.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power fluctuation dimmed lights in
Colorado, Wyoming, Montana and parts of South Dakota and was blamed
for a radioactive gas leak at a Colorado electric plant.
   Mark Severts, spokesman for Public Service Co. of Colorado in
Denver, said the radiation leak Monday posed no danger to the
public or plant workers.
   Severts said 0.3 curies, or less than one-thousandth of the
concentration PSC is authorized to release on a scheduled basis,
was released at Fort St. Vrain Nuclear Generating Station near
Platteville as a result of the power disturbance.
   ``It's no big deal,'' he said, adding that PSC notified the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission and the state Health Department as
required.
   PSC temporarily closed the plant, as well as one of two
generating units at its Comanche plant near Pueblo.
   Dennis Eyre, administration manager for the Western Systems
Coordinating Council, said utility employees in the affected states
were working to discover the cause.
   ``There was a power system component malfunction'' that caused
electricity to be shifted from one line to another line, he said.
That in turn triggered the fluctuation, which he said lasted ``a
few seconds.''
   He said power went out completely for a brief period in portions
of Wyoming, but in most of the affected area power levels were only
reduced.
   In Wyoming, Rick Kaysen, customer service manager for Cheyenne
Light, Fuel and Power Co., said he had not heard of any major
difficulties related to the fluctuation.
   ``I thought someone was playing with the lights,'' he said.
</TEXT>
