<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingChecks     04-05 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Checks,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly 6,000 Social Security Checks Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every pensioner's nightmare is unfolding
here for nearly 6,000 Social Security recipients _ the Postal
Service has lost or mislaid their checks.
   ``These checks could be sitting in any number of post offices
around the country,'' said Bruce Sanders, manager of quality
control for the Postal Service in Kansas City, Mo.
   Checks totaling at least $3 million were delivered from the U.S.
Treasury's regional financial center in Kansas City, Kan., to the
main post office in Kansas City, Mo., according to Jack Adams,
director of the regional center.
   The checks for 5,800 to 5,900 residents of southwest Indiana
were to be sent by plane to Louisville, Ky., and then trucked to
Evansville. But they never made it to Kentucky and are no longer in
Kansas City, Sanders said Monday.
   The checks were placed in eight trays presorted by zip codes,
Adams said, declining to speculate how the trays were lost.
   ``I'm always amazed, so I don't even try to guess,'' he said.
   The Social Security Administration allows the Postal Service
three mailing days before acting to replace missing checks in such
cases, said Phyllis France, district manager of the Evansville
Social Security office. The three-day limit ends Wednesday, and
reissued checks would take 10 days to deliver.
   Isadore Goldblatt, 74, said there had been no interruption in
the delivery of his bills.
   ``I'm hurting,'' he said. ``That's really the only income I
have.''
</TEXT>
