<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MoundsvilleEscape 1stLd-Writethru a0516 04-05 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moundsville Escape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0516,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Searching For Three Escaped Killers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with corrections official saying
no leads, men probably far away by now, picking up 2nd graf pvs,
`Police immediately ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOUNDSVILLE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three convicted killers who escaped
from the West Virginia Pententiary are ``probably several states
away by now,'' a state prison official said today.
   ``There's been no news on them, whatsover,'' said Corrections
Commissioner A.V. Dodrill. ``We're not searching any areas around
the prison.
   ``Information has been given to other police agencies in the
area, and they are checking that out. What it boils down to is
routine police work.''
   Authorities in Ohio and Pennsylvania also reported no trace of
the three, who broke through an elevator shaft and used bolt
cutters to escape Sunday night.
   Police immediately gave protection to those who helped convict
one of the three, Bobby Stacy, including a Columbus, Ohio, woman
who testified against him. The woman, a former friend of Stacy's,
received death threats and her car was burned during his trial.
   Stacy, 35, was convicted of killing a police officer and accused
of shooting another. Authorities say he had vowed to kill the
prosecutor and circuit judge who had put him behind bars.
   ``He is educated and cold-blooded. That's the worst combination
there is,'' said Charles Hatcher, an assistant Cabell County
prosecutor and one of those Stacy threatened to kill. ``My fear is
that some police officer is going to get killed, because that's
this guy's method.''
   Hatcher said he had no plans to ask for protection for himself,
but Cabell County Circuit Judge Alfred E. Ferguson asked that an
extra bailiff be assigned to him.
   Stacy, David Williams, 28, and Tommie Mollohan, 45, were
discovered missing from the maximum-security prison during a
routine check Sunday night, officials said.
   State police searched West Virginia, Ohio and Pennsylvania for
the three, and roadblocks were set up on routes leading into Ohio
and Pennsylvania, which borders Marshall County, where the prison
is, to the east.
   Mollohan was convicted of robbing and then killing a Brounland
grocer in 1973 after he escaped from a Florida prison. He also was
wanted in Georgia and North Carolina on armed robbery charges.
   Williams, serving a life sentence for felony murder, arson and
robbery, was convicted in the December 1980 slaying of a Marytown
resident, who was found bludgeoned in the rubble of his burned home.
   Warden Jerry Hedrick told reporters Monday that evidence
indicated the escapees had outside help. He said bloodhounds
tracked their scent across the street to a museum parking lot,
where the trail disappeared.
   Hedrick said the three, all maintenance workers, knocked a hole
in the wall of an elevator shaft in the prison infirmary to gain
entrance to a shed where equipment, including bolt cutters, is kept.
   Then they climbed through another elevator shaft to the second
floor of an unused building, where they used pipe and a cord to
lower themselves to the ground, he said.
   The escapees hid behind ventilation equipment, then used the
bolt cutters to cut through a lock on a gate and flee, he said.
   ``Something wasn't right with security,'' Hedrick said.
``Something was overlooked.''
   Stacy, formerly of Columbus, Ohio, was serving a life sentence
without chance of parole for the 1981 slaying of Huntington police
officer Paul Harmon, who was shot several times in the head with
his own service revolver. Harmon had been investigating another
officer's report of a suspicious person.
   At the time of the killing, Stacy was free on bond after being
charged with shooting a Huber Heights, Ohio, police officer with a
sawed-off shotgun.
   Stacy was a successful businessman who used the money from his
crimes for business ventures. When he was arrested, he owned a bar,
at least two houses and several automobiles.
   Huntington police officers, who usually patrol traffic alone,
teamed up in pairs Monday. ``It's always better to have two people.
A suspect is less likely to shoot that way,'' said Lt. Toby Shy.
</TEXT>
