<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DaughterSuit     04-05 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Daughter Suit,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Loses $300,000 Jury Award Against Father</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has set aside a $300,000 jury award
to an 11-year-old girl who sued her father for hitting her in the
face, saying the amount was excessive.
   ``I was shocked at the verdict,'' Circuit Judge William G.
Plummer said Monday. ``That's the simplest way I can put it.''
   He ordered a new trial to decide what compensation Samantha
Baskin should receive from her father, Peter Baskin, a prominent
lawyer. But he cautioned that the girl's emotional health must be
considered before another trial can begin.
   The lawsuit stemmed from an incident Jan. 19, 1985, during which
Samantha was hit in the face after she interrupted an argument
between her parents.
   According to testimony at the three-day trial in January, Baskin
and his wife, Heidi, were arguing at the family's Falls Church home
when Samantha, then 8 years old, repeatedly told her father to stop
shouting because she was trying to sleep.
   Baskin, 45, told the jury that he followed his daughter upstairs
to her bedroom and, while he was trying to spank her on the
buttocks, she flipped over, cursed him with a word she had been
reprimanded for using before, and he slapped her on the face.
   ``This is a slap-in-the-face case, maybe too hard,'' but
nonetheless parental chastisement for repeated use of profanity,
said Leonard S. Sattler, one of Baskin's attorneys.
   Sattler argued Monday that the award, which included interest
dating to the incident, was out of proportion to the injury, which
he described as a temporary bruise.
   Samantha's attorney, David L. Duff, agreed there was limited
physical injury to his client. He argued, however, that she
suffered extensive emotional injury. Duff maintained that
Samantha's ``bond with her father was absolutely destroyed that
night.''
   In a separate court proceeding, Baskin was acquitted of a
criminal charge arising out of the incident.
</TEXT>
