<HEAD>Singer James Brown Charged with Assaulting Wife</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Brown surrendering, bond set, other
details.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede BEECH ISLAND, S.C.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul singer James Brown surrendered today to
face charges that he beat his wife and fired a gun into a car while
she was inside.
   Brown, 54, was charged Monday with assault with intent to
murder, aggravated assault and battery. The two-time Grammy winner
turned himself in this morning and was released on $15,000 bond,
said Aiken County Sheriff Carrol Heath.
   Brown has denied the charges.
   His wife, 38-year-old Adrienne Brown, told authorities that he
fired several shots at the couple's luxury car late Sunday while
she was inside and that he later beat her with an iron pipe.
   The incidents allegedly occurred at Brown's residence in Beech
Island, S.C., just across the Savannah River from Augusta, Ga.,
Heath said.
   Mrs. Brown, the singer's third wife, was treated for bruises at
University Hospital in Augusta on Monday evening and released, the
hospital said.
   Brown, a two-time Grammy Award winner known as the ``godfather
of soul,'' said the argument began because he was leaving for a
South American tour Thursday and his wife was upset because she
would not be going.
   ``I never laid a hand on her,'' Brown said. ``I can tell you
it's over now. She's not coming back to my house. She's just mad
because I won't take her to Brazil, and she's not going to go.
She's never going to go.''
   Mrs. Brown told officers she was sleeping in the car after the
argument Sunday night when three shots were fired into the trunk of
the car and a fourth hit under the right front headlight. She said
she was beaten when she sneaked back into the house early Monday.
   Brown's attorney, Albert Dallas, said: ``Mr. and Mrs. Brown have
had an ongoing domestic issue for three years. Mr. Brown has filed
for divorce half a dozen times. They have always reconciled their
differences.''
   Brown, who created such soulful hits as ``Please, Please,
Please'' and ``It's a Man's World,'' won his second Grammy in 1987
for the rhythm and blues vocal ``Living in America.''
</TEXT>
