<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeacherDress     04-05 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Dress,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Teaching Assistant Can't Be Fired For African Head Wrap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fired teaching assistant's abilities
weren't marred by the native African head wrap she wore in class,
and she can't be denied unemployment benefits for that reason, a
judge has ruled.
   The Mississippi Employment Security Commission improperly
witheld compensation from Deborah V. McGlothin, Hinds Circuit Court
Judge Frank Banks ruled recently.
   The 34-year-old McGlothin was dismissed as a teaching assistant
at Whitfield Elementary School on March 17, 1987. Principal Kisiah
W. Nolan recommended the firing because McGlothin refused to stop
wearing head wraps, court records show.
   McGlothin went to court because she was refused unemployment
compensation. A commission referee said her firing was based on
misconduct, and that disqualified her from benefits.
   ``There was absolutely no showing that McGlothin's dress in any
way affected her performance or caused a disruption,'' Banks said
in the ruling last week. ``Such practices are protected by the
First Amendment to the United States Constitution and cannot be
`misconduct' within the meaning of the (unemployment compensation)
statute, so as to deny unemployment benefits.''
   ``I hope the case will set a precedent for serious-minded people
of our culture and religion,'' McGlothin said. ``I'd like to
commend Judge Banks.''
   McGlothin, who hopes to become a certified teacher, testified
the head wrap is a form of cultural and religious expression.
McGlothin said she follows the beliefs of the African Hebrew
Israelites of Ethiopia.
   Her religion doesn't force her to wear the head dress, but
members of her faith ``wear it on occasion, especially during times
of spiritual growth,'' she said at an unemployment commission
hearing.
   Nolan had sent her a memo telling her to stop wearing the head
wrap or be fired, court records show.
   ``All children need positive role models, but especially do
elementary-aged children because of their very impressionable young
minds. I am concerned that your appearance is giving them a
distorted view of what is appropriate,'' Nolan said in the memo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
