<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Fiji-Chief     04-05 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Fiji-Chief,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fijian Made Chief Amid Roasted Pigs, Grass Skirts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Club-carrying warriors in grass skirts
presented this Pacific archipelago's president with roasted pigs
and mats Tuesday, installing him as a tribal chief.
   The traditional ceremony gave President Ratu Sir Penaia Ganilau
tribal authority over 40,000 indigenous Fijians in four provinces
of the island chain about 2,000 miles east of Australia.
   Ganilau, 69, was appointed president of the Republic of Fiji in
December after coup leader Sitiveni Rabuka broke from British rule
and set up a military-backed republican government. Rabuka said he
intended to restore political control to ethnic Fijians, who make
up 45 percent of the population of 715,000.
   They are outnumbered by Indians, who represent half of Fiji's
people.
   Guards with clubs stood by as thousands of tribesmen watched
Tuesday's elaborate ceremony on Taveuni island 150 miles north of
the capital of Suva.
   During the ceremony, Ganilau was presented with trays of whole
roasted pigs, mats and foodstuffs by vassal tribes, guests and
other chiefs. Fiji maintains a complex tribal hierarchy.
   After he was installed, Ganilau observed custom by beginning a
four-day retreat.
</TEXT>
