<HEAD>Man Accused Of Car Theft Is Arrested During Court Recess</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was in court facing charges of
stealing a 1988 Lincoln Town Car was caught driving a stolen 1981
Mercedes while his trial was in recess for lunch, police said.
   Charles Turk's difficulties, bad enough Monday morning, were
worse Monday afternoon.
   Turk, 26, in court to face the first charge, was told to come
back at 1:30 p.m., when a jury was to be selected.
   He came back 90 minutes late via the county jail.
   In the interim, Turk was spotted driving a 1981 Mercedes
reported stolen March 30, according to an arrest report. After he
lost control of the car and smashed into a tree, police said they
saw him rush into a woman's apartment. The woman told officers she
didn't know Turk.
   Turk was charged with burglary, resisting arrest, opposing a
police officer, fleeing and eluding police and reckless driving.
Bail on the charges totaled $11,500.
   His public defender, Terry Rogers, was granted a postponement.
Rogers told Griffin his client wanted some time to think about his
legal predicament.
