<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceVice     04-05 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Vice,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Diego `Re-Evaluates' Controversial Procedures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   San Diego police are re-evaluating procedures
that allow vice officers to disrobe and engage in sexual foreplay
during prostitution investigations, a high-ranking police official
said.
   The probe was prompted by local news accounts of the San Diego
Police Department's use of such tactics in contrast to metropolitan
police departments elsewhere in the state, said Deputy Chief Norman
Stamper.
   ``We are very carefully evaluating our enforcement posture,''
said Stamper, who recently was assigned to head the force's
26-member vice unit.
   According to court records, San Diego vice officers stripped
naked and allowed themselves to be fondled last year while
soliciting for sex during investigations into massage parlors and
escort services.
   The tactics are allowed under state law, but police departments
in Los Angeles and San Francisco and other cities have outlawed
such activities because they were considered embarrassing to the
force or entrapment.
   The San Diego review could take between a few weeks and several
months, Stamper said.
   ``Any time you're dealing with prostitutes, gambling or
drunkenness, one thing is clear _ vice enforcement is different
than other types of enforcement,'' Stamper said. ``If you want to
judge it _ it's a dirty, messy job.''
   ``We pride ourselves on being a professional organization whose
officers act in a professional manner,'' Stamper said.
</TEXT>
