<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BigFee     04-05 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Big Fee,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jacksonville Law Firm Bills DOT $1,593 An Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law firm billed the state Department
of Transportation $1,593 an hour for the equivalent of 25 days work
its attorneys spent fighting a land condemnation case.
   The department was billed $325,000 for 204 hours by the law firm
of Greene, Greene, Falck and Coalson, and two courts approved the
fee.
   The law firm, which is now disbanded, also collected $1,372 an
hour _ $280,000 _ from landowner David M. Foster under a
contingency fee agreement.
   The combined bonanza for the law firm came to $2,965 an hour.
   ``The trial judge and the appellate court must have thought it
was a difficult case'' when they awarded the fee, said William L.
Coalson, who was a partner in the firm.
   The $1,593 hourly rate approved by the court was four times
greater than the previous record of $340 per hour awarded in a
condemnation case in 1978, according to a memo from the agency's
lawyers.
   The Department of Transportation is considering taking its case
to the Florida Supreme Court, in part to discourage other lawyers
from asking for similar fees in cases where the agency takes land
to build or improve a highway, transportation officials said.
   The case started when the state offered Foster $582,000 for nine
acres to improve an intersection in Jacksonville, said Ken
Towcimak, the agency's right-of-way chief.
   Foster argued that the land was far more valuable because it was
behind a shopping center and therefore ripe for retail development.
   At a December 1986 trial, the 12-member Duval County jury said
the parcel was worth $1.9 million, $1.3 million more than the
original offer by the road department.
   To fulfill its legal obligation to pay attorney and appraisal
fees for landowners, the road department was ordered by the court
to pay $325,000, although Coalson's firm disclosed the contingency
arrangement by which it had already earned $280,000.
   ``What our client pays us with his eyes wide open is none of
their (the state's) business,'' Coalson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
