<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Honduras-Drugs     04-05 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-Drugs,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Man Wanted In U.S. In Killing Of Drug Agent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today arrested Juan Ramon
Matta, a Honduran wanted by the United States in the slaying of a
special narcotics agent, his lawyer said.
   Lawyer Carlos Lorenzana said in a telephone interview that about
60 policemen, supported by army helicopters, raided Matta's
luxurious home in Tegucigalpa before dawn and captured him and
seven bodyguards.
   Lorenzana said the raid began at 5:45 a.m., but gave no other
details. He said Matta was taken to a special police unit
headquarters at the village of La Venta, 12 miles east of the
capital, where he was being questioned.
   A police spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity, refused
to provide reporters details of the raid or confirm it had
occurred. But armed police surrounded Matta's and Lorenzana's homes
in the capital.
   Matta, 43, returned to Honduras after escaping in 1986 from a
Colombian prison where he was being held on charges that he was a
top operative for the Medellin drug cartel.
   He was jailed here briefly and on his release threw 100 lempira
bills out the window of his Mercedes to convicts in the yard. The
bills are the equivalent of $50.
   ``In jail, there are always needy people,'' he told The
Associated Press in an interview in February.
   He said of the charges against him, ``It's all a lie, a story.''
He also claimed U.S. agents tried three times to kidnap him in the
past year.
   Matta is wanted in the United States on drug charges and in
connection with the 1985 torture-murder of U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration agent Enrique Camarena Salazar in Guadalajara,
Mexico.
   He is a Honduran citizen, and the constitution prohibits his
extradition.
</TEXT>
