<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Contras-Negotiations     04-05 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras-Negotiations,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Demand Freedom in Nicaragua For Truce Negotiators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders today demanded freedom for their
negotiators to move around Nicaragua during next week's peace
talks, rejecting a Sandinista proposal limiting them to a Managua
airport hotel.
   ``We will not go to Nicaragua to be confined,'' Contra director
Pedro Joaquin Chamorro said at a news conference at the Miami
headquarters of the Nicaraguan Resistance, as the anti-government
rebels are formally called.
   Adolfo Calero, the director named today as head of the
negotiating team, said the Contras were demanding the right to meet
freely with Nicaraguan opposition leaders, the press, Roman
Catholic and anti-draft groups, and to publish their ads in both
the government and opposition press.
   Chamorro said the Contras sent their counterproposal to the
leftist Sandinista government late this morning and were awaiting a
reply.
   The rebel leaders said they intend to arrive April 12 in Managua
with 60 people, including the five directors, members of the
Resistance assembly, and political figures.
   Their schedule calls six meetings with the Sandinistas before
the delegation leaves April 15.
   ``The agenda is open,'' said Calero, saying the Contras will
emphasize democratization.
   The Contras dismissed several reported violations of the truce
signed last month in Sapoa, Nicaragua.
   ``Overall the cease-fire is holding,'' said Chamorro.
   But he added that the truce cannot become definitive until the
Sandinistas agree and take steps toward democratizing Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
