<2ND_LINE>PM-Skull Found, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seek Link Between Missing People, Alleged Assault</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with digging continuing today,
other police comment. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `While Berdella ....'
Contents of the following may be offensive to some readers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police using hand shovels and a backhoe
continued digging today in the back yard of a home where three
skulls and gruesome photographs of torture were found.
   The investigation began after a 22-year-old man told police he
had escaped from the house after being held for five days in a
basement, tortured and sexually assaulted. The owner of the house,
Robert Berdella, was arrested Saturday.
   Police are reviewing disappearances of young men in 1984 and
1985 as well as other unsolved cases to see if there is a
connection, Sgt. Troy Cole of the Kansas City Police Department's
homicide unit said Monday.
   Berdella, 39, was charged with seven counts of forcible sodomy,
one count of felonious restraint and one count of first-degree
assault. He pleaded innocent to the charges but remained in custody
in lieu of $500,000 bond.
   A skull believed to be that of a human was found Sunday buried
in the yard. Two other skulls, one also believed human were found
by police in Berdella's three-story house, along with what appeared
to be human neck bones, police spokesman Alan French said today.
   The excavation of Berdella's back yard was expected to be
completed later today, he said, and police then planned a more
thorough examination of the house.
   Investigators already drilled through some sections of what
appeared to be a freshly poured concrete floor in the basement, but
found nothing suspicious.
   Sgt. Laura Mulloy, a police spokeswoman, said pictures seized in
the house showed a captive hitchhiker being tortured and a young
man who may have been dead.
   ``The neighborhood is in shock over this,'' said Astrid Bebuhr,
who lives across the street from Berdella. ``There was no
indication that somebody was being tortured in his home.''
   Police found a white metal box filled with feathers buried in
the yard. Ms. Mulloy said officers did not know the significance of
the discovery.
   French said an FBI agent who is a specialist in cults would be
joining the investigation today.
   While Berdella was waiting in a Jackson County courtroom to be
arraigned Monday, he was assaulted by a man whose son has been
missing for four years, said Jackson County Prosecutor Albert
Riederer.
   Berdella was not seriously injured.
   Paul Howell, 44, told a reporter after police let him go that
his son, Jerry Howell, was reported to have been seen with Berdella
before disappearing in July 1984. His son was 19 years old at the
time.
   Berdella owns Bob's Bazaar Bizarre, a shop in the Old Westport
Flea Market, where his wares include replicas of skulls, as well as
beads, jewelry and exotic ornaments. Howell, the father of the
missing boy, had a shop in the same flea market but closed it after
his son's disappearance.
   Berdella's neighbors said he was active in a crime prevention
program in his neighborhood. He lobbied for neighborhood watch
signs and urged neighbors to put up porch lights, they said.
</TEXT>
