<2ND_LINE>AM-Purple Heart,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Purple Heart For Boy Who Recovered From Coma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RETSIL, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of a World War I veteran has
given her husband's Purple Heart medal to a 13-year-old boy who's
recovering from a 2{-month coma after a near-fatal, 40-foot fall.
   Shane Nicholich accepted the medal gingerly from Eleanor Prong,
79, a resident of the Washington Veterans Home here.
   ``I'd like to give you this medal, Shane, for the fighter you
are,'' Mrs. Prong said Saturday.
   In July 1986, Shane, then 12, fell out of a tree in his back
yard and suffered a severe head injury and brain damage. A 2{-month
coma followed, and doctors weren't encouraging about his recovery.
   But in February, Shane, of Sumner, won the school district
spelling bee by spelling ``hypodermic.''
   He's resumed a somewhat normal life, though he still undergoes
therapy.
   Mrs. Prong said she and her late husband, Gustave August Prong,
have no close relatives and she wanted Shane to have the medal.
   Prong, who died at age 61 in 1959, was awarded the Purple Heart
posthumously about 10 years ago, 62 years after his left kneecap
was shattered by German bullets in the Argonne Forest in France.
</TEXT>
