<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0665 04-05 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0665,790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 6 grafs after 4th graf pvs, `Jackson said,' with
campaign manager trying to reach party leadership to protest
Colorado situation, additional comments from Jackson; EDITS to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic candidate Jesse Jackson today
complained that the slow count of caucus results in Colorado was
``beyond explanation'' and suggested it may have been delayed to
give the appearance of a lead for rival Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson said Colorado state Democratic Party Chairman Buie
Seawell had appeared ``biased and politically unethical'' for
remaining in control of the party apparatus while endorsing Dukakis.
   ``The state chairman endorsed Mr. Dukakis,'' Jackson said. ``You
cannot very well be a fair referee and coaching another player.''
   Jackson said Colorado Democrats had changed 30 caucus sites as
late as Friday or Saturday without telling the Jackson campaign.
   Jackson said his campaign manager, Gerald Austin, had been
trying to reach Democratic Party Chairman Paul Kirk to protest the
Colorado situation.
   ``It comes very close to obstructing justice,'' Jackson said. He
said the changing of caucus sites ``goes to the heart of the
pre-clearance provisions of the Voting Rights Act.''
   As an example of unfairness, Jackson said one of the caucus
sites was in the governor's mansion.
   ``A caucus site in the governor's mansion does not appear to be
proper,'' he said. The caucus sites ``should be in very public
places, mutually agreed upon by the candidates and the party.''
   Jackson said he did not publicly protest the changing of caucus
sites while campaigning in Colorado over the weekend because he
wanted ``to avoid creating conflict.''
   He said Austin had protested to Seawell, whose response Jackson
described as ``not one that was rationale.''
   Jackson spoke to reporters after appearing before auto workers
in Kenosha, the last stop of his campaign in Wisconsin as voters
were going to the polls for the state presidential primary.
   ``This long and slow count represents a certain ineptness ... it
heightens suspicions,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson said the point was underscored by the fact that missing
precincts were in Denver and Boulder _ not remote areas. As of this
afternoon, only a quarter of the Denver vote had been counted.
   ``To report selectively certain precincts today could be a way
of feeding the media on a timetable that favors a candidate you
favor _ and of course the state chairman favors a candidate. ...
It's controlling the process,'' Jackson said.
   ``The fact is the count should have been in now .... It is
unthinkable in 1988 with all this technology that Denver and
Boulder would come in last,'' he said.
   The state Democratic Party early this morning called off
counting for the night with Dukakis in the lead. With 44 percent of
the precincts reporting, the Massachusetts governor had 46 percent
to Jackson's 40 percent.
   ``It's beyond explanation the returns are this slow and this
late,'' Jackson said.
   He said Seawell's endorsement ``undermines credibility and makes
the process look to be less than just.''
   But Jackson added that he wasn't trying to ``impugn anyone's
character.''
   Jackson was hoping in Wisconsin to demonstrate broad support
beyond minorities, who make up a small portion of the voting
population in the state, and repeat the success he scored with a
landslide victory in neighboring Michigan 10 days earlier.
   Jackson was runing behind Dukakis in the latest Wisconsin
polling, but the race was considered a close two-way contest, with
Democrats Albert Gore Jr. and Paul Simon also running.
   Jackson hoped, as in Colorado a day earlier, that the large,
enthusiastic and racially mixed crowds that greeted him were a
harbinger of the primary outcome.
   As he campaigned, however, Jackson was dogged at every stop by
questions about his appeal to Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega to leave and offering ``to do whatever I can to help
alleviate the suffering'' _ an appeal that he made two weeks ago
but that burst back into view with Noriega's response on the eve of
the voting.
   Faced with a suggestion from the State Department that he was
interfering, Jackson telephoned top State Department officials from
a campaign stop and told reporters he and the administration were
in agreement on the need for Noriega to leave and for humanitarian
aid to Panama's poor.
   ``Our positions in fact overlap,'' Jackson said. ``Our position,
that he should go, is the same.''
   Jackson said he was not warned to tone down his efforts, but the
suggestion of a foreign policy misstep was not what the Jackson
campaign wanted just at the time it was seeking a breakthrough in
substantial white support.
</TEXT>
