<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-CopterCrash 3rdLd-Writethru   04-05 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Copter Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0588,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Pilot and West German Killed in Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with identity of pilot and type of
helicopter, Army saying second victim was West German employee,
sted soldier. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STUTTGART, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small U.S. Army helicopter
crashed in southern West Germany today, killing the American pilot
and a West German U.S. Army employee, the Army said.
   There were no other casualties in the 9 a.m. crash near Nabern,
25 miles southeast of Stuttgart, according to a statement by the
Stuttgart-based U.S. Army 7th Corps.
   The statement identified the dead pilot as 1st Lt. Glen P.
Adams, 28, who was assigned to Headquarters Company, 4th Battalion,
159th Aviation, 11th Aviation Brigade, in Schwaebisch Hall, near
Stuttgart. The Army could not provide his hometown. Adams is
survived by his wife.
   The second victim was a West German employee of the U.S. Army,
who was a passenger on the aircraft, the statement said. His name
was being withheld until his next of kin had been notified, the
Army said.
   A board of officers from the U.S. Army Safety Center, Fort
Rucker, Ala., was scheduled to arrive in West Germany Wednesday to
investigate the cause of the crash of the OH-58A Kiowa helicopter,
the statement added.
   ``The helicopter was on a routine support mission. There were no
weapons or ammunition on board,'' U.S. Army spokeswoman Hilda
Goodhand said in a telephone interview.
   Stuttgart police said the helicopter went down in an open area,
apparently after running into tree branches in a heavy fog. U.S.
military officials immediately cordoned off the site.
   It was the third crash of a NATO military aircraft in less than
a week.
   A French Mirage jet fighter crashed on March 30 one mile from a
nuclear power plant in the southern state of Bavaria, killing the
pilot.
   One day later, a U.S. Air Force F-16 fighter jet crashed into
the southern town of Forst, demolishing three houses and killing a
resident and the pilot.
</TEXT>
