<DOCNO> AP880405-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Romania     04-05 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Romania,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Villages to Vanish to Get More Land For State Farms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian officials have spelled out plans
to erase 7,000 villages and form big agricultural-industrial
centers by the year 2000, a move that critics of the regime say
will ruin traditional country life.
   The huge project unveiled last month by Romanian Communist Party
leader Nicolae Ceausescu calls for radical cuts in the number of
villages, from 13,000 to only 5,000 or 6,000.
   A statement published March 4 in the party daily Scinteia said
the move aims ``to eradicate basic differences betweeen villages
and cities and ensure the harmonious development of all areas of
the country.''
   Romanian officials writing in the government press say the
program is intended to gain about 765,600 acres of land for use by
state-owned collective farms.
   They say this will be achieved by banning construction of
one-family homes and concentrating several families in city-style
apartment blocks.
   Thousands of such apartment blocks _ many with only rudimentary
amenities _ have been built since 1986, when a new systematization
law on getting more farmland was passed.
   Families put into such apartment blocks lose their traditional
small plots, which are regarded as a staple provider of food in the
shortage-plagued Communist nation, and they must use communal
facilities to grow food and raise livestock.
   About 8,300 apartments were built in 15 rural communities around
Bucharest last year, according to official figures.
   ``The entire project amounts to the destruction of villages, the
traditional family cell of Romanians,'' said Mihnea Berindei, a
Romanian emigre living in Paris, in a telephone interview with the
Associated Press on Tuesday.
   Berindei, who is spokesman of the Paris-based League for the
Defense of Human Rights in Romania, said thousands of churches also
were threatened with demolition under the ``systematization
plans,'' the official title for the project to reduce the number of
villages.
   ``This project has no equivalent in Eastern Europe,'' he said.
   In 1981, Ceausescu launched a ``new agricultural revolution''
aimed at boosting disappointing cereal outputs, the source of
widespread food shortages and rationing.
   Romanian agriculture has been plagued by lack of incentives,
fodder shortages for private livestock and a system of contracting
which forces farmers to sell their produce to the state under
obligatory contracts against low prices.
   Despite official promises in December to enable each Romanian to
buy about 13 pounds of meat a month on average, meat is still
rationed to a little more than two pounds per capita a month and is
in short supply, Romanian sources say.
   Addressing a conference of local government officials in
Bucharest on March 3, Ceausescu announced the villages project will
entail the merger of scores of villages and communes into 558
agricultural-industrial centers, viewed as communities linking
rural and town life.
   The nationwide undertaking is likely to lead to the relocation
of hundreds of thousands of villagers from old family homes to
two-or three-story apartment blocks with communal kitchens and
sanitary installations.
   Ceausescu urged in his speech that doctors, teachers and farm
engineers who live in nearby towns and commute daily to the
villages where they are employed should move into the rural
apartment blocks starting this year.
   Some apartments destined for the ``village intelligentsia'' have
already been built and officials say the program will be completed
by 1989.
   Half of Romania's population of 23 million resides in the
country, according to official figures. The collectivized
agriculture is almost fully state-owned, except for 9 percent of
farmland permitted to peasants as small private plots around their
homes or in hilly areas where collectivization was not possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
