<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Austria-Space     04-05 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Austria-Space,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austria to Go Into Space With Soviet Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday decided to
train scientists to serve as astronauts in a Soviet space flight.
   Austria will also build a satellite under the plan, which calls
for Austrian participation in several Soviet space projects.
   Soviet Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov raised the idea in June on a
visit to Vienna.
   Possible candidates for Austrian participation in a space flight
will be sought through newspaper and trade journal advertisements.
The education in the Soviet Union is to last two years, the Austria
Press Agency reported.
   Austrian scientists have already made proposals for space
experiments, and researchers at Technical University in Graz are
working on a small satellite to place outside the Soviet space
station ``Mir.''
   The cost of Austrian participation in a Soviet space mission,
tentatively set for 1992, was estimated at $13 million.
</TEXT>
