<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lyubimov     04-05 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lyubimov,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exiled Stage Director Enthusiastic About Moscow Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exiled director Yuri Lyubimov
said Tuesday he was looking forward to seeing friends, former
colleagues, and the Taganka Theater when he visits to Moscow next
month.
   Lyubimov, in an interview with The Associated Press, stressed
that his first visit to the Soviet Union in almost five years was
still pending government approval.
   ``I do not have a visa or an official invitation yet,'' Lyubimov
told the AP, speaking in Russian and using a German-speaking
interpreter.
   Lyubimov, founder of Moscow's Taganka Theater and director there
until his exile, was invited by the theater to preside in May over
final rehearsals of ``Boris Godunov,'' the controversial piece that
led to his exile and expulsion from the Communist Party.
   ``I'm very much looking forward to seeing friends, actors, and
the Taganka Theater,'' said Lyubimov, 70, adding that he would only
spend about 10 days in the Soviet Union.
   ``I would only spend about 10 days there,'' he said.
   He did not, however, rule out possibly working in Moscow again
in the future.
   ``I have various contracts to work in Western Europe and in
Israel for the next few years,'' Lyubimov told the AP. ``But there
are time gaps between those engagements when I could possibly work
in Moscow.''
   The Taganka's deputy director, Alexander M. Yefimovich, said
Monday in Moscow that Lyubimov would be coming for a brief working
visit.
   Lyubimov, who is working on a production of Richard Wagner's
``Tannhaeuser'' in Stuttgart, said he was invited to Moscow last
week by Taganka Theater director Nikolai Gubenko in Madrid, where
the troupe was performing Maxim Gorky's ``Mother.''
   The director declined to give the dates of his Moscow visit.
   He is, however, expected to stay in Stuttgart at least until the
May 7 premiere of ``Tannhaeuser,'' said Stuttgart Theater
spokeswoman Annemarie Gross.
   Lyubimov, who founded the Taganka Theater and made it famous
with its avant-garde productions and controversial themes, battled
with censors throughout much of his career in Moscow.
   In July 1983 he went to London to direct Fyodor Dostoyevsky's
``Crime and Punishment.'' He extended his stay, demanding
assurances that he would be allowed artistic freedom once back in
the Soviet Union.
   The director was fired from the Taganka in March 1984 and
expelled from the Communist Party. He lives in Jerusalem with his
wife, Katalin, and son, Peter. He became an Israeli citizen this
year.
   Since his departure from Moscow he has been staging productions
around the world. His plans for the next few years include
productions in Britain, Sweden, and Israel, Lyubimov said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
