<DOCNO> AP880405-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-USATodayTV     04-05 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USA Today TV,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Version of USA Today Taking Shape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In case anyone had any doubts, the staff
preparing ``USA Today: The Television Show'' for its fall debut
demonstrated Tuesday that the video version of the national
newspaper will mirror the publication that spawned it.
   At a news conference at the newspaper's offices just outside
Washington, the executive producer and four hosts of the program
discussed a show they said will offer segments that people find
interesting and understandable, graphics that will glitter and
stories that will supplement _ not compete with _ the network news.
   ``If we can't do it better or different, we're not going to do
it,'' the show's executive producer, Steve Friedman, said. ``Once
you've looked at a burning ship in the Persian Gulf four or five
times, you don't want to look at it any more.''
   The nighttime show premieres Sept. 12. It will run for 30
minutes every weeknight and have an hour-long weekend edition. Like
the newspaper, it will have segments devoted to news, lifestyle,
sports and business, focusing on articles that will appear in USA
Today the next morning.
   Friedman said the producers so far had 118 firm contracts with
television stations across the country to broadcast the program,
covering 85 percent of the country. Those agreements make the show
more available to early evening viewers than any program with the
exception of ``Wheel of Fortune,'' said Friedman, who guided NBC's
``Today'' show for nearly a decade.
   The team selected to host the program include Edie Magnus, hired
from ABC News's ``World News This Morning'' to anchor the
``Front-Page'' segment; and Robin Young, a former contributing
correspondent for NBC's ``Nightly News'' and ``Today'' shows who
will host the ``Life Section.''
   In addition, Bill Macatee, a former NBC News sports reporter,
will host the show's ``Sports Section,'' while former ABC News
White House correspondent Kenneth Walker has been hired to anchor
the ``Money Section.''
   ``We have a pretty much open mandate to do what we find
interesting,'' Macatee said.
   As examples of what the show may offer, Macatee said segments
could include allowing baseball fan and former President Richard
Nixon to call the final out of a World Series game.
   ``Or let's have the head of an airline dress like a pilot for a
day to see how it fits, see how people react,'' he said.
   The hosts, whom Friedman described as ``my dream team,'' not
only would introduce segments but report many of them.
   ``A lot of people can report,'' Friedman said. ``A lot of people
can read a TelePrompTer. Very few people can do both.''
   Friedman also said the show would rely heavily on reporters for
the newspaper, with television cameras brought into the paper's
newsroom for interviews with the writers.
   He said that if a reporter for the paper had an exclusive
interview with a news subject, he might be asked on camera, ``What
was that person really like close up? Did you see the kids?''
   The news conference _ featuring a 12-minute demonstration tape _
was the first of six also to be held in New York, Detroit, Chicago,
Dallas and Los Angeles over a fast-moving three days that Friedman
said he is calling the ``Prop-capade.''
   The reference was to series of USA Today articles based on
cross-country and global trips, dubbed ``Bus-Capade'' and
``Jet-Capade,'' by Allen H. Neuharth, chairman of the Gannett Co.,
which publishes the newspaper.
   The program is produced by GTG Entertainment, a partnership
between Grant Tinker, the former NBC chairman of the board and
independent producer, and Gannett. Gannett, the country's largest
newspaper chain, owns 90 daily papers, 10 television stations and
16 radio stations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0135 </DOCNO>
