<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Brown     04-05 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Brown,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soul Singer Free On Bond On Assault With Intent To Murder Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul singer James Brown turned himself in
Tuesday after being charged with beating up his wife and shooting
up her car while she cowered inside.
   ``He beat her up real bad; she's got bruises all over her. He
also shot up her car,'' Aiken County Sheriff Carrol Heath said.
   Brown, 54, is charged with assault with intent to murder and
assault and battery of a high and aggravated nature. He was
released on $15,000 bond.
   Heath said Brown's wife, Adrienne Lois Brown, 38, told
authorities Brown shot at her car while she was inside and later
beat her with a pipe.
   Brown denied the charges. He said he and his wife had argued
because he was leaving without her Thursday for a South American
tour.
   Brown, a two-time Grammy winner, is famous for such soul music
hits as ``Please, Please, Please,'' ``It's a Man's World,''
``Papa's Got a Brand New Bag'' and ``Living in America.''
   Heath said the incident occurred late Sunday or early Monday at
the Browns' residence near Beech Island, S.C.
   ``I never laid a hand on her. I can tell you it's over now.
She's not coming back to my house,'' Brown said.
   An investigator's report said four bullets hit the car, three in
the rear and one under a headlight. Mrs. Brown was not hit by the
gunfire.
   Mrs. Brown, who said she planned to file for a legal separation,
said she and the singer have been married for eight years.
   ``I didn't do anything to provoke him, no sir,'' said Mrs.
Brown. ``This is not the first time he's done this. He's knocked
out all my teeth.''
</TEXT>
