<2ND_LINE>AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt, 2 takes, 750-1,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colorado Unfolds as Wisconsin Voters Go To the Polls</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Colorado count resumes this afternoon; Wisconsin polls close
9 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson, locked in a
grind-it-out struggle for the 1988 Democratic presidential
nomination, faced off Tuesday in the Wisconsin primary. Dukakis led
his rival narrowly in a slow count from the Colorado caucuses.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. spent heavily in Wisconsin and sought an
elusive breakthrough outside his native South. Sen. Paul Simon
struggled for survival, with several big industrial states still to
come, beginning with New York on April 19.
   Vice President George Bush won Colorado handily and faced only
nominal opposition in Wisconsin as he continued his grand march
toward nomination at the Republican National Convention this summer.
   With returns compiled from 51 percent of Colorado's precincts,
Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis was winning 44 percent of the vote.
Jackson, the man with momentum in the race since his smashing
Michigan landslide 10 days ago, had 42 percent. Gore had 3 percent.
Dukakis had 3,035 county delegates to Jackson's 2,915.
   Jackson complained that party officials who favored Dukakis were
manipulating the slow count. ``It heightens suspicions,'' he said.
``It's beyond explanation.''
   Early Republican straw poll numbers from Colorado's caucuses
Monday night showed Bush with 1,288 votes, or 78 percent, and
former television evangelist Pat Robertson with 136, or 8 percent.
   But Wisconsin loomed as a far more important test than Colorado
in the see-saw Democratic struggle, partially because it offered
more delegates _ 81 compared with Colorado's 45. Democratic rivals
invested heavily in time and money in their bid to claim the
support of Wisconsin's large blue collar vote and gain fresh
momentum for the rest of the primary season.
   Dukakis held a shaky lead over Jackson in pre-election surveys
in overwhelmingly white Wisconsin, with Tennessee Sen. Gore a
distant third. Illinois Sen. Simon lagged with single-digit support
in the polls and seemed likely to suspend his campaign if he fared
poorly.
   For the Democrats, Wisconsin turned out to be a surprisingly
important test in their nominating wars, a gauge of a struggling
Dukakis campaign and of Jackson's surprising momentum. It was a
prelude, as well, to delegate-rich primaries in New York,
Pennsylvania and Ohio just ahead.
   Dukakis looked for a victory to silence the critics who said
defeats last month in Illinois and Michigan called into question
his ability to attract the blue collar votes a Democrat needs to
win the White House in the fall election.
   Jackson aimed for a win in a state where only 4 percent of the
voters were black, reckoning that would give him dramatic new
stature in the race.
   Gore spent heavily in television advertising in hopes of
sneaking up on his rivals or at least winning 20 percent of the
popular vote. He needed that much to re-qualify for federal
matching campaign funds.
   Simon said a poor finish would force him to reassess his
candidacy. A decision to suspend rather than withdraw was one
possibility, aides said, a move designed to gain additional
delegates from his homestate of Illinois to be used in any
back-room brokering at the party convention this summer.
   For Republicans, there was no suspense at all.
   Bush ran a television advertising campaign in Wisconsin, but it
was hard to see why. Following Sen. Bob Dole's withdrawal a week
ago, Robertson was his only active rival, and he didn't bother
campaigning in the state.
   Wisconsin had 81 Democratic delegates at stake, with the bounty
parceled out on the basis of popular vote by congressional district.
   Republicans had 47.
   Bush began the day with 841 delegates, out of 1,039 needed for
the nomination. Robertson had 17.
   Dukakis led Jackson, 671.55 to 665.55. Gore had 381.8 delegates
and Simon had 170.5. It takes 2,081 to claim the Democratic
nomination.
   So unpredictable was the Democratic race that campaign aides
said it might hinge on factors entirely beyond their reach.
   Milwaukee picked a new mayor for the first time since 1960, and
the forecast was for an unusually heavy vote in the state's biggest
city.
   Under state rules, Republicans were permitted to cross over and
vote in the Democratic contest. When GOP Gov. Tommy Thompson made
complimentary remarks about Jackson last week, some Democrats
feared that Republicans might do just that mischievously, voting
for the former civil rights leader in the belief that he would be
an easy victim for Bush in November.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
