<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1458EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Boylan     04-05 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Boylan,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brennan Refuses to Free NJ Lawyer From Defending Alleged Mobster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court justice on Tuesday refused to
free a prominent New Jersey lawyer and his firm from having to
defend an alleged mobster whose previous attorney became seriously
ill.
   Justice William J. Brennan rejected an emergency request by
Matthew P. Boylan and his firm to suspend a court order holding
them in contempt for refusing to defend an alleged organized crime
boss.
   U.S. District Judge Judge Harold Ackerman in Newark held Boylan
in contempt on Feb. 29 after the original defense lawyer became
terminally ill with cancer and had to leave the case. Ackerman is
presiding over the trial.
   Boylan is a former director of the New Jersey Division of
Criminal Justice and a former assistant U.S. attorney for New
Jersey.
   Ackerman also issued a contempt citation against Boylan's law
firm, Lowenstein, Sandler, Kohl, Fisher & Boylan of Roseland, N.J.,
for its refusal to assist Boylan. He fined Boylan $2,500 a day
until he accepted the assignment and the firm $10,000 a day.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the contempt
citations on March 9.
   Boylan balked at representing Anthony Accetturo, allegedly the
leader of the Lucchese organized-crime family in New Jersey.
   Ackerman said he selected Boylan because of his pretrial work
for the defendant.
   Milton M. Ferrel Sr. had been Accetturo's lawyer until cancer
forced him to leave the case.
   Boylan said representing Accetturo would mean he would have to
neglect obligations to five other clients.
   He and his firm noted that the trial of Accetturo and 20 others
on extortion, gambling and narcotics charges began in November
1986, has produced more than 27,000 pages of transcripts and is
likely to continue for another six months.
   The 3rd Circuit court gave Boylan 24 days to prepare his defense
of Accetturo.
   The case is U.S. vs. Accetturo, A-735.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
