<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1516EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Contras     04-05 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Demand Freedom in Nicaragua For Truce Negotiators</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders said Tuesday they would not continue
peace talks with the Sandinistas unless their delegation is allowed
to travel and speak freely inside Nicaragua during next week's
negotiations.
   The Sandinistas had told the Contra leaders they must remain
confined to an airport hotel, said rebel director Adolfo Calero,
named Tuesday as chief negotiator.
   ``It is a virtual imprisonment,'' Calero said at Contra
headquarters here. ``It is not in keeping with the idea of
reconciliation, with the idea of democratization.''
   The Contras said they will not go to Managua for the next round
of talks unless they are permitted to travel freely around
Nicaragua and speak with opposition groups.
   The Contras, who expect to arrive in Nicaragua April 12 with a
60-member delegation, plan meetings with domestic opposition
leaders, Roman Catholic bishops, anti-draft groups, business
leaders and reporters.
   They will also demand the right to place ads in both government
and opposition newspapers announcing their agenda and meetings.
   ``We are demanding that we be free when we are in Nicaragua,''
said Calero. He said the Contras were awaiting a reply to their
counterproposal, which was sent Tuesday morning to the Sandinista
foreign ministry.
   Director Pedro Joaquin Chamorro said he had been informed that
La Prensa, the principal opposition newspaper, had run out of
newsprint Tuesday, and insisted the Sandinistas supply it under
terms of the agreement negotiated last month in Sapoa, Nicaragua.
   The Contras sidestepped the possibility of a public rally inside
Nicaragua during their stay, saying that would be decided by local
opposition parties.
   The rebels expect to meet six times with the Sandinistas before
leaving April 15, and will concentrate on steps toward
democratizing the country, said Calero.
   ``It will become the Sandinistas' acid test,'' said Calero. ``It
will be very difficult for the Sandinistas to keep the agreement
and hold on to power.''
   The Contras dismissed several ``very minor'' truce violations by
both sides in recent days.
   ``Overall the cease-fire is holding,'' said Chamorro. He said
despite initial resistance to the pact by rebel field commanders,
they have come to accept the truce arrangement.
   Chamorro denied suggestions, made in testimony before a
congressional committee, that there were links between the Contras
and Panama's strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``We have no links with Gen. Noriega _ absolutely,'' said
Chamorro. He said reports Contras had been trained in that country
were ``absolutely false,'' and said it was the Sandinistas, not the
rebels, who received aid through Panama.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1651EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d i AM-CounterfeitMoney     04-05 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Counterfeit Money,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dog Helps Young Men Find Counterfeit Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two young men who noticed
their dog digging in a brush-covered field helped recover an
estimated $10 million to $12 million in counterfeit cash that
Canadian and U.S. police had been seeking since 1976.
   The men, whose names were withheld, dug up two garbage bags
stuffed with about $4 million in bogus U.S. federal reserve
banknotes before calling police.
   Royal Canadian Mounted Police officers, digging Monday, found an
additional $8 million in uncut sheets of counterfeit $100, $50 and
$20 U.S. bills described as ``really good quality.''
   Cpl. Barry Danton of the Vancouver RCMP commercial crime squad
said an investigation had produced suspects but no arrests. He said
U.S. Treasury Department agents and the RCMP had been looking for
the money since 1976 when ``quite a bit'' of the same batch was
seized.
   ``We knew it was buried but we thought it was somewhere else,''
he said. ``We knew it was around.''
   ``We estimate it at about $10 million to $12 million,'' said
Danton. ``We haven't had time to count it yet. We're just going by
thickness. It filled the trunk of a car pretty good.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
