<1ST_LINE>u p PM-ColoCaucuses 4thLd-Writethru a0702 04-05 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colo Caucuses, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0702,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Lead Holds as Counting Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs NEW with updated numbers; pick up 5th graf pvs,
``Vice President; INSERTS 2 grafs Seawell, Dukakis response to
Jackson charges after 12th graf, ``This long</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis held onto a narrow lead over rival
Democrat Jesse Jackson in Colorado's precinct caucuses today with
the resumption of a slow-moving counting process that Jackson said
``heightens suspicions.''
   ``The fact is, the count should have been in now,'' Jackson said
today in Kenosha, Wis. ``The long count is unfair.''
   With 57 percent of the precincts in Colorado reporting, the
Massachusetts governor had 45 percent of the vote while Jackson had
41 percent. Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, who made little
effort in the state, trailed with less than 3 percent.
   Dukakis had 3,626 county delegates to Jackson's 3,276, according
to figures supplied by the Colorado Democratic Party.
   Calculations based on the incomplete returns indicated Dukakis
would win 21 national convention delegates if he maintained his
lead in later returns and the results held up at the congressional
district and state conventions in the next few weeks. Jackson would
win 17 delegates and another seven would be uncommitted.
   Vice President George Bush dominated straw polls taken at
Republican caucuses, cornering nearly 80 percent of the vote and
staving off a feared ambush by Pat Robertson.
   Dukakis and Jackson had hoped to use the caucuses _ which are
the first step in selecting 45 Colorado Democratic delegates _ to
gain stature for today's Wisconsin primary.
   But with the results trickling in and the candidates within a
few percentage points of one another, it appeared neither would be
able to claim a big victory.
   State Democratic chairman Buie Seawell, a Colorado super
delegate and Dukakis supporter, said he believed the Massachusetts
governor would be the winner. However, he said, ``Jackson has done
one hell of a job in a state that is not Jackson country.''
   In return, Jackson criticized the slow counting process,
supervised by Seawell.
   ``The state chairman endorsed Mr. Dukakis,'' Jackson said. ``You
cannot very well be a fair referee and coaching another player.''
   ``This long and slow count represents a certain ineptness ... it
heightens suspicions,'' he said.
   Seawell responded today that Jackson ``is just wrong'' and said
he took ``personal offense'' at the candidate's remarks. He said
his staff reported every precinct where results were available
Monday night.
   ``To the best of my knowledge, it was run fairly and well,''
Dukakis said today of the Colorado contest.
   As expected, Bush, who stands almost alone in his quest for the
nomination, dominated the scant returns reported to Republican
Party officials. Bush's chief rival, Bob Dole, dropped out last
week.
   Early Republican straw poll results showed Bush with 1,288 straw
votes or 78 percent and Robertson with 136, or 8 percent, at 201
GOP precinct caucuses.
   Dukakis had picked up endorsements several weeks ago from Gov.
Roy Romer and Seawell, but Jackson made his presence felt with a
series of strong campaign appearances over the Easter weekend.
   While no delegates to the Democratic or Republican national
conventions were chosen Monday, the caucuses began a complicated
delegate selection process that will culminate at the state
conventions in May and June.
   Colorado will send 51 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, six of them super delegates, including Romer and
Seawell. Thirty-six Colorado Republicans will attend their party's
national convention.
   The state Democratic Party had planned to provide results by
12:30 a.m. today from Colorado's 13 most populous counties, which
account for 80 percent of the state's 2,784 precincts. But the
party was able to report less than 20 percent of the state's
precincts by its self-imposed deadline.
   Some caucuses delayed their start in order to allow sports fans
to watch the end of the Kansas-Oklahoma NCAA basketball
championship. One precinct took a recess so participants could
watch the game.
   Dukakis' campaigners were pleased with the initial caucus
results.
   ``We had hoped to hold our own in Denver and we are doing better
than we expected,'' said David Villarino, Dukakis' state director.
   ``We are doing well among the Hispanics. Jackson had hoped to
seal the Hispanic vote but we have done well there,'' he said.
   Mike Veit, Gore's campaign director, said his campaign had spent
only $17,000 in Colorado. ``I think people in Colorado still have a
sort of a Gary Hart hangover,'' he said, refering to the state's
former senator who twice entered and dropped out of the race and
noting the large number of uncommitted delegates.
   ``They've been on sort of a roller-coaster.''
</TEXT>
