<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lower Holiday Viewing Hurts Nets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``CBS won xxx, to CORRECT Wallis, sted Wallace</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The King of England and even Sophia Loren
weren't enough to lure viewers to their sets over the holiday
weekend, according to last week's Nielsen ratings.
   The week ending April 3 was NBC's fifth weekly win in a row and
its 24th win in the 30-week season, which ends in two weeks. NBC
had an average rating of 14.6. ABC had 12.8 and CBS 12.6. The
season-to-date averages are: NBC 16.2, ABC 13.8, CBS 13.5.
   All three networks lost viewers on Easter Sunday. The
three-network share, or percentage of the viewing audience, is an
average 71 for the season. On Sunday it was 67, and 69 for the week.
   CBS won the night with ``60 Minutes'' and ``Murder, She Wrote''
leading into ``The Woman He Loved,'' the story of King Edward
VIII's abdication to marry Wallis Warfield Simpson, an American
divorcee. The movie, starring Jane Seymour and Anthony Andrews, had
a rating of 14.5 and a 25 share and ranked 27th.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   NBC launched the two-part ``The Fortunate Pilgrim,'' starring
Sophia Loren as matriarch of an immigrant family, but got only a
13.1 and 22 share to rank 40th out of 73.
   NBC began the evening badly with a repeat of an Andy Williams
special that got a measly 4.2 rating and 9 share and was the
lowest-rated prime-time network show of the week. That, NBC said,
provided a poor lead-in for a repeat ``Family Ties,'' which landed
in the bottom 10, perhaps the worst performances ever for the
formerly top-10 show.
   The highest-rated made-for-TV movie was last Monday's ``Addicted
to His Love'' on ABC, which was 10th. On Sunday, ABC came in for
the night with the theatrical film ``Superman II.''
   The top-rated shows of the week were: ``The Cosby Show'' NBC,
with a 25.1 rating and a 42 share, ``A Different World'' NBC,
``Cheers'' NBC, ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC, ``Golden Girls'' NBC,
``ALF'' NBC, ``The Wonder Years'' ABC, ``Matlock'' NBC, ``Growing
Pains'' ABC and ``Addicted to His Love'' ABC.
   NBC won in prime-time but continued in third place in news. The
``CBS Evening News'' was still No. 1 with a rating of 10.5 and a 21
share. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had a 10.3 and 20. ``NBC
Nightly News'' had 9.0 and 18.
   NBC analysts say they are still baffled by the fall of their
newscast to third place, despite research they say shows Tom Brokaw
as the most popular of the three network anchors.
   In prime time, though, NBC was cheered by ``In the Heat of the
Night,'' a series based on the movie of the same name, which ranked
11th and equaled the 28 share of its premiere. Also, ``Miami Vice''
won its time period for the second time this season when it was
moved to 10 p.m. EST last Friday.
   Saturday NCAA basketball playoffs on CBS ranked 38th, but
apparently gave a boost to ``West 57th,'' which had a 20 share and
wasn't among the bottom 10 for a change. NBC won the night with
repeats.
   The lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``Family Ties,''
``Frank's Place,'' ``Ohara,'' ``Dolly!'' ``My Sister Sam,''
``Hotel,'' ``Buck James,'' ``More Than a Game,'' ``Trial and
Error'' and ``Andy Williams and the NBC Kids.''
  
</TEXT>
