<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AmericansArrested     04-05 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Americans Arrested,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Governments Arrest Eight Americans a Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans abroad were arrested at a rate of
eight per day last year, more than 40 percent of them on narcotics
charges, the State Department said Tuesday.
   In an annual report designed to frighten tourists thinking of
taking drugs on vacation, the department said: ``As we approach the
busy travel season, many Americans are getting ready for that long
awaited trip abroad. For some, the trip will become a nightmare.''
   ``Those Americans who assume there is no real danger in buying
or carrying just a `small' amount of drugs on their overseas trip
may be in for a very unpleasant surprise,'' the report said.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the seriousness
of the problem was underscoreourt's conviction and
six-year jail sentence Tuesday of Conan Owen, a 23-year-od by a Spanish
cld
Virginia photographer who said he unwittingly brought cocaine into
Spain in an acquaintance's suitcase.
   The Justice Department has said it believes in Owen's innocence
and the report said ``travelers should be particularly wary of
persons who ask them to carry a package or drive a car across a
border. They might unknowingly become narcotics traffickers.''
   Last year, 3,041 Americans were arrested abroad, 41 percent of
them on drug-related charges. It was a 10eral
penitentiaries in Oakdale, La. and Atlanta, Ga., the report said.
   The largest number of inmate mistreatment complaints from
Americans abroad came from the inmates of the San Luis Rio Colorado
prison in northern Mexico.
   About one-fourth of the 164 Americans arrested in the area
covered by the consulate in Hermosillo, Mexico, complained of
mistreatment and ``U.S. officials found such reports credible and
made a vigorous formal protest in August,'' the report said.
   Since then, no reports of mistreatment at that prison have been
received, the report said.
   The number of American incarcerated in Saudi Arabia declined,
mostly because that country has become more lenient toward
foreigners accused of breaking such Islamic laws as possession of
alcoholic beverages.
   People found guilty of having liquor are generally deported a
few days after arrest, rather than sentenced to jail terms, the
report said.
   In honor of the 60th birthday of the King of Thailand, several
American were freed from prison last year and a few others had
their sentences reduced. Still, 30 Americans remained in Thai
prisons at the end of the year.
   The United States spent more than $46,000 for medical assistance
and food for U.S. prisoners. About $20,000 of this was spent in
Thailand ``where prison conditions are substandard,'' the report
said.
</TEXT>
