<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Panama-Troops     04-05 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Troops,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter Units Leave U.S. for Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVIS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 members of
the 7th Infantry Division left for Panama on Tuesday to bolster
protection for U.S. citizens and other interests.
   The unit from Fort Ord arrived at this sprawling Air Force base
45 miles northeast of San Francisco late Monday, and lumbering C-5A
transports began lifting off about 11:30 a.m. today.
   Heading south with them are 26 aircraft of the Army's most
effective helicopter inventory: 15 UH-60 Blackhawk utility
helicopters; seven rocket-and-missile-ready Cobra attack gunships,
and four OH-58 Kiowa observation helicopters.
   ``I'm looking forward to going. This is what we've trained for.
We're just going to do out job,'' said maintenance commander Capt.
Louise Morgan, 31, of Bovey, Minn., shortly before the units began
leaving.
   She said the only grumbling she'd heard was from troops who had
to stay behind at Fort Ord.
   ``The other troops are excited. I don't think anyone is worried
... It's always in the back of your mind that you're going,'' she
said.
   Another maintenance worker, 1st Sgt. Ed Luna, agreed the unit
was prepared for anything. ``If we get caught in the middle (of
combat) we'll just have to do what we have to do ... we're ready,''
said Luna, 45, of Honolulu.
   The United States has been using economic sanctions in an effort
to oust Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who has been
indicted for drug trafficking. Some U.S. citizens in Panama have
reported being harassed during a six-week financial crisis there.
   The deployment comes only days after fellow soldiers returned
from emergency deployment to Honduras, where the administration
said Nicaraguan Sandinistas had established a threat after crossing
the border.
   The Fort Ord troopers are joining some 1,100 other soldiers and
Marines heading for Panama. No word was given on how long the new
troops can be expected to remain in Panama.
</TEXT>
