<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-US     04-05 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Asks Aid in Return for MIA Accounting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Vietnames official said Tuesday
the United States should help rebuild this country if it wants a
full accounting of 1,700 Americans still listed as missing 13 years
after the war's end.
   Nguyen Dy Nien, a deputy foreign minister, made the comment the
day before Vietnam was to turn over what it says are the remains of
27 missing Americans, its largest delivery so far.
   He repeated charges that Washington, by merely encouraging
private aid to Vietnam, has not done its part under an agreement
reached in August between U.S. envoy John W. Vessey and Vietnam's
foreign minister, Nguyen Co Thach.
   The agreement calls for Vietnam to end a long deadlock on
accounting for Americans missing in the war, which ended in April
1975, and the United States to address Vietnam's own humanitarian
concerns.
   Washington has sent investigative medical teams to Vietnam and
encouraged private aid, but has not lifted an embargo on official
aid imposed to protest Vietnam's decade-long occupation of
neighboring Cambodia.
   ``We don't care what the (private groups) are doing ... We think
the government should participate,'' Nien said. ``It must show its
concern, its direct commitment.''
   He spoke to Sen. Larry Pressler, a South Dakota Republican who
arrived Tuesday to discuss issues including the fates of 1,767
Americans still officially missing in action. Pressler is a member
of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   Nien said the U.S. government has done nothing since the war
ended to help Vietnam recover from American bombing that destroyed
thousands of schools, and has not aided Vietnam's disabled veterans
or the half-million orphans created by the conflict.
   He said it was ``unfortunate that (the agreement) was not fully
implemented and it sometimes was wrongly interpreted. Both sides
recognized the humanitarian issues of each other and both must be
resolved.''
   Wednesday's delivery is the fourth since the Vessey agreement.
   If U.S. Army laboratories identify the 27 sets of remains, it
would mean substantial progress because Vietnam has repatriated
only 152 confirmed remains. The largest previous transfer _ Aug.
14, 1985 _ involved 26 remains, and at least 24 were confirmed.
   Pressler told Nien his constituents often say they believe Hanoi
returns the remains gradually and still holds some living American
prisoners. Nien called the charges ``unthinkable.''
   Nguyen Can, head of the special Vietnamese office on resolving
the MIA issue, denied charges that the skeletal remains of U.S. Air
Force pilot Edwin B. Tucker were kept for years at a medical school
or hospital before being returned to the United States on Nov. 25.
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution has reported that Tucker's
remains were used as a teaching tool. He was shot down over the
northern city of Hon Gai in April 1967.
   Can, deputy director of the Foreign Ministry's North American
affairs department, told The Associated Press the charge has
``aroused indignation on the part of our people and proves there is
no good will on the part of the United States.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
