<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Immigration     04-05 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Immigration,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Won't Stay Order to Broaden Amnesty Standards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Tuesday refused to stay his
order that the Reagan administration broaden its standard for
determining whether certain illegal aliens qualify for amnesty
under the 1986 immigration law.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin denied the Justice
Department's motion for a stay pending appeal of his ruling that
overturned a regulation for processing amnesty requests from aliens
who had legally entered the country but overstayed tourist or
student visas.
   The regulation, which Sporkin said violated the plain language
of the immigration law, required that the illegal status of
non-immigrant aliens be known to the Immigration and Naturalization
Service as of Jan. 1, 1982 for them to qualify for amnesty.
   Sporkin said the law merely required that any federal agency
have documentation, such as a tax or Social Security form, from
which officials could conclude an alien's status was illegal as of
that date.
   Groups that counsel illegal aliens who brought the suit
estimated that as many as 50,000 non-immigrant aliens were being
denied legalization under the disputed regulations.
   More than 1 million illegal aliens have sought naturalization
under the amnesty program that expires May 4. Congress is
considering legislation to extend the deadline by six months.
   Sporkin, who had issued a preliminary injunction last week, made
the ruling permanent.
</TEXT>
