<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0718,0823</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arabs Killed in Ninth Infiltration Effort Since November</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 1 graf and SUBS 11-14 ``An army ... '' with 6
grafs to make clear that two incidents may not be connected and ADD
another claim of responsibility.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers fired at ``suspicious shadows''
Tuesday in south Lebanon and fought Palestinian guerrillas trying
to cross the border, killing two, the army said. Four Israelis were
reported wounded.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers fired rubber bullets at protesters,
putting out the left eye of a 16-year-old Palestinian, the army
said. It was among the few violent incidents in a relatively quiet
day in the occupied West Bank and Gaza, where an Arab rebellion
began Dec. 8.
   Forty-one high school students about to be drafted wrote Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin saying they would would ``not take part in
acts of oppression and occupation in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.'' The number writing such letters now stands at 107.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz went to Jordan and Syria
promoting the U.S. peace plan. He got an inconclusive response from
King Hussein of Jordan, whose approval is considered essential.
   The attempted penetration Tuesday was the ninth infiltration
effort since Nov. 25, when a guerrilla in a hang glider flew into
Israel from Lebanon and killed six soldiers before being shot to
death.
   That attack was thought to have made the Israeli army seem
vulnerable, and violence in the occupied territories began two
weeks later. At least 138 Arabs and an Israeli soldier have been
killed during the 4-month-old rebellion in the lands Israel
captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said violence in the West Bank
and Gaza has emboldened guerrillas.
   ``The fact that the events in the territories are the focus of
world attention obligates them ... to prove again that terrorism
has to be the main tool for achieving political goals,'' he said on
army radio.
   ``They've increased their attempts, and certainly they will
continue to try as often as possible to attack Israeli targets.''
   Israel radio said Fatah, the main Palestine Liberation
Organization guerrilla group led by PLO chief Yasser Arafat, took
responsibility in a statement at Sidon in south Lebanon. A
anonymous telephone caller made the claim to a journalist in Sidon
but Fatah's Beirut office denied knowledge of such a claim.
   Another guerrilla group, the pro-Syrian Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, claimed responsibility in a typewritten
statement distributed in Sidon. It said the purpose was to
emphasize ``rejection of the imperialist plans carried by Shultz.''
   An army spokesman said troopers saw ``suspicious shadows'' early
Tuesday at the edge of Israel's self-declared ``security zone,'' an
area just north of the border with Lebanon that varies in depth
from six to 10 miles. It is patrolled by Israeli troops and a
surrogate militia called the South Lebanon Army.
   The soldiers fired, the shadows disappeared, and blood and
abandoned weapons were found on the ground in the area, he said.
   Several hours later, soldiers encountered guerrillas within a
mile of Israel's border north of the Kfar Yuval farming settlement
and exchanged fire with them, according to the army report.
   It said the Palestinians were armed with assault rifles, a
rocket-propelled grenade launcher and about a dozen grenades.
   Army spokesmen said the encounters took place more than two
miles apart and it was not clear whether they were related.
   ``The soldiers seized positions,'' a unit commander identified
only as Col. Motti said on Israel radio. ``We were 10 meters apart.
We spoke to them, called upon them to surrender. They responded
with fire.
   ``An additional force was positioned behind the terrorists. At
5:30 a.m., the commander of the region ordered the soldiers to
storm the guerrillas.''
   Army spokesmen did not say how many guerrillas there were or
whether any were captured or escaped.
   Helicopters and armored vehicles searched the area after the
battle, the radio said, indicating the army thought some
Palestinians may have escaped.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers fired rubber bullets at protesters
in the Nuseret refugee camp, and Abu Hajad Ramzi lost his left eye,
said Ilana Zeev, spokeswoman at Barzilai Hospital in Ashkelon, an
Israeli coastal city.
   An Israeli car was set afire after the driver, a Jewish settler
from Kiryat Arba in the West Bank, got lost in Gaza and wandered
into the strip's Deir al Balah refugee camp, Israel radio said. It
said the driver fired shots into the air and ran with his passenger
to a nearby military post.
   Soldiers destroyed four homes of Palestinians suspected of
inciting protests, three in the northern West Bank village of El
Yamun and one in Gaza City, army and Arab reports said.
</TEXT>
