<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NaturalGas     04-05 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Natural Gas,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeowners Would Pay More for Natural Gas if Pipeline Policy
Changed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residential natural gas rates will increase if
interstate pipelines are permitted to serve large industrial users
directly, a group of gas distribution companies and others said
Tuesday.
   An industry organization, the Process Gas Consumer Group,
disputed the claim.
   The distribution group, led by Southern California Gas Co. and
Associated Gas Distributors, an East Coast trade association,
presented the summary of a study of 14 unidentified gas
distribution companies.
   The summary said that if all industrial customers on 13 of these
systems who could be served directly by interstate pipelines were
to shift to the pipelines, rates to other customers would have to
rise by 1 percent to 21 percent. The median rate increase was 5.7
percent.
   The increases would occur because the fixed cost of the
distribution system would be spread over a smaller number of
customers. An earlier study by the Consumer Federation of America
estimated that distribution companies could lose $2 billion in
revenues if industrial customers could switch to direct service by
the interstate pipelines.
   There are only a few such ``direct service'' customers now,
often a factory that years ago chose to locate itself in an
isolated area directly on a pipeline route, or was already there
when the pipeline was built.
   The distribution group held a news conference to call attention
to its support of a bill introduced last month by Rep. Edward
Markey, D-Mass. He wants to prevent the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission from approving so-called ``bypass'' service over the
objections of state regulators.
   A Markey aide, Cathy Hurwit, said he introduced the bill because
``when large customers can get off the system and come back on at a
later date, you do have some concerns that the remaining customers
are paying more than their fair share.''
   Rep. Philip Sharp, D-Ind., chairman of the subcommittee with
jurisdiction over the bill, has said he does not want to deal with
natural gas issues this year. Nonetheless, Rufus McKinney, lobbyist
for Southern California Gas, said he was optimistic that backers
could at least win hearings on the issue.
   Jan Vlcek, counsel to the Process Gas Consumer Group, said his
group opposed the Markey bill because, ``There isn't a great deal
of confidence in public service commissions in a lot of states'' to
protect industry, who, he said, often is paying more more than its
share of distribution company costs.
   ``This is cast as industry vs. residential customers. I dispute
that. There's a third party in these transactions, the shareholders
of the distribution company,'' who, Vlcek said, were earning in
some cases 16 percent to 17 percent on their investment.
</TEXT>
