<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     04-05 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Plans Fund-Raisers As Campaign Nears Giving Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush plans fund-raising
stops in Texas, Florida and New York during the next week even
though his well-heeled campaign is nearing the federal limit on
contributions, aides said Tuesday.
   Bush is close to collecting the maximum allowed by federal law
for spending on primary campaigns and may reach that level in
another few days, Bush aides said. He would be the first 1988
candidate to do so.
   Once the cap is reached, the candidate cannot raise any more
money for his campaign under federal election law. The law permits
$27 million to be raised and spent for direct campaign expenses but
exempts from the limit legal and accounting costs.
   The campaign had set a goal of $33 million.
   ``Once you get to the `max,' that's it, you can't pull in any
more dollars,'' said Bush spokesman Peter Teeley.
   However, Teeley said, ``we could raise money for other
candidates, we could raise money for the party or state
organizations.''
   Exactly what would be done with money that comes in after the
limit is reached hasn't been decided, the spokesman indicated.
However, the campaign must budget carefully from now on to avoid
spending over the $27 million cap.
   With more than four months to go to the GOP convention, Bush has
the Republican nomination virtually in the bag. His only major
rival, Sen. Bob Dole, withdrew a week ago, although former
television minister Pat Robertson technically is still a candidate.
   Bush has won 841 delegates so far of the 1139 needed for
nomination.
   Bush was spending most of this week in Washington, ``cleaning up
a lot of paperwork... catching up,'' Teeley said. ``And he'll be
thinking of the future.''
   The vice president flies to Texas on Friday for a fund-raising
event in Fort Worth, then goes to Florida, where he will make
appearances in St. Petersburg and Miami.
   He plans to spend Monday through Wednesday in New York,
including stops in Schenectady, Syracuse, Buffalo, Elmira and
Manhattan. The New York primary is April 19.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
