<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     04-05 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-South Africa,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Warns Anti-Apartheid Activists of Possible South African Hit
Teams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid activists in the United States
say they have been warned by the FBI they might be targeted by
South African government hit teams.
   The warnings have taken on special importance in the face of
last week's assassination in Paris of Dulcie September, a
representative of the African National Congress which is fighting
to topple the white minority South African government, the
activists say.
   The ANC blamed the South African government for Ms. September's
shooting death but South Africa denied the allegation. Police
sources in Paris said the killing appeared to be the work of a
professional, and French President Francois Mitterrand said he
would ask South African authorities about the attack.
   The Washington representative of the ANC, Dumi Matabani, said he
was contacted last September by FBI agents who told him they ``had
a strong suspicion that a South African hit squad'' might be in the
United States.
   ``They said they would try and stop it, and told me to be
careful,'' Matabani said. The FBI did not offer any protection but
``they told me that if I was followed, I should take the car number
and call them,'' Matabani said.
   An ANC representative in New York, Themba Ntinga, said his
office had also been warned by the FBI.
   Nomonde Ngubo, a South African employee of the United Mine
Workers in Washington and an anti-apartheid activist, said she too
had been contacted by the FBI several times in recent months.
   Ngubo said the FBI agent had declined to discuss anything on the
phone, and that her lawyer would probably be setting up an
appointment soon for her to meet with representatives of the agency.
   A spokesman for the FBI, Gregory Jones, declined to comment
about the activists' claims. But he added that ``any information
that comes to the FBI's attention about possible loss of life or
violence, we're obliged to pass on to the interested party.''
   In recent months South Africa has increased its attacks against
guerrillas of the ANC, mounting a cross-border raid into Botswana
last week and killing four people. Over the past few years ANC
representatives in Brussels, Mozambique and Zimbabwe have been
targeted for violent attacks.
</TEXT>
