<1ST_LINE>r w AM-D'Amato-Carlucci     04-05 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-D'Amato-Carlucci,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Denies He Called Defense Secretary, Joint Chiefs Cowards</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci charged that
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato called him and the Joint Chiefs of Staff
``cowards'' for not doing more to oust Panamanian strongman Manuel
Antonio Noriega, but the New York Republican said Tuesday he didn't
phrase it that way.
   ``I did not call Carlucci a coward,'' D'Amato said through a
spokeswoman. ``My recollection of the conversation was that (I
said) the inaction would be perceived as cowardly.''
   Carlucci made the allegations in a letter to D'Amato that
followed an emotional telephone conversation the two had last week.
After learning D'Amato had denied the alleged name-calling, Defense
Department spokesman Col. Arnold Williams said, ``I think the
letter probably speaks for itself.''
   In the phone call, D'Amato had complained that the defense
secretary was willing to send 3,200 soldiers to Honduras but would
not send a senior military officer to Panama to tell Noriega to
leave, said Jack Kinnicutt, a spokesman for D'Amato.
   The New York senator was disturbed that the U.S. government had
sent Deputy Assistant Secretary of State William Walker to Panama
on March 21 to speak to Noriega, Kinnicutt said.
   ``You don't send a deputy assist secretary of state to ask him
if he's going to kindly leave,'' D'Amato said at a news conference
Tuesday. ``That's not the kind of messenger or message that Noriega
understands.''
   Writing to D'Amato, Carlucci said he had ``been reflecting on
your emotion-charged telephone call'' during which, he said,``you
charged that I and the Joint Chiefs of Staff are `cowards' and that
we are `supporting a drug dealer.'
   ``I hope you can indicate to me that you, in fact, did not mean
(the charges) as stated,'' Carlucci said.
   Carlucci's letter did not address the substance of D'Amato's
original complaint.
   At the news conference, D'Amato released a letter he sent to
Carlucci in which he said, ``I certainly do not believe that the
Joint Chiefs of Staff are cowards. There is not doubt, however,
that the lack of U.S. action in Panama has made us appear weak in
many people's eyes.''
   D'Amato said he told Carlucci on the phone: ``We are being
perceived as cowards, lacking the resolve to deal with a drug
dealers, a tinhorn drug dealer by the name of Noriega. It's not a
question of questioning anybody's particular manhood or the
patriotism of the Joint Chiefs.''
   D'Amato called on the U.S. government to ask for Noriega's
extradition, and said the use of military force may be necessary to
ensure his ouster.
   ``I am not in a position to say what kind of action with
specificity should be taken but I'll certainly tell you this,'' he
said.
   ``If it's the use of force to remove a drug-dealing dictator who
poses a threat to the United States, to our security, to the canal,
why, then I think we have to use all measures, including force, to
bring about his removal.''
</TEXT>
