<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Challenger,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Unknown Challenges Kennedy, Says Senator's Out of Touch</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little-known Massachusetts Republican went to
one of the Kennedy family's early strongholds Tuesday to formally
launch a challenge to the re-election of U.S. Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy.
   Joseph Malone, the 33-year-old former executive director of the
Massachusetts Republican Party, made his announcement in front of
the North End home of another Massachusetts long-shot: Paul Revere.
   The heavily Catholic neighborhood first went for a Kennedy in
152, when John F. Kennedy upset Henry Cabot Lodge in a senatorial
election.
   Malone invoked his Italian heritage and the ethnic diversity of
Massachusetts as he launched his campaign. The Waltham native and
1978 Harvard graduate also invoked the name of Revere, who fought
for ``freedom from unfair taxation, and freedom from an overly
intrusive government.''
   Kennedy, Malone said, represents an older, out-of-date
generation in American politics that solves problems by spending
money.
   Malone said his candidacy would highlight, ``not the `me'
generation, the `we' generation. It's a generation that believes in
the power of the individual, not the power of an ever-expanding
government. It's a generation that seeks real economic opportunity,
not a government jobs program.''
   Malone is a close ally of the last Republican to challenge
Kennedy, Ray Shamie, the retired Walpole businessman who is
currently chairman of the Republican State Committee. Shamie was
among the 30 supporters standing behind Malone and holding a green
campaign sign.
   Malone ran Shamie's 1982 run against Kennedy and another losing
bid by Shamie against John Kerry in 1984.
   Shamie acknowledged that Malone is an extreme long shot against
the veteran senator who has held office since 1962. But he said,
``politics is the most unpredictable business I've been in.''
</TEXT>
