<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--Reagan-Agriculture     04-05 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Reagan-Agriculture,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Signs Food-for-Poor Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Tuesday signed
legislation that gives the Agriculture Department greater leeway to
distribute surplus food commodities to poor nations.
   Under the amendments to the Agriculture Act of 1949, Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng can now measure how much foodstuffs will be
sent against available supplies, rather than having to meet a
strict quota set forth in law.
   The law allows Lyng to disburse these foodstuffs, ``subject to
the availability of commodities.''
   The legislation also requires the secretary to make private
voluntary organizations, in addition to agencies of foreign
governments, eligible to take part in the distribution of surplus
food commodities.
   It imposes for the first time a 45-day deadline for the Agency
for International Development to approve surplus food shipments.
And it extends until 1990 a farmer-to-farmer program in which
American farmers travel to foreign countries to give technical
assistance.
</TEXT>
