<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignAgenda     04-05 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Agenda,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Media Political Role Overrated, Journalists Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The role of the news media in setting the
agenda for the 1988 presidential campaign is overrated, three
leading journalists suggested Tuesday.
   ``I don't think I'm the finger of God every night on the NBC
Nightly News,'' said anchorman Tom Brokaw during a panel discussion
sponsored by the Gannett Center for Media Studies.
   ``I don't think it's so much the media setting the agenda,''
said Louis D. Boccardi, president of The Associated Press ``as it
is the media having become almost the centerpiece of the process.''
   ``The question is, is anyone setting the agenda,'' said Nancy
Hicks Maynard, vice president of the Oakland, Calif., Tribune. ``If
it is the press, it certainly isn't because of the campaign
coverage.''
   Boccardi said the media have done well covering campaign issues,
but he said there also is a need for ``horse race'' coverage,
stories on who is winning where.
   ``I don't think we ought to particularly apologize for trying to
track and keeping our eyes and hopefully keeping the audience's eye
on where the race is going,'' he said.
   Brokaw said voters set an agenda based on information from a
wide variety of sources including paid political advertising and
the political climate.
   The NBC anchorman said one of the most striking aspects of the
campaign was ``the continuing strength of Ronald Reagan in most
regions of the country.''
   Boccardi said Jesse Jackson has ``established himself now as a
credible candidate'' and that has brought him ``more intensive
coverage.''
   ``He's hotter now than he was a few weeks ago,'' said Boccardi.
</TEXT>
