<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     04-05 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lehder's Chef Testifies Of Life On Norman's Cay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cook who worked for Carlos Lehder
Rivas in the Bahamas testified Tuesday that he was hired by a
reputed leader of the Medellin cocaine cartel.
   Lehder, 38, and a co-defendant are on trial in federal court on
charges of conspiring to smuggle some 3.3 tons of cocaine into the
United States from Colombia via Norman's Cay in the Bahamas from
1978 to 1980.
   Cook Keith Goldsworthy, 32, testified Jorge Ochoa, identified by
U.S. prosecutors along with Lehder and others as being a leader of
the violent cartel responsible for most of the cocaine shipped into
the United States, hired him and his wife to go to Norman's Cay as
Lehder's chef in 1980.
   Goldsworthy said he cooked for nine or 10 people, taking
Lehder's eight guards their lunches at outposts on the island. He
said everyone ate supper at the same house.
   He also described a raid on Norman's Cay in November 1980. He
said he was told the night before that the raid would occur and was
told he should tell police he was a tourist. He said others on the
island went into hiding.
   He also testified that Norman's Cay guards either carried
weapons or kept them in their cars. He also said Lehder was always
with one of his two bodyguards.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise.
   Co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, is charged with only being a
member of the smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
