<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1945EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AfghanEvacuation     04-05 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan Evacuation,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Permit Would Allow Afghan Communists to Evacuate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER C. PUTNAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is issuing evacuation permits
for Afghan Communist Party and government officials to use if they
must flee their country after a Soviet troop withdrawal, a human
rights organization said Tuesday.
   The New York-based group, Freedom House, released a copy of a
blank 3-by-5-inch pass that it said was among 20 captured by Afghan
Moslem guerrillas, who have battled the Afghan government and
Soviet troops since 1979.
   Ludmilla Thorne of Freedom House said the United States issued
similar passes to South Vietnamese government officials when they
were evacuated by air from Saigon in 1975 as the South Vietnamese
capital fell to the communists.
   The copy of the Russian-language Afghan permit bears the emblem
of a red star with a hammer and sickle and the words ``Permit for
Special Evacuation.''
   After the word ``Comrade,'' there is a blank line for the name
of the card holder, followed by ``is granted the right for special
evacuation by air and land transport, with the retention of all
housing and food privileges after arrival at the new site.''
   That is followed by a place for the signature of an ``authorized
person'' and the date. The stamp of the Soviet Embassy in
Afghanistan appears at the bottom.
   On the reverse side instructions in Pushtu, the Afghan language,
inform the bearer that he can bring only one suitcase and no
weapons or food.
   A map of Kabul attached to the document pinpoints two evacuation
points, one near the Soviet Embassy.
   Earlier reports from South Asia have spoken of the existence of
such evacuation passes in Afghanistan.
   The Soviet Union has reportedly begun preparations to remove the
first of its 115,000 soldiers from Afghanistan despite an impasse
in United Nations-sponsored peace negotiations in Geneva.
   Those talks began this year, but Ms. Thorne said the permit
obtained by Freedom House was found in October in the briefcase of
an Afghan intelligence officer who was attacked by Afghan
guerrillas.
   She said it could not be learned when the permits were first
printed or how many had been prepared.
   The evacuees' destination was not specified on the permit, but
Ms. Thorne said it was presumed they would be taken to the U.S.S.R.
if the Soviet withdrawal led to the downfall of the communist
government in Kabul.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
