<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TelevisionStudy     04-05 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Television Study,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV May Help Racial Understanding, Howard Beach Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study at one New York City high school found
that television may help break down racial and ethnic stereotypes,
researchers said Tuesday.
   The study was conducted at a high school in the Howard Beach
section of Queens, which gained national attention as the site of a
racially motivated killing in 1986.
   ``The good news is that the kids like the ethnic characters on
television and they identify with them,'' said Robert Lichter, a
political scientist who conducted the study for the Center for
Media and Public Affairs. ``The bad news is that they like the bad
characters too.''
   The survey found that black characters are the most popular on
television, and that Cliff Huxtable, portrayed by Bill Cosby in
``The Cosby Show,'' is the most popular character of all.
   Both Italian-American students and non-Italians said that
Italian characters such as Tony Micelli on ``Who's the Boss?'' were
most typical of their ethnic group.
   Jewish students responded the least favorably to ethnic
characters across the board, but also were the least likely to view
them as realistic portrayals.
   In general, the study found that the more students liked
television characters, the more likely they were to regard them as
typical of their racial or ethnic group.
   Huxtable was one exception: although black students
overwhelmingly regarded him as a typical black man, non-blacks were
evenly split on whether he was typical.
   The choice of John Adams High School in Howard Beach was
coincidental, Lichter said. He said he and his wife, sociologist
Linda Lichter, conducted their research several weeks before the
1986 incident in which a group of white youths attacked three black
men, one of whom died.
   The study was co-sponsored by the American Jewish Committee's
Institute for American Pluralism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
