<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NevadaDrought     04-05 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nevada Drought,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dust Bowl Conditions Developing In Nevada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Above-average temperatures and
below-average rainfall and snowpack are producing conditions in
Nevada reminiscent of the dust bowl weather of the 1930s, state
climatologist John James says.
   James, chairman of a newly formed governor's committee on
drought, commented Tuesday as the panel met here to review weather
information and discuss possible water conservation steps.
   James said Western Nevada had the driest February and March on
record and has had only .02 inch of rain in more than 2{ months.
   National Weather Service representatives told the committee that
snowpack in the Sierra Nevadas is about 25-40 percent of normal and
reservoirs in the in northern Nevada and eastern California are at
only half their average levels.
   Temperatures have run above normal in 12 of the past 14 months
in Nevada, James said, adding that such a pattern of high
temperatures and lack of precipitation happened only once before in
the state _ during the 1930s.
   State Engineer Pete Morros, who oversees Nevada's groundwater
resources, said he already has received reports of some shallow
household wells in the Reno area and elsewhere starting to dry up.
</TEXT>
