<2ND_LINE>AM-Central America-Drugs, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0708,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haitian Official Tried To Import Cocaine Into U.S., Congress Told</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with later testiony. Picks up
into 3rd graf pvs, bgng: Law enforcement</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Haitian Gen. Jean-Claude Paul tried to import
some 900 pounds of cocaine into the United States in a 1986 deal
which went awry, a Cuban-American who was involved in the plan told
Congress on Tuesday.
   Paul commands the most feared Army unit in Haiti and is
considered one of the leaders of the troubled Caribbean nation,
according to testimony from Osvaldo Quintana to the Senate Foreign
Relations subcommittee on terrorism and narcotics.
   Quintana's testimony in heavily accented English was part of the
panel's ongoing investigation of drug smuggling from Latin America.
   Earlier Tuesday, a convicted marijuana dealer told the
subcommittee that U.S. law enforcement officials were paid to look
the other way while huge amounts of marijuana were shipped to the
United States from Colombia.
   Quintana, a native of Cuba who came to the United States in
1967, had headed Ocean Seafood International, a Miami-based
company. He detailed how he became involved with Paul two years ago
through a business deal offered by Paul's wife, Marie Marielle
Delinois.
   She originally interested Quintana through an offer to sell him
seafood, Quintana testified, but once he went to Haiti to
investigate the deal, it turned into a plan to sent 412 kilograms
(about 906 pounds) of cocaine into the United States through Miami.
   The deal fell through when the people hired to fly the cocaine
from Paul's Haitian farm to Miami stole the drugs, Quintana said.
Paul's henchmen have tried twice to kill him since then, including
one attempt that occurred near the Miami offices of the Drug
Enforcement Administration, Quintana said.
   Quintana is now under DEA protection and Paul has been indicted
for conspiracy in the case. Also indicted March 10 in the same case
was his brother, Antonio, and Mrs. Delinois.
   Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., chairman of the subcommittee, noted
that Quintana's testimony shows ``yet another country ... polluting
the streets of our country'' with drugs. Previous testimony before
the subcommittee has centered on Central and South American nations.
   Earlier, Michael P. Vogel testified that marijuana was moved
aboard planes as large as a DC-6, along with shrimp boats and _ on
one occasion in 1983 _ a barge which carried 150 tons of the drug
into a Louisiana port.
   Law enforcement officials were paid off ``when it had to be
done,'' Vogel said. Usually, they were given ``$50,000 or $60,000
to do nothing,'' he said. ``They were paid to look the other way.''
   Vogel did not name any of the officials he said received
payments.
   On one occasion in 1979 or 1980, Vogel said, he and several
other members of his drug smuggling organization met in Panama with
Omar Torrijos, then that nation's leader, and Manual Noriega, to
discuss using a small island off the Panamanian coast for
transshipping drugs.
   Torrijos was killed in a 1981 plane crash and eventually was
succeeded by Noriega, who has been charged in Florida with
involvement in the drug trade. Noriega has denied the charges and
is resisting U.S. efforts to push him out of office.
   The two Panamanians ``were being extremely greedy,'' said Vogel,
since they were seeking payoffs of up to $100,000 per planeload of
drugs.
   Vogel, 37, pleaded guilty in 1986 to charges arising from his
14-year career as a drug smuggler. He told the subcommittee he is
now serving a 12{-year prison term.
   Vogel, a native of Detroit, said he became involved in the drug
business while he was a student at the University of Miami. He
brokered a sale for a friend and ``I made a good amount of money
and lo and behold, I was off and running.''
   Vogel told the committee he only dealt in marijuana because ``I
have moral problems with cocaine.''
   Vogel declined to say how much money he had personally made from
his drug business, but said the organizations in which he was
involved made hundreds of millions of dollars.
   For example, the barge load of marijuana was worth $90 million,
and his organization only paid $30 million for the drug, meaning a
$60 million profit, Vogel said.
   Vogel described one occasion in 1979 or 1980 in which he said a
plane loaded with marijuana was flying from Indiana to Florida, but
had to turn back because the destination was fogged in. The plane's
operators dumped their cargo _ bales of marijuana _ by pushing them
out the door of the plane while flying over northern Georgia in the
middle of the night.
   The emergency plan had been to dump the drugs in the the
Chattahoochee National Forest in northern Georgia, but instead,
Vogel said, he later was told that some of the bales had fallen on
the streets of a nearby town. Vogel said he did not know either the
name of the town or the exact date of the incident.
   Vogel said his organization developed detailed, elaborate
methods of evading U.S. efforts to halt the drug trade.
   Those tactics included intelligence collection and electronic
countermeasures, he said. In addition, smugglers obtained the
frequencies used by U.S. officials for communications, and at one
point, they even had the frequency of Air Force One, the
president's plane.
</TEXT>
