<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 2013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RecreationCommission     04-05 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Recreation Commission,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closed Meetings of Recreation Commission Violated Law, GAO Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential advisory commission on
recreation held 34 closed meetings in violation of the law,
congressional investigators said in a report released Tuesday.
   However, the General Accounting Office report released by Rep.
Don Young, R-Alaska, also concluded that the violation ``may not
have had a material impact on the commission's operations and its
final report and recommendations.''
   The commission chairman said he never realized so many minor
get-togethers like informal lunches would count as ``meetings.''
   The 15-member group in question, the President's Commission on
Americans Outdoors, was organized in September 1985 under an
executive order issued by President Reagan and made its report in
December 1986.
   The GAO report appeared to uphold many complaints by a group
opposed to the commission's recommendations, the National Inholders
Association. An ``inholder'' is an owner of private property
surrounded by public land, such as the owner of a home in a
national park.
   A lawsuit filed by the group to overturn the report got nowhere
when a judge ruled that it could not sue because it had failed to
protest when the alleged violations were occuring.
   The commission was formed as a government advisory committee,
which meant that it had to hold its meetings in public with a
15-day notice, a designated federal official had to attend each
meeting and detailed minutes had to be kept. Permission had to be
sought from the host agency head to close a meeting, and reasons
for closing it had to be submitted.
   ``The (Interior) department committee management officer thought
that responsibility for (the act's) requirements was being handled
by the commission, but commission officials were unaware that such
a transfer of responsibility had occured,'' the GAO report said.
   As a result, and despite an extensive campaign to generate
public advice, the commission published notices for only 18 of its
60 meetings, and only 10 were published in time; proper procedures
for closing 34 of the 60 meetings were not followed; minutes were
kept for only 27 of 60 meetings and the department employee
designated to attend commission meetings attended only 11.
   Lamar Alexander, a former governor of Tennessee who was chairman
of the commission, said in written comments: ``I did not ever
imagine that a `meeting' could be a lunch among a few of the
commission members where no decisions were reached or a staff
working session which some commission memebrs briefly attended. If
such an unusual definition of `meeting' is what Congress really
intended, then perhaps GAO officials could visit commissions like
ours when they begin and say that.''
   Rick Ventura, assistant secretary of Interior for policy, budget
and administration, wrote that the department was reviewing its
procedures and would make sure that similar presidential
commissions assigned to it would be served by staff familiar with
the law.
   Charles Cushman, executive director of the National Inholders
Association, said the commission ``operated in a vacuum and made
silly recommendations'' that it might not have made if the
requirements had been met.
   But Derek Crandall, president of the American Recreation
Coalition, a trade association, said Cushman ``could not be more
wrong. ... We had an extraordinarily open process, and did nothing
in camera.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FTC-Trump     04-05 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Trump,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Agrees To Pay $750,000 Penalty To Settle Antitrust Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York real-estate magnate Donald Trump
agreed Tuesday to pay a $750,000 civil penalty to settle an
antitrust lawsuit stemming from his attempted takeovers of Holiday
Corp. and Bally Manufacturing Corp.
   Trump agreed to pay the penalty to settle a suit filed by the
Federal Trade Commission alleging that his 1986 stock purchases in
the two companies violated the notification procedures required by
the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act.
   The law requires that buyers must notify the government before
purchasing more than $15 million worth of voting stock in a company
and wait 30 days before completing the transaction.
   The FTC complaint, filed in U.S. District Court along with the
proposed settlement agreement, charged that Trump violated the law
by failing to notify the government of Holiday stock acquisitions
made between Aug. 22, 1986 and Oct. 17, 1986.
   The complaint also charged that Trump committed the same
violation when he acquired more than $15 million in shares of Bally
stock between Nov. 13, 1986 and Dec. 1, 1986.
   The settlement is the second in two days by the FTC involving
the so-called ``parking'' of stock with a brokerage house.
   On Monday, the Belzberg family of Canada agreed to pay a
$400,000 penalty to settle a similar suit arising from its attempt
to buy a controlling interest in Ashland Oil Co.
   Both cases involved the purchase of stock options through Bear,
Stearns & Co., which, in turn, bought actual shares. The FTC
contends that the subsequent exercise of the stock options was
covered by the notification procedures of the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act.
   In a statement, Trump said he decided to settle the case ``to
avoid protracted litigation within the federal government over a
highly technical disagreement between the FTC and the business
community.''
   Trump said ``I firmly believe that I was in full compliance with
the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act reporting restrictions.''
   Trump said ``the most respected lawyers in the business'' told
him the law exempted the purchase of stock options. ``Bear, Stearns
also gave me the same assurance,'' Trump said. ``I assume Bear,
Stearns will reimburse me for the expense.''
   A Bear, Stearns spokeswoman said the company had no immediate
comment.
   Wickes Cos. agreed last month to pay a $300,000 civil penalty to
settle a similar complaint. Bear, Stearns also served as the broker
for Wickes Cos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
