<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-05 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0410</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>April Brings Warm Weather
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The central and southeastern United States enjoyed summery
temperatures in the 80s on Tuesday, with temperatures in much of
the country 15 to 25 degrees above normal for early April.
   Warm humid air covered an area from Texas into the middle
Mississippi Valley, but a cold front that extended from the upper
Great Lakes into the southern Plains led cooler and drier air into
the region.
   Temperatures were in the 80s from Texas into the middle
Mississippi and Ohio valleys and in the Southeast. Readings were in
the 70s as far north as lower Michigan.
   The low temperature for the nation Tuesday morning was 3 degrees
below zero at Yellowstone Park, Wyo.
   Several records were set for high temperatures, including 86
degrees in Athens, Ga., which tied a record from 1978; 83 at
Indianapolis, breaking by 2 degrees a record set in 1873 and tied
in 1929; and 86 degrees in Louisville, Ky., breaking a record of 85
set in 1873.
   Winds gusted to 50 mph early Tuesday afternoon across the
central and southern high Plains. Wind gusts were clocked at 49 mph
at Amarillo, Texas, and at 48 mph at Beatrice, Neb.
   Showers were scattered across western Washington state, and
across parts of New England. Quillayute, Wash., recorded more than
half an inch of rain, and Portland, Maine, recorded half an inch.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 29 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 94 at Meridian, Miss.
   The forecast for Wednesday was showers and thunderstorms from
the eastern two thirds of the Great Lakes through the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys, the middle and southern Atlantic states and into
the central Gulf Coast. Showers will be scattered across the
Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 60s or 70s across much of
the nation, with 80s from the central and southern valleys of
California through the southern Plateau into the Rio Grande Valley
of Texas and from east Texas through the Gulf of Mexico coast into
the Carolinas as well as Florida. Highs will reach the middle to
upper 90s across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures into the 50s were forecast for the northern Pacific
coast and from the upper Mississippi Valley through much of the
Great Lakes and much of New England. Highs were expected in the 40s
from northeast Minnesota across upper Michigan.
</TEXT>
