<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KingMarch     04-05 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-King March,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cross-Country Trek Leaves Lorraine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following two yellow farm horses
temporarily dubbed mules, marchers in a cross-country pilgrimage
for the poor stepped off Tuesday from the small motel where Martin
Luther King Jr. died 20 years ago.
   ``We're trying to stir up the countryside. We're trying to bring
people out to express their outrage about poverty,'' said the Rev.
Joseph Lowery, president of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, a civil rights organization founded by King.
   The combination march and motorcade through Mississippi, Alabama
and Georgia was scheduled to begin Monday following a memorial
service on the 20th anniversary of King's death.
   The trek was delayed a day, however, because two mules that were
to pull a farm wagon on the marching portions of the trip failed to
arrive on time.
   The two animals trucked in for the trip Tuesday turned out to be
small yellow work horses but were strapped up to the wagon as the
procession got under way.
   ``Today, they're mules,'' Lowery said as he climbed aboard the
wagon.
   Lowery said SCLC marches often use a mule-drawn wagon as a
symbol of poverty.
   The 30 or so marchers walked about a mile and a half from The
Lorraine before loading the wagon on a rental truck, putting the
horses on a trailer and climbing aboard three vans for a trip to
Marks, Miss., the first stop on the tour.
   The group plans to ride in the vans for the rural parts of the
trip and stage marches and rallies at towns along the way.
   The pilgrimage is scheduled to arrive in Atlanta on April 29.
   Lowery said his group will hold several public hearings on the
trip for a report on poverty to be given to the Republican and
Democratic parties at their conventions this summer.
   ``Most poor people are working people,'' he said. ``They simply
don't earn enough to carry them out of the pits of poverty.''
   In recent years, particularly during President Reagan's
administration, the nation has lost the urgency it once felt to
help the poor, Lowery said.
   ``You're not going to get the private sector, where most jobs
are, to respond until you get public policy that encourages them,
that requires them and offers the incentives for them to provide
job training and job opportunities for those who need it,'' he said.
   Lowery said the cross-country trek was begun at The Lorraine
because King was assassinated there while helping the working poor
by leading a strike by sanitation workers.
   ``We will not let any commemorative service for Dr. King end
with a benediction,'' Lowery said. ``That's why we closed the April
4 event with a pilgrimage as part of the poor people's campaign.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
