<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Sees Justice In Mecham Ouster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson said Tuesday he saw justice and a touch of irony in the
state Senate's action voting Evan Mecham out of the governor's
office after an impeachment trial.
   Jackson, who frequently invokes the memory of slain civil rights
leader Martin Luther King Jr., noted that it was Mecham's move to
reverse the state's King holiday that was among the first of the
governor's troubles. And, he noted, Mecham was voted out on Monday,
the 20th anniversary of King's slaying.
   ``The long shadow of Dr. King seems to hover over Gov. Mecham,''
Jackson said after arriving here to campaign toward Arizona's April
16 Democratic presidential caucuses.
   ``One of Dr. King's favorite sayings was, `The arc of the
universe is long, but it bends toward justice,''' Jackson told
reporters. ``It's a way of saying the wheels of justice grind
slowly, but they grind fine.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Musicians Urge Young People To Register And Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Zappa wants you to vote. So do Stevie
Wonder, John Cougar Mellencamp and a long-haired, glittery British
rock group called Whitesnake.
   The musicians are pitching voter registration on MTV, the cable
television operation better known for rock videos than public
service, with the aim of increasing registration among those aged
18 to 21 above the current 13 percent.
   Mellencamp tells viewers that ``we do make a difference.''
   ``If you don't register, you can't vote, and if you don't vote,
democracy doesn't work,'' Zappa says. ``Consider the alternative.''
   MTV, which started running the public service announcements
Friday, said further spots are planned.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Elder Gore Plugs Son's Presidential Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Sr.
dismissed the idea Tuesday that his son's Democratic presidential
campaign has its back to the wall.
   He said the hunt for Democratic National Convention delegates is
only half over and asserted that it will be decided by primaries in
New York, Pennsylvania and Ohio.
   ``This is it. This is the major leagues,'' Gore said, adding
that his son, a senator from Tennessee, is in the presidential
competition to stay ``and will be a contestant at the convention.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Kean Predicts Democratic Leaders Will Try To Stop Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, who advocates a
Republican ``politics of inclusion,'' said Tuesday that he believes
Democratic leaders will do all they can to keep Jesse Jackson from
getting the presidential nomination.
   Kean, who has been mentioned as a GOP vice presidential
possibility, said he believes Jackson's candidacy would be opposed
because party leaders believe a black can't win the White House and
because of Jackson's sometimes radical ideas.
   ``They don't think he can win, and they don't want him as
president,'' Kean told reporters.
   The governor, who has endorsed Vice President George Bush for
president, said he believes ``the country is ready'' for a black
president. ``Whether or not the country is ready to vote for Jesse
Jackson is another matter,'' he added.
