<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 2049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-US     04-05 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Bases in Philippines Needed In Face Of Soviet Buildup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American envoy at the opening of
talks on the future of U.S. military bases in the Philippines said
Tuesday the facilities are needed in the face of a Soviet buildup.
   Ambassador Nicholas Platt said the six bases, where about 20,000
U.S. military personnel and defense workers are stationed, are
critical to security in Southeast Asia.
   Many Filipinos have called for an end to the garrisons, which
they see as a vestige of colonialism.
   Platt said that while U.S. troop strength in the region has
remained constant, the ``Soviet military presence has grown from an
essentially zero base to one of substantial proportions.''
   ``It only requires an overnight shift in Soviet intentions,
given their current capability, to transform this presence into a
serious economic and military threat to the Philippines and to the
region,'' he added.
   U.S. and Philippine officials are reviewing a 1947 agreement
under which the United States operates the bases, the last major
U.S. military installations in Southeast Asia. They technically are
under command of the Philippines but are effectively controlled by
the United States.
   As the talks got under way at a seaside convention complex in
Manila, about 500 people staged a peaceful march to the U.S.
Embassy protesting the bases. Eight imprisoned communist rebels
issued a statement demanding the bases be closed.
   The government has been fighting a 19-year war against communist
guerrillas.
   Spokesmen for the two countries said Tuesday's closed-door
meeting was devoted to drawing up an agenda and agreeing on
procedures for the talks, which are expected to last three months.
   The leases for the bases expire in 1991. Under the new
Philippine constitution, a lease extension must be approved by
two-thirds of the 23-member Senate, where opposition to the bases
is strong.
   Philippine negotiators were expected to press the United States
for an increase in the $180 million Manila receives each year for
the bases.
   Platt indicated Washington would resist such demands.
   ``For decades, we have borne the main financial burden for the
defense of the free nations,'' he said. ``Now, the resulting
serious deficits and imbalances must be addressed as a matter of
top priority.''
   He said the presence of the U.S. bases allows the Philippines to
use its resources on economic development and battle the communist
rebels. Platt also predicted more foreign investment in the country
if the bases remain.
   Philippine officials have said they also will press for
information on whether the installations, which include the Clark
air and Subic naval bases and four smaller facilities, are used to
store or transport nuclear weapons.
   The new constitution states that the country opposes such
weapons ``consistent with the national interests.''
   Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus said the talks will be held in
an atmosphere ``of candor and friendship,'' but suggested the
Philippine negotiators will be sensitive to growing opposition to
the U.S. bases.
   President Corazon Aquino has not said if she supports an
extension of the leases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
