<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0748 04-05 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0748,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Damascus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shultz Says Palestinian State `Makes No Sense'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with results of day's meetings.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz discussed
the U.S. peace plan with two Arab leaders at length Tuesday and
said ``the going is very tough.''
   Meeting with reporters on the flight back to Jerusalem, he
reported no ``convergence'' with Israel on Mideast negotiations
during talks with King Hussein of Jordan in Amman and President
Hafez Assad of Syria in Damascus.
   Shultz said he brought with him questions from Hussein to
present on Wednesday to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres.
   Hussein's approval of the plan is considered essential. A senior
Israeli defense official said Monday that Israel might be nudged
into acting on the plan if Hussein accepts it in principle.
   Among points at issue is how negotiations on Palestinian
self-rule, which Shultz hopes will begin May 1, would link with
talks on a final settlement. Shultz would like the second stage to
begin in December.
   He will take answers from the Israelis to Hussein later
Wednesday after a stop in Cairo to see President Hosni Mubarak of
Egypt.
   ``I can't report any particular sense of convergence on the
intiative at this point,'' the secretary told reporters on his U.S.
Air Force jet. ``People are raising questions and expressing
reservations.''
   Shultz added, however: ``We continue to think what has been put
forward is basically what can potentially work, so we stick with
it.''
   All sides urged him to continue in his effort for negotiations,
he declared, but ``I don't want to give any big plus sign because
that would not be warranted by the facts.''
   Shamir and Peres are prepared to negotiate with the Arabs on an
overall settlement but ``there are all sorts of questions'' on the
Israeli side, including a connection between Palestinian self-rule
and talks on an overall agreement, Shultz said.
   Israel's Cabinet is deadlocked over whether to accept the U.S.
proposal. Shamir leads those holding out, while Peres and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin favor it.
   In Amman, Shultz and Hussein met for 75 minutes, then had lunch.
In Damascus, the secretary spent two hours and 45 minutes with
Assad and said they had ``sharply different'' views on how to hold
the negotiations.
   ``We think we made a reasonable amount of headway'' however,
Shultz said. April Glaspie, head of the State Department's
Jordan-Lebanon-Syrian desk, remained in Damascus for further
discussions.
   In an interview with Jordanian newspaper editors in Amman,
Shultz ruled out participation in peace talks by the Palestine
Liberation Organization. ``How do you talk to someone who says we
want to exterminate you (Israel)?'' he asked.
   He also said: ``We don't think an independent Palestinian state
on the West Bank makes sense.''
   The interview was videotaped but not shown on early evening news
programs by Jordan's state-run television network. A senior
government source said privately the Shultz comments were
considered ``very much pro-Israeli.''
   Jordanian television usually can be seen in Israel and Syria,
and by Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, which have been torn by four months of violence.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said in Washington
that Hussein had not dropped his insistence that talks with Israel
be held at a peace conference in which the Soviet Union and United
States would take active roles. Israel prefers direct negotiations
with the Arabs.
   Shultz made clear in the Jordanian interview that PLO
partricipation in peace talks is impossible until it accepts
Israel's right to exist and renounces terrorism.
   ``Israel is here. It's here to stay,'' he said.
   Several of the editors questioned whether the United States
could be a fair mediator between Arabs and Israel. The secretary
said Washington is a friend of both sides.
</TEXT>
