<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham-Future     04-05 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Future,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Says Job Not `The End of the World'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Mecham-Mofford Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after he was convicted and removed
from office by the state Senate, former Gov. Evan Mecham said
Tuesday he is doing fine but has not decided whether he will try to
get his job back.
   However, Mecham warned that those who ousted him may not realize
they have ``awakened a sleeping giant'' in the Arizona electorate.
   ``I know that they are aroused, I know that they are incensed, I
know that they are right down angry,'' said Mecham, a first-term
Republican convicted in an impeachment trial that ended Monday.
   Mecham _ who described himself as the ``recent former governor''
_ appeared relaxed as he spoke to a Kiwanis Club and said, ``I have
no rancor in my heart for anybody.''
   He was removed from office Monday when the Senate convicted him
of obstructing justice and misusing $80,000 from the governor's
protocol fund.
   ``I haven't yet determined what my course will be,'' Mecham
said. ``I haven't yet said that I'm not going to be a candidate in
the recall.''
   Earlier, in a telephone interview from his surburban Glendale
home, he said, ``I'm doing fine. ... I've got a clear conscience
and I haven't done anything wrong.''
   ``This job wasn't the end of the world for me; I didn't need it
in the first place,'' Mecham said.
   Several weeks ago, Mecham had said that if the Senate convicted
him, he might go to the U.S. Supreme Court to claim that his rights
had been violated. He said Tuesday he had not decided whether he
will do so.
   Two Senate leaders _ Republican Majority Leader Robert Usdane
and Minority Leader Alan Stephens _ said there was talk among
senators about reconsidering their vote against excluding Mecham
from holding office again. The two said they opposed reopening the
issue when the Senate meets Wednesday.
   Mecham faces a criminal trial April 21 on charges of concealing
a $350,000 campaign loan. If convicted, he would be barred from
holding office again.
   Meanwhile, Mecham attorney Jerris Leonard told KTAR radio he
does not believe Mecham can run in the May 17 recall because the
Senate removed him from the four-year term he began in January 1987.
   ``My understanding is that he cannot run again until 1990,''
Leonard said.
   The recall election remained scheduled despite the vote removing
Mecham from office and the installation of Democrat Rose Mofford,
the secretary of state who until Monday was acting governor.
   Mecham told the Kiwanis group he expects lawmakers and Mrs.
Mofford to adopt a 10 percent tax increase to make up for a 1988-89
budget deficit estimated at $349 million. Such a tax hike is
unnecessary, he said, although in January Mecham proposed a ``tax
equity'' plan that amounted to a $90 million hike.
   Mecham said he disagreed with Mrs. Mofford's decision to sign
legislation allowing a second weekly lottery game and another
measure allowing new state buildings to be funded through
lease-purchase.
   Leonard said he planned to ask the Senate on Wednesday to
require the state to pay Mecham's attorney fees, which Leonard said
were ``in the range of $300,000.''
   Officials still must decide what to do with the protocol fund,
which Leonard said is in the bank. Mecham's auto dealership repaid
the $80,000 loan that was the subject of one impeachment charge.
</TEXT>
