<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Koch-Jackson     04-05 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koch-Jackson,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch Says Other Candidates Are Afraid to Critize Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch charged Tuesday that the
other presidential candidates have not challenged Jesse Jackson's
position on vital issues for fear of being labeled as racist.
   ``We have seen the other candidates, up until now, dance around
Jesse Jackson, and the media dance around Jesse Jackson as though
they were afraid they were either going to insult him or his
supporters,'' Koch said. ``I think it would insult him and his
supporters by not treating him equally.''
   Koch maintained that the other presidential candidates have been
afraid to insult Jackson, the black candidate, or his supporters by
questioning his positions on aid to the Palestine Liberation
Organization and on cutting back on defense in favor of vast social
programs.
   Although Koch said Jackson was ``the smartest of all those guys
running,'' he maintained that this didn't mean he'd make the best
president.
   ``But, he knows how to answer. He can defend himself,'' Koch
said. ``He doesn't need presidential security from questions. And
so when the candidates wouldn't take him on, and the media wouldn't
take him on, I decided I would.''
   The mayor was critical of Jackson last Friday saying Jews would
be ``crazy'' to vote for him since he embraced PLO leader Yasser
Arafat.
   He said Jackson's domestic social programs would ``break the
bank'' in three weeks, and his proposed defense cutbacks would
leave the United States ``defenseless'' in six weeks.
   ``It seems to me everybody who's running for president ought to
be subject, with respect to their public behavior and their public
statements and their philosophy, under a microscope,'' the mayor
said.
   ``Aren't you patronizing Jesse Jackson by saying he shall be
spared from having to defend his positions?'' Koch said when asked
if he had had any backlash from his criticism of the Democratic
candidate.
   Koch said, ``I encourage everybody to speak the truth as they
know it. I encourage Jesse Jackson to respond. I encourage Jesse
Jackson to say where are we wrong and also to point out the
infirmities, the moats, if you will, in the eyes of the other
candidates. I encourage that debate.''
   ``Remember,'' he added, ``we're electing a president. This is
not a matter of silence. Silence today is not golden. Silence today
is chicken!''
</TEXT>
