<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiberaceAuction     04-05 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberace Auction,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberace's Flamboyance Evident at Auction of Possessions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a half-acre building, for sale to the
highest bidder, are many of Liberace's luxurious possessions _
mirrored pianos, furs, classic cars and glittery memorabilia.
   ``It is really sad. We would all rather have Lee here,'' Debbie
Reynolds said Tuesday during a preview of the Liberace Collection.
``There's a little bit of something for everyone.''
   The sale, with items accumulated for decades by the late
entertainer, runs Saturday through Tuesday.
   Liberace, a pianist without peer who symbolized extravagance and
outlandish dress, died Feb. 4, 1987, at age 67 from complications
caused by acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   A Convention Center hall was packed with more than 2,000
treasures, including mirrored Baldwin pianos, furs, classic cars
and furnishings from Liberace's Las Vegas, Nev., home, Los Angeles
penthouse, New York apartment, Malibu Beach house and Lake Tahoe
estate.
   Gaudy, ornate, peculiar, tacky and ordinary all apply.
   There are green, blue, red and purple shoes. There are belts,
hankies, crowns, a sleigh and stuffed animals. A General Electric
Toast-R-Oven, big screen TVs and several videocassette recorders
and stereo speakers.
   Potted phony floral arrangements were everywhere, and there was
a 7-foot-tall climbing bougainvillea and a miniature piano with
silk flowers.
   ``He would go shopping from K mart to Neiman Marcus,'' said Dora
Liberace, the entertainer's sister-in-law and administrator of the
Liberace Museum in Las Vegas. Asked what he would think of the
displays, she said:
   ``He probably would have been right here in front watching it
all go on sale, then he'd go right out and buy more. He loved
shopping and he usually bought two of everything.''
   In addition to a dozen pianos, 13 vehicles, including three
limousines, a Rolls-Royce with a wild brocade interior, a 1977
Chrysler station wagon with piano keys on the side and a 1982 van,
were expected to bring the most money.
   Butterfield & Butterfield and Christie's are conducting the
auction to benefit the decade-old non-profit Liberace Foundation
for the Performing and Creative Arts, which funds scholarships at
28 schools and colleges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
