<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 2113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FlagFlap 1stLd-Writethru a0789 04-05 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flag Flap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0789,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oklahoma Governor Signs Resolution But Balks at Flying Flag</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 1 graf at end to explain flag display.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Henry Bellmon signed a controversial
resolution Tuesday requiring the Confederate flag be flown over the
Capitol, but said the flag pole would remain empty until he knows
which Confederate flag to display.
   During debate on the bill, black legislators urged colleagues
not to adopt the resolution, saying the Confederate flag was an
offensive symbol of racism and slavery and had been used by
organizations such as the Ku Klux Klan.
   Bellmon's announcement came at a news conference the day after
the author of the resolution, state Sen. Herbert Rozell, said he
would refuse the governor's request to recall the bill and change
it.
   In asking for the recall, Bellmon said the bill did not
stipulate which of the three flags used by the Confederacy from
1861 to 1865 should be flown.
   Rozell said Monday the resolution was written so Bellmon ``could
fly the flag that is the least offensive.''
   But Bellmon said Tuesday, ``If I chose any one of the three I'm
going to be criticized for it.''
   The flag has sparked controversy in several other Southern
states recently. Opponents say the Confederate flag is a symbol of
oppression; supporters say it is historic, not a racial symbol.
   In Georgia, legislators have introduced a bill to redesign the
state flag, which incorporates the design of the Confederate
banner, and in Alabama, black lawmakers were arrested for trying to
remove a Confederate flag from the Capitol dome.
   For years, the Stars and Bars flag used by the Confederacy until
1863 was part of a 14-flag display south of the Capitol steps. The
display was removed during recent reconstruction and Office of
Public Affairs Director Helen Arnold said she did not plan to have
it restored.
   Rozell then introduced the resolution to require the flag
display be resurrected.
   The flag display represents the countries that have claimed a
portion of Oklahoma territory in the past, including France and
Spain. Bellmon has said the existence of the Confederacy and its
control over a portion of Oklahoma are undisputed facts, and the
display is in historical context.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
