<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 2036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia     04-05 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laughing Gunmen in Massacre of 28 Yelled ``Kill Everyone You
Can!''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Please note language in 23rd graf, ``Then you ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen laughed and screamed ``Kill
everyone you can!'' as they massacred 28 villagers at a rural
Easter festival, newspapers in the capital reported Tuesday.
   The hooded killers shot dead an elderly, one-legged man as he
struggled to get on the donkey and flee, the Bogota daily El Tiempo
quoted an unidentified survivor as saying.
   A 10-year-old boy, Oscar Sierra, who was among those ordered to
lie face down in the dirt and not look up, was shot in the head at
point-blank range by one of the killers when he lifted his head,
another survivor was quoted as telling an El Tiempo reporter.
   One other child, a 14-year-old boy, was also killed in the
Sunday bloodbath.
   There were conflicting reports on the number of wounded, ranging
from 10 to 15. A death toll of 33 given Monday was revised downward
to 28 Tuesday by Gov. Jose Gabriel Amin Manzur of northwest Cordoba
state.
   The governor said police and the army suspect the massacre was
the work of leftist guerrillas, El Tiempo said.
   However, the murders had all the earmarks of the work of a
right-wing death squad.
   El Tiempo and another Bogota daily, El Espectador, sent
reporters to the scene, a thatched roof hut in remote mountains
where about 200 people were celebrating the end of Holy Week.
   The area, know as Mejor Esquina, lies 280 miles west of the
capital city of Bogota and has about 50 families, with no house
closer than 1,500 feet to its neighbor.
   Here is what happened, according to the accounts given reporters:
   The traditional partying started Saturday afternoon, with an
eight-piece band of guitars and accordions playing the songs dear
to Colombian peasants _ballads of hard-working cowboys, lost love
and happiness amid poverty.
   A pig was slaughtered for the feast and chickens were killed.
   Sunday started off with horse races. In the afternoon there was
a dance for the children in the small farmhouse made of mud bricks.
   Women cooked stew in huge pots throughout the afternoon and the
men drank beer and aguardiente, a Colombian liquor with a faint
taste of licorice.
   In the evening, the peasants danced and shouted to each other
over music blaring from large speakers. Only a few noticed vehicles
park about 150 feet away with lights out.
   Some people said there were about 10 gunmen. Others said there
were as many as 20. Some said they wore military jungle clothing.
Others said they wore police uniforms.
   One thing all survivors agreed on was the gunmen laughing
crazily as they fired repeatedly into the crowd amid shouts,
screams, the hysterical crying of children.
   Some people ran into the hut, and gunmen followed, firing as
they entered.
   Jose Llorente said he survived because the bodies of dead
friends lay atop him as the killers fired into the room.
   No one in the band was killed. One gunman smashed an accordion
and whacked the musician across his backside with the flat part of
a 2-foot-long machete.
   The shooting lasted about 20 minutes and the gunmen became more
selective in choosing victims. Eight people were shot in the back
of the head as they lay face down in the hut.
   The gunmen left, warning survivors to keep their faces in the
dirt for five minutes.
   ``Then you can look up and cry over what you find, you sons of
bitches!'' one attacker shouted.
   That is when the 10-year-old boy was shot for lifting his head.
   The sound of the vehicles died out and the village was filled
with the groans of the wounded, cries of people calling for loved
ones, the agonized whinnying of injured horses.
   The next day, in nearby Planeta Rica, someone painted on a wall,
``The Magnificient Ones are here to clean things up.''
   There are a dozen right-wing death squads in Colombia with names
like the Vampires and the Crickets. This the first time the
Magnificient Ones had been heard of.
   Death squads have killed about 600 people in the last three
years.
   The left says the army is behind killings. The army denies it.
The government says it has been unable to find out who organizes
the death squads.
   So far no one from any death squad has been caught.
   Leftist guerrillas draw combatants from rural areas, and Mejor
Esquina may have been one of them.
   At the school, a guerrilla slogan _ Long live the Popular
Liberation Army _ has been painted near the entrance.
   The schoolmaster, Tomas Berrios Wilches, was among those killed.
</TEXT>
