<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     04-05 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Condemns Foreign Interference In Ethnic Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev lashed out Tuesday at
foreigners he said were trying to aggravate an ethnic dispute in
the southern Caucasus.
   ``They are trying to interfere in our internal affairs, to
exacerbate problems from the outside and (are) engaging in
provocations,'' he said. ``At present this is particularly visible
in connection with the events around Nagorno-Karabakh.''
   His comments were similar to recent remarks in the official
press condemning purported outside interference in the dispute over
Nagorno-Karabakh, a region in Azerbaijan that Armenians want
attached to their republic.
   The Soviet leader's remarks came at a Kremlin meeting with Willy
Brandt, head of the Socialist International and a former chancellor
of West Germany. The official news agency Tass reported on the
meeting.
   Gorbachev singled out broadcasters for criticism.
   ``Various radio stations, including official ones, have joined
in the subversive activity,'' he said. ``Especially active ... is
Deutsche Welle (West German radio).''
   Tass did not say how the radio stations were purportedly being
subversive, but other Soviet reports have accused Western
journalists of sharpening tensions between Armenians and Azeris,
the dominant ethnic group in Azerbaijan.
   Gorbachev told Brandt, ``We will handle problems that have
accumulated, including on the nationalities issue, within the
framework of the democratic process we have firmly chosen.''
   Soviet newspapers reported Tuesday that four businesses have
gone bankrupt in Stepanakert, the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh,
because of a strike but that workers have been returning to their
jobs in increasing numbers.
   The first reports that workers were returning to their jobs came
Friday. The government newspaper Izvestia reported Tuesday that
workers were continuing to go back to work to their jobs because of
repeated appeals by Communist authorities.
   Workers began striking in Stepanakert on March 24 to protest
government refusal to turn the city and the surrounding region,
Nagorno-Karabakh, over to the Armenian republic. Most of the
region's 160,000 residents are ethnic Armenians but since 1923 it
has been part of the neighboring republic of Azerbaijan.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the national parliament,
announced a plan on March 23 for $690 million in economic, social
and culture improvements for Nagorno-Karabakh, which some Armenians
say has suffered under the control of Azerbaijan.
   Izvestia said that in Stepanakert on Tuesday, all workers of the
building materials plant showed up as did more than half of the
employees of the electrical engineering works and silk mill. About
a third of the workers of the shoe and furniture factories reported
for work, it said.
   The annexation issue touched off demonstrations and strikes in
Nagorno-Karabakh on Feb. 13, and the unrest spread to the Armenian
captial, Yerevan. The dispute led to ethnic rioting Feb. 28 in the
Azerbaijani city of Sumgait that left at least 32 people dead.
</TEXT>
