<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Tibet     04-05 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Tibet,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama Says He May Be Willing to Meet Chinese Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama, Tibet's spiritual leader in exile,
said Tuesday he may be willing to meet Chinese leaders in Beijing
to discuss the future of his homeland.
   ``I feel the more time goes on, there may be more room to
develop human understanding,'' he said in a television interview.
``We need more patience, more determination. I am trying to find
some way, a middle way, or some kind of compromise.''
   ``If circumstances really became more favorable and more
positive, I would have no hesitation to go'' to the Chinese capital
to discuss Tibetan independence, he told Britain's commercial
Channel 4 network.
   The 52-year-old Dalai Lama arrived Monday on a 12-day private
visit.
   He chided Britain for not being more openly critical of China's
control of Tibet. The Dalai Lama fled Tibet to exile in India in
1959 after an abortive Tibetan uprising against the Chinese.
   He said Monday that Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservative government had asked him to refrain from making
political statements during his visit, which he said will be mainly
devoted to Buddhist teaching.
   Published reports have suggested Britain does not want to upset
China in the period leading up to the transfer of Britain's Hong
Kong colony to China in 1997.
   China, which claims Tibet has been an integral part of the
nation for centuries, moved troops into the remote mountain region
in 1950. Many Tibetans resent the Beijing government because of
opression of Tibetan religion and customs and the destruction of
temples during the ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution in 1966-76.
</TEXT>
