<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeditionTrial     04-05 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sedition Trial,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates Complicated Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury deliberated a second day Tuesday
without deciding the fate of 13 people, nine of them accused of
conspiring to violently overthrow the U.S. government and establish
an Aryan nation.
   At midafternoon, the jury asked U.S. District Judge Morris
Arnold for a trial transcript. Arnold sent jurors a note saying a
transcript would be about 7,000 pages and would not be ready for
three or four months.
   He told jurors that recordings of long portions of testimony
could not be played for them and they should rely on their memory
and notes. The jury was to resume deliberations Wednesday.
   The case went to the jury on Monday, after a trial that began
Feb. 16 and included 192 witnesses.
   Defendant Richard G. Butler told reporters Tuesday that the
trial is a move by the government to snuff out views that do not
meet its approval. He said he expects to be acquitted, but added,
``In any case, they win _ they break us financially.''
   Butler and defendants Robert E. Miles and Louis Ray Beam Jr. are
considered among the leaders of the white-supremacist movement in
the United States.
   One of Beam's lawyers, Kirk Lyons, said acquittal would slow the
movement more than a guilty verdict because it would show that
white supremacists ``can get a fair trial in American courts. If
acquittal comes back in this case, it will go a long way toward
neutralizing the right wing. If they're convicted, the right wing
will think they've been shanghaied.''
   Besides the nine people accused of seditious conspiracy, which
carries a maximum of 20 years in prison and a $20,000 fine, five
defendants are accused of conspiring to kill federal officials and
two of transporting stolen money across state lines. The murder
plot could be punished by life imprisonment; the transporting
charge by a term of 10 years plus a $10,000 fine.
   A key government witness was James Ellison, who is serving 20
years for racketeering. He led a white-supremacist group named the
Covenant, the Sword and the Arm of the Lord. His group carried out
bombings in furtherance of a conspiracy, he testified, that was
made in July 1983 at Hayden Lake, Idaho, at a convocation of
Butler's group, the Aryan Nations.
   Defendants at that meeting have said that there was no
conspiracy and that Ellison made up the story in hopes of getting a
sentence reduction.
</TEXT>
