<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Exports,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Welcomes Japanese Crackdown On Strategic Arms Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department on Tuesday praised
Japan's ``new energy and dedication'' in tightening controls on
sales of strategic exports to communist countries.
   Paul Freedenberg, undersecretary of commerce for export
administration, said Tokyo's reported crackdown on two Japanese
firms accused of violating export regulations in the sale of
electronic measuring equipment to China ``demonstrates Japan's
serious regard for protecting sensitive technology.''
   ``We are beginning to see actions that demonstrate Japan's
commitment to a strong and effective export control regime, a
commitment that has recently been reinforced with increased funds
and stronger export control laws,'' Freedenberg said in a statement.
   He added that the latest actions underscore ``the new energy and
dedication of the Japanese government in administering and
enforcing multilateral export control rules.''
   He cited the Japanese government's announcement Monday that it
was investigating alleged export violations by Kyokuto Shokai Co.
Ltd. and Shinseki Koeki Co. Ltd.
   The Japanese Ministry of International Trade and Industry said
the companies' sales to China occurred in 1985-86, prior to the
tightening of trade laws brought about by the disclosure that
Toshiba Machine Corp. had illegally exported machinery used in the
production of silent submarine propellors to the Soviet Union.
