<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MoundsvilleEscape 2ndLd-Writethru a0819 04-05 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moundsville Escape, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0819,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search for Three Escaped Killers Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with police now calling
sighting false. Picks up 7th graf pvs, ``Earlier a.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOUNDSVILLE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for three killers who
escaped from the West Virginia Penitentiary focused for hours
Tuesday on what turned out to be a false sighting at a restaurant,
state police said.
   ``At first check, it seemed to be them,'' said state police Sgt.
D.E. Cook. ``But after further checks, we couldn't make a positive
I.D.
   ``We retraced all the people who saw them. They weren't the
three,'' Cook said, adding that the investigative effort had taken
six hours.
   State police had said four workers at a fast food restaurant in
Cross Lanes, 11 miles west of Charleston and about 170 miles south
of the prison, had made a positive identification of the escapees
based on mug shots.
   Convicted murderers Bobby Stacy, Tommie Mollohan and David
Williams used stolen bolt cutters in their Sunday night escape from
the Moundsville prison.
   Earlier, a prison official blamed the escape on antiquated
facilities and the need to use inmate labor.
   Corrections Commissioner A.V. Dodrill said at least one of the
escapees was probably familiar with ``every nook and cranny'' of
the 122-year-old prison, which Dodrill says can be kept running
only with the help of the inmates.
   As a result, he said, inmates often become familiar with the
institution's weaknesses.
   ``This prison is in terrible shape. The plumbing is especially
bad. It needs constant renovation,'' Dodrill said.
   Mollohan, 45, was convicted of robbing and killing a grocer in
1973.
   At the time, Mollohan had escaped from a Florida prison and also
was wanted in Georgia and North Carolina on armed robbery charges.
   ``Mollohan was the ringleader,'' Dodrill said. ``He is an
excellent plumber and probably knew every nook and cranny.''
   Stacy, 35, was convicted of killing one police officer and
accused of shooting another. Authorities said he had sworn revenge
on those who had put him behind bars.
   Police have assigned protection to those who helped convict
Stacy, including the judge in his case and a Columbus, Ohio, woman
who testified against him.
   Williams, 28, was serving a life sentence for felony murder,
arson and robbery. Dodrill said authorities are trying to determine
whether the three were aided in their escape by correctional
officers. ``That possibility does exist,'' the commissioner said.
   The last escape from Moundsville was in February 1983, when two
inmates climbed over a wall behind the prison. They were recaptured
within 24 hours.
   In 1979, 15 inmates, including convicted cop killer Ronald
Williams, escaped from the massive, stone block prison, killing an
off-duty state trooper who was driving past. All 15 eventually were
recaptured.
 
</TEXT>
