<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Reform 3rdLd-Writethru a0732 04-05 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reform, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0732,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pravda Editorial Condemns Stalinism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-8 UPDATE with Gorbachev comments. Pick up 6th
graf pvs, Pravda's editors ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda on Tuesday
denounced Soviets who are nostalgic for dictator Josef Stalin's
rule and say Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms are damaging socialism.
   Pravda also lashed out at publications that praise Stalinism and
said Gorbachev's ``glasnost'' policy of more openness on some
issues does not include criticizing principles of the economic
reforms the Soviet leader calls ``perestroika.''
   ``We need disputes helping to advance perestroika and leading to
the consolidation of forces and cohesion around perestroika rather
than to disunity,'' Pravda said in a full-page, unsigned editorial.
   It said the Soviet Union needs people dedicated to improving
housing, food supplies and services rather than those obsessed with
uncovering suspected enemies of socialism.
   ``A patriot is not he who cries out loudly about an alleged
`internal threat' to socialism, who, joining with a few political
extremists, seeks internal enemies everywhere,'' Pravda said. ``A
patriot is he who acts in the interest of the country, of the
people, without fear of any difficulty.''
   In a Kremlin meeting Tuesday with Willy Brandt, the head of
Socialist International and former chancellor of West Germany,
Gorbachev acknowledged that his reforms have generated controversy.
   The official Tass news agency quoted Gorbachev, general
secretary of the Soviet Communist Party, as saying, ``There are
people who think everything is collapsing. Just as in the beginning
of this century `matter vanished' in the perceptions of some people
as a result of new discoveries in physics, now it seems to some
that socialism is vanishing.''
   Gorbachev said that what is really happening is that socialism
``is ridding itself of everything that had deformed it in the past
and is demonstrating tremendous dynamism, the wealth of its social
and humanistic content.''
   Pravda's editors said they felt compelled to address the issue
of Stalinism because another newspaper had raised it improperly.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya, official daily of the Russian republic's
party and government, carried a letter from a Leningrad teacher who
defended Stalin. It was published March 13, just before Gorbachev
left for Yugoslavia and his chief of propaganda, Alexander N.
Yavovlev, went to Mongolia.
   In the past year, Soviet publications have criticized the
excesses of Stalin, who ruled for three decades and died in 1953.
   Gorbachev said in November the dictator's guilt for the purges
in which millions died was ``enormous and unforgivable,'' but
defended Stalin's policies of rapid industrialization and
collectivizating of agriculture.
   The Pravda editorial appeared to be an attempt to draw the party
line on Stalinism.
   It repeated criticisms of Stalin but said Gorbachev's opponents
won't let the issue rest, either because they feel more comfortable
with Stalin's repression or because it would serve their own
interests.
   ``In one person this may be directed at taking more and giving
less, in another in wrapping in respectable clothes their efforts
to claim a monopoly in science, personal innocence or something
else,'' the paper said.
   Pravda criticized the system under Stalin as ``thoughtless
execution of orders and suppression of initiative.'' The Soviet
Union cannot hide from the fact that ``many thousands'' of party
workers, economic and military officials, scientists and cultural
figures were exiled or killed, it said.
   Gorbachev launched his effort to restructure Soviet society
three years ago, and Pravda said there are those who feel
widespread changes could undermine the Soviet system.
   ``Not all realize fully that the administrative-command methods
have exhausted themselves,'' it said. ``All who pin hopes on those
methods or their modifications would do well to wake up to the fact
that we have had that more than once, but it did not bring about
the desired results.''
   People should ``get rid of the nostalgia for the past, when some
people said things and others were supposed to heed and
uncomplainingly fulfill the orders,'' Pravda advised.
   It said statements in the letter published by Sovietskaya
Rossiya are ``an attempt, little by little, to revise party
decisions.''
   ``At meetings at the party Central Committee it has been said
more than once that the Soviet press is not a private shop and that
the Communists writing in the press and the editors should be aware
of their responsibility for the articles and the publications,'' it
declared.
   ``In this case the newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya, which has .. .
done much for perestroika, has departed from this principle.''
</TEXT>
