<HEAD>Teen-Ager Pleads Guilty To Stabbing Man For Pennies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old boy on Tuesday pleaded guilty
as an adult to second-degree murder in the death of an 86-year-old
man during a robbery for a jar of pennies.
   Matthew Schrom of Austin, one of two 16-year-olds accused of
fatally stabbing Michael Linard Fink in January, entered the plea
in Mower County District Court.
   Attorneys for both sides presented Judge Paul Kimball with a
proposal under which Schrom, who was charged with first-degree
murder in juvenile court, would plead guilty to second-degree
murder in adult court.
   The other teen-ager, charged in juvenile court with first-degree
murder, remains in custody in lieu of $100,000 bond. A hearing is
scheduled next week, but County Attorney Nancy Evans has said she
does not expect a plea agreement in his case.
   Sheriff Don Hoffman has said the boys took a few dollars in
pennies from Fink's home. The boys knew Fink and were invited into
his home, the sheriff said.
