<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     04-05 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslems and Christians Join in General Strike for Wage Increases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Feuding Moslems and Christians joined in
a nationwide strike Tuesday to demand 300 percent wage increases to
counter inflation and the economic chaos brought on by 13 years of
civil war.
   In southern Lebanon, rival Moslem factions engaged in a gun
battle that left one man killed and four wounded.
   Police said the fight near the town of Nabatiyeh was between the
Syrian-backed Shiite Amal militia and the pro-Iranian Shiite
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   They said Amal militiamen had raided several villages and
rounded up 10 Hezbollah members in a search for gunmen who fired at
the car of Amal's militia commander in Nabatiyeh, Mahmoud Faqih, on
Monday. Police said Faqih was not in the car at the time.
   The one-day general strike was the latest in a series of
demonstrations that began nearly two years ago to protest the
economic situation.
   Banks, schools, shops, gasoline stations, government offices and
other businesses closed in both Christian east Beirut and Moslem
west Beirut and cities and towns throughout the country.
   But some Lebanese were sceptical.
   ``We've tried this before and nothing happened,'' said Adel
Bohsali, an employee at a pastry shop in west Beirut.
   The General Confederation of Labor Unions, which claims 300,000
members, said Beirut airport, hospitals, pharmacies, bakeries and
newspapers were exempt from the strike.
   In 1975, when the civil war began, the annual inflation rate was
9 percent. It is now 225 percent.
   The Lebanese pound, once the soundest currency in the Middle
East, exchanged at 2.5 to the U.S. dollar before the civil war and
the rate last week was 360 per dollar.
   The pound's collapse sent prices soaring in a country that
imports more than 85 percent of its needs.
   In its strike call, the labor confederatin said Tuesday's action
was a warning and an indefinite work stoppage would begin April 15
if the demand for the 300 percent increase, retroactive to January,
was not met.
   A government source, speaking with the condition he not be
identified, said Cabinet ministers were considering a compromise
that would approve wage increases but they would be limited to 100
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
