<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ExitPolls 2ndLd-Writethru a0938 04-05 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Exit Polls, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0938,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Polls Under Quarter of Whites, Loses Blue Collar Vote</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with more exit poll numbers; pick up 6th graf
pvs bgng ``We're seeing...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson narrowly lost the votes
of Wisconsin's blue collar workers to Michael Dukakis and attracted
only a quarter of the white vote, exit polls said.
   Jackson drew huge crowds at strike sites and hard-pressed
manufacturing communities in Wisconsin, but that enthusiasm did not
translate into primary votes. Dukakis beat Jackson solidly among
white blue collar workers and edged him in that category with
blacks included, ABC News and NBC said.
   Dukakis won 41 percent of blue collar Democratic voters, ABC
said, to Jackson's 37 percent. Among white blue-collar voters only,
Dukakis had 47 percent, Jackson 27 percent. NBC's numbers were
similar, with 43 percent of the overall blue collar vote going for
Dukakis and 37 percent for Jackson.
   As in previous contests, the black vote went overwhelmingly for
Jackson. Among whites, ABC and CBS said Jackson won 23 percent
support while NBC put the figure slightly higher at 28 percent.
   Jackson won just 7 percent of the white vote in Wisconsin in
1984. ABC polls said he won 22 percent in Connecticut last week and
32 percent in liberal Vermont on March 1. Said ABC poll analyst
Doug Muzzio: ``We may be looking at his ceiling here.''
   ``We're seeing a dual electorate: a black electorate and a white
electorate,'' Muzzio said. ``Jackson does extremely well among
blacks and Dukakis does substantially well among whites.''
   Electability may have been an issue, with two-thirds of all
Democrats saying they think Dukakis will be the presidential
nominee, NBC News found. Even four in 10 Jackson voters expected
Dukakis to win the nomination.
   While support for Dukakis was spread widely among demographic
groups, CBS News poll analyst Pama Mitchell said ``it looks to me
from our numbers that Dukakis' support is softer'' than Jackson's
or Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s.
   The CBS-Times poll found that Dukakis supporters were split
evenly between those who backed him strongly and those who liked
him ``with reservations,'' while Jackson's strong supporters far
outnumbered his weak ones.
   In another measure, NBC said four in 10 Dukakis supporters
wished other candidates were in the race. Nonetheless, more than
six in 10 Wisconsin Democrats said he would be the strongest
nominee of the current candidates.
   Dukakis also scored well in the goodwill category. The CBS-Times
poll said 74 percent of Democrats expressed a favorable view of
Dukakis, with 22 percent unfavorable. Jackson was rated favorably
by 55 percent and unfavorably by 40 percent.
   ``It isn't that Jackson isn't liked,'' said Kathleen A.
Frankovic, a CBS pollster. ``It's just that Dukakis is liked
better.''
   Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois had the greatest unfavorable rating,
more than five in 10, and a favorable rating of about four in 10.
Gore was viewed favorably by better than five in 10 but unfavorably
by about four in 10.
   The ABC and the CBS-Times polls found no evidence of a movement
by Republicans to cross over into the Democratic primary and vote
for Jackson as the Democrat most likely to lose to George Bush. The
CBS-Times poll found that of the 14 percent of Democratic voters
who said they were Republicans, 42 percent voted for Dukakis, 28
percent for Gore and 20 percent for Jackson.
   The exit polls all had a margin of sampling error of about 3
points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
