<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Press 1stLd-Writethru a0914 04-05 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Press, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0914,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Paper Suspends Publication, Has No Newsprint</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: La Prensa suspends publication indefinitely, new info-changes
grafs 1-7. Pick up 4th pvs: The Ministry of Industry...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   La Prensa, Nicaragua's only opposition
newspaper, suspended publication indefinitely Tuesday saying the
Sandinista government had not provided newsprint.
   A front-page story said ``with this edition we exhaust our
supply of paper, so we will not be able to circulate as long as the
Sandinista government, the only supplier, doesn't sell us paper.''
   Anti-Sandinista rebels have charged that the government, by not
providing newsprint, violated a recent promise to allow a free
press.
   Tuesday's La Prensa article rejected government suggestions that
La Prensa ran out of newsprint because of mismanagement of its
limited supply, saying publishers had reduced the daily's size from
12 to 8 pages and taken other steps to conserve.
   Deputy publisher Cristiana Chamorro said earlier Tuesday:
   ``We have no paper to come out tomorrow, or on the following
days, because the government claims there is no newsprint in the
country, but we know there is.''
   In a telephone interview, she noted the country's two other
daily newspapers, the official Sandinista publication Barricada and
pro-government Nuevo Diario, ``have been coming out normally with
eight full pages.'' Barricada and Nuevo Diario are morning papers
and La Prensa is an afternoon daily.
   The Ministry of Industry said in a statement it could not solve
La Prensa's problem because a shipment of newsprint scheduled to
arrive in March had not reached Nicaragua. It said the government
is not expecting another shipment until April 17.
   ``Once this shipment is received the Ministry of Industry will
proceed to distribute paper proportionally, according to the
established mechanisms,'' the statement said.
   It added that the government had advised the three newspapers to
take precautions against using up their stockpiles of newsprint. La
Prensa last published on April 29, then announced it would take its
traditional Holy Week break.
   Nicaragua does not manufacture newsprint, and the leftist
government controls imports and distribution.
   La Prensa was shut down from June 1986 until last Oct. 1,
reopening as part of the government's efforts to comply with a
regional Central American peace plan.
   Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, a rebel leader, told a news conference
in Miami Tuesday that the Sandinistas should supply La Prensa with
newsprint under a cease-fire agreement reached last month by the
rebels and government.
   He is a brother of Christiani Chamorro and was a co-publisher of
La Prensa until going into exile to join the rebels, known as
Contras.
   ``The government originally informed us that an agency of the
Interior Ministry could supply us with 70 rolls, enough for one
week, but at the last moment they told us the newsprint wasn't
there anymore,'' Ms. Chamorro said. ``We have taken steps to find
out if they can provide us with paper and we will know tomorrow if
we will be coming out, after midday.''
   She said the government told La Prensa it was expecting some
newsprint to arrive on a Soviet freighter April 17.
   The Soviet Union and Cuba provide the Sandinistas with military
equipment, food and other supplies.
   A letter from Defense Minister Humberto Ortega to rebel leader
Adolfo Calero said, ``It is clear that in Nicaragua there exists
total and unrestricted freedom of expression for any political
group of sector of the population.
   ``The problem of the lack of paper that is an editorial business
is not the responsibility of the government.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
