<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   04-05 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0515</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   F.W. Woolworth Co. has received notice that Dart
Group Corp. intends to acquire a substantial amount of the stock in
the nation's 13th largest retailer.
   Woolworth, which built its reputation in the five-and-dime store
business before expanding into specialty retailing, responded to
Dart's move with the adoption by its board of a ``poison-pill''
takeover defense.
   The retailer said in a statement Monday it was notified a
partnership controlled by Dart Chairman Herbert Haft had filed with
federal antitrust officials documents indicating the group intended
to acquire $15 million or more of Woolworth's stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM-UA Communications Inc., the
filmmaker that was sold and then bought back by financier Kirk
Kerkorian, says it has received several takeover proposals, and
plans to create a special committee of directors to study them.
   MGM-UA's chairman and chief executive, Lee Rich, declined to
identify the suitors in Monday's announcement. But analysts
suggested that Kerkorian, who owns 79 percent of the company's 50.1
million shares, may be seeking to take MGM-UA private.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. is approaching stockholders of
Farmers Group Inc. with a proposal hinting at a possible increase
in the $63 per share bid for the nation's seventh largest insurer.
   Batus said Monday it would consider paying more ``in a friendly
transaction supported by the board of Farmers Group.''
   Batus has been trying since January to win control of the Los
Angeles company, but its directors have refused to negotiate with
Batus, the American subsidiary of the London-based BAT Industries
Inc. PLC.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese auto plants in the United States,
through efficiency and parts imports, could cost the domestic
industry 45,000 jobs between 1985 and 1990, a General Accounting
Office study says.
   The job-loss estimate offered Monday was far below the 200,000
forecast by the United Auto Workers union.
   Japanese automakers have invested more than $5 billion in U.S.
assembly plants since 1980. Seven Japanese auto manufacturers and
more than 100 Japanese auto parts suppliers operate in the United
States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence dipped slightly in March
amid concern about unemployment, a new survey by a business-backed
research concern says.
   The Conference Board reported Monday that its Consumer
Confidence Index slipped to 112.8 from 114.9 last month. The index
has a 1985 base of 100.
   The Conference Board said consumers are confident about general
business conditions, but 29 percent of the survey's respondents
said jobs were plentiful, down from 31 percent in February.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturing corporations' after-tax profits
averaged 4.3 cents per dollar of sales in the October-December
quarter, down almost one-fourth from the third quarter of 1987, the
government says.
   The Commerce Department said Monday that American manufacturers'
after-tax profits totaled a seasonally adjusted $26.4 billion in
the fourth quarter, compared with $33.6 billion in the third
quarter, when profits averaged 5.6 cents per dollar.
</TEXT>
