<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has let stand a $3 million
libel award won by cigarette maker Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp.
against CBS Inc. and a television anchorman in Chicago.
   In another significant case, the high court agreed on Monday to
review rulings limiting Korean Air Lines' financial liability for a
1983 disaster in which 269 people died _ the shooting down of a KAL
passenger jet over Soviet airspace.
   The justices also agreed to examine the authority of federal
judges to second-guess decisions by pension and welfare plans that
deny benefits to workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has told
comestic companies they have 30 days to stop claiming their
over-the-counter creams can reverse or retard aging of the skin.
   In letters to 22 companies, the FDA on Monday effectively cut
off discussions that started last spring when the agency warned the
manufacturers that some of the claims they were making for their
products might subject them to the same kind of regulation applied
to drugs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. says it will study a
decision by a court in India before deciding whether to appeal the
court's order to pay $192 million in interim relief for victims of
the 1984 Bhopal gas disaster.
   But Carbide said the ruling by the High Court in the central
Indian state of Madhya Pradesh ``will not serve the real needs of
the Bhopal victims.''
   The court ruled Monday on Carbide's appeal of an earlier
decision in which a district judge ordered an interim relief
payment of $270 million. Union Carbide had argued that the interim
relief could prejudice a decision in the Indian government's $3
billion suit against the company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has more than 90 million
households for the first time, but each household contains fewer
people than ever, the Census Bureau says.
   The bureau said Monday that the 90,031,000 households in the
United States averaged 2.64 members each as of last July 1, down
from 2.65 people in 1986.
   ``The reason is, in effect, changes in the age structure,''
explained Campbell Gibson, a population specialist for the bureau.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. workers will meet in Kansas City,
Mo., this week to approve demands guiding the fitting of an
industry pattern United Auto Workers union contract to the smallest
of the Big Three automakers.
   The union's 140-member national Chrysler council said Monday it
will discuss and approve demands packaged by union leaders and an
elected, 10-member rank-and-file bargaining committee during
meetings from April 5-7.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted a broad loss Monday, as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials dropped 7.46 to 1,980.60.
   Bond prices tumbled and interest rates rose.
   The dollar turned mixed in the United States after falling in
Asia. The currency markets remained closed in Europe for the Easter
holiday observance.
   Soybean futures prices soared, grain prices were mostly higher,
precious metals rallied and cattle prices fell.
</TEXT>
