<DOCNO> AP880405-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Woolworth-Dart Bjt   04-05 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Woolworth-Dart, Bjt,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woolworth: Hafts Intend to Acquire Stake In Retailer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   F.W. Woolworth Co., faced with the prospect of
becoming Dart Group Corp.'s latest takeover target, is shoring up
its defenses.
   Woolworth said Monday that a partnership controlled by Dart
Chairman Herbert Haft _ who is fresh from an unsuccessful raid
against Stop & Shop Cos. _ had disclosed it planned to acquire $15
million or more of the retailer's stock.
   The nation's 13th largest retailer, which built its reputation
running a national chain of five-and-dime stores before expanding
into specialty retailing, said its board approved a ``poison pill''
takeover defense after Dart's disclosure.
   Woolworth issued a statement that its board adopted the defense
``to deter coercive or unfair takeover tactics.''
   Wall Street indicated it expected the Hafts to make a bid soon
for Woolworth. The retailer's stock shot up $8.87{ to $54.12{ in
New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Based on Monday's closing stock price and the company's roughly
65.7 million common shares outstanding, Woolworth had a market
value of about $3.6 billion.
   Less than a month ago, Dart terminated a $1.03 billion bid for
Boston-based Stop & Shop after its target agreed to a leveraged
buyout by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
   Landover, Md.-based Dart owns and operates Trak Auto Inc. and
Crown Books Corp.
   The Hafts repeatedly have said they were serious about buying
and operating a retailer, but doubts linger about their actual
intentions. Dart's string of unsuccessful but profitable takeover
moves against such retailers as Dayton Hudson Corp., Supermarkets
General Corp. and Safeway Stores Inc. in recent years has given
Haft and his son, Dart President Robert Haft, reputations as
corporate raiders.
   Dart has made millions of dollars from its takeover forays by
acquiring stock and later either selling it back to the target
company or to another suitor.
   Robert Haft was not available when a reporter called for comment
Monday.
   A source close to Dart confirmed the partnership had disclosed
in a March 18 filing with the federal government of its intentions
to acquire a Woolworth stake. The source declined to say whether a
takeover bid was in the offing.
   Joseph Carroll, a Woolworth spokesman, declined to comment when
asked what steps the company might take if and when the Hafts make
a takeover bid.
   Woolworth's poison pill would make a hostile takeover more
expensive by allowing the company's shareholders to buy its stock
at a steep discount. It becomes effective when an investor acquires
20 percent of Woolworth's stock, on the commencement of a tender
offer for 30 percent or more of the retailer's shares, or when a
hostile bidder acquires at least 15 percent of the company's stock.
   Edward Johnson, a retail industry analyst with Prescott Ball &
Turben Inc., said that if faced by a hostile buyout attempt
Woolworth might consider going private under a leveraged buyout.
   Other options open to the retailer include acquiring another
company itself or spinning off one of its units to shareholders.
   Johnson said Woolworth's low stock price and the company's
low-rental properties and successful specialty store formats make
it an attractive target. Woolworth, founded 109 years ago by Frank
W. Woolworth as a five-and-dime store, has grown to an empire of
more than 6,300 general merchandise and specialty stores worldwide.
In recent years, the company has shifted its focus from its
well-known Woolworth stores to its specialty operations, which
include Kinney shoe stores and Foot Locker and Lady Foot Locker
athletic footwear stores.
   For the fiscal year ended Jan. 30, Woolworth earned $251 million
on sales of $7.14 billion.
</TEXT>
