<1ST_LINE>r f PM-US-InternationalPay     04-05 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-International Pay,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Cheapest, Norway Most Expensive for US Employers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico was the cheapest country last year and
Norway the most expensive for U.S. employers who measure labor
costs in dollars, according to figures compiled by the U.S. Labor
Department.
   In dollar terms, costs in Mexico were $1.37 an hour in 1987,
compared with $1.49 in 1986 and a U.S. average of $13.46. Wages
more than doubled when measured in Mexican pesos, but the peso's
foreign exchange value fell so quickly that labor costs in dollars
actually declined.
   Norway's average hourly compensation totaled 118.52 kroner, or
about $17.58.
   The figures released Monday take into account of the drop in the
value of the dollar, changes in local pay rates, the cost of social
insurance and other benefits. The calculations do not include the
relative efficiency of workers in different countries.
   Wages and other benefits for workers rose in terms of Brazilian
cruzados, but in dollar terms there was a decline to $1.49 from
$1.60 an hour because of the low value of the cruzado against the
dollar.
   Brazil and Mexico are the Third World's two biggest debtors,
which tends to depress the foreign exchange value of their
currencies. They were the only two nations where dollar-denominated
labor costs dropped last year.
   Low wage rates in developing countries are considered a key
competitive advantage for those nations in exporting goods to the
United States.
   Labor in the newly-industrialized countries of Asia and Latin
America remained less than a fifth as costly as in the United
States. Costs in Asia's ``four tigers'' _ Hong Kong, South Korea,
Singapore and Taiwan _ rose by only 1 to 4 percentage points
relative to those in the United States.
   Of 22 countries, eight had costs higher than the $13.46 U.S.
hourly average.
   They were, in addition to Norway: Switzerland, 25.46 Swiss
francs, or $17.06; West Germany, 30.26 marks, or $16.83; Sweden,
96.07 krona, or $15.14; Netherlands, 30.61 guilders, or $15.11;
Belgium, 563.37 Belgian francs, or $15.08 and Denmark, 99.20
kroner, or $l4.49.
   All 23 countries for which the Labor Department had statistics,
including the United States, showed higher labor costs in terms of
their own currency.
   ``Japan's relative cost level in 1987 _ of 84 percent _ greatly
exceeded the previous peak of 72 percent reached in 1986,'' said
the report from the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   The increase in Japan's labor costs was due largely to the rise
of the yen against the dollar. That also was the reason for most of
the rise in European costs, although they also were affected by
declines in working hours by Norway and Denmark, the report stated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
