<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessDatabase     04-05 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Database,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Setting Up International Computer Bank Of Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American companies soon will have access
to a new computer database offering information about millions of
products made by their foreign competitors, according to the head
of the University of Tennessee project.
   ``It is the only one of its kind in the country,'' David Faulds,
assistant professor of international marketing, said Monday. ``It's
kind of surprising given the emphasis on product quality now.''
   The International Product Quality Database uses various consumer
reports to come up with product quality rankings from on an item
and on up to 48 specific product features, said Faulds. It also has
marketing information on the products, he said.
   ``We're still compiling (entries) and trying to develop
off-campus computer capability...so U.S. companies can tap into
this by phone,'' Faulds said.
   C. Warren Neel, dean of the university's College of Business
where the database was created, said the computer bank would give
U.S. manufacturers an edge in knowing the strengths and weaknesses
of their international competition, thereby helping them improve
their own positions in the marketplace.
   So far, the database has nearly a million brand names and
rankings on products sold in Australia, Belgium, Canada, Denmark,
France, West Germany, Great Britain, Japan, The Netherlands, New
Zealand, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland and the United States.
   Faulds said the database should be available to American
companies in less than two years, but the university had not
decided whether to let foreign businesses have access.
   ``We're kind of debating that right now,'' he said. ``There is a
political side.''
   Faulds said he has spent five years collecting the product
quality rankings and comments by such groups as automobile testers,
government bureaus, engineering associations, independent and
consumer product testing groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
