<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MGM-UA     04-05 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MGM-UA,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filmmaker Receives Several Takeover Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several unidentified suitors have
made takeover proposals for MGM-UA Communications Inc., the
filmmaker that was sold and bought back by financier Kirk Kerkorian.
   The company's announcement Monday sent MGM-UA stock up $3 for
the day to close at $12 a share on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The offers will be studied by a special committee of directors
which was to be created at a scheduled board meeting today.
   ``We have a duty to our shareholders to explore these matters,''
said Lee Rich, MGM-UA's chairman and chief executive.
   Rich declined to identify the suitors but analysts suggested
Kerkorian, who owns 79 percent of the company's 50.1 million
shares, may be seeking to take MGM-UA private.
   Other possible suitors, they said, are investors Marvin Davis
and Burt Sugarman, whose separate bids for other companies are
stalled and considered unlikely to succeed. Davis had no comment, a
spokesman said, and Sugarman was traveling and unavailable for
comment.
   The company said it announced the proposals when the New York
Stock Exchange expressed concern over an unusual increase in
trading of the company's stock.
   Kerkorian had been majority owner of the old Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer
and United Artists studios, then sold them in 1986 to media
entrepreneur Ted Turner for $1.5 billion plus assumption of some of
its debt. As part of that deal, Kerkorian immediately bought back
the UA segment.
   Later, Turner sold off all of the MGM unit, except its film
library, which he retained for use on his Atlanta-based
superstation WTBS. Kerkorian purchased the studio and Lorimar
Telepictures Corp. bought some other assets.
   Kerkorian paid a total of $730 million to buy back the two
segments.
   The new MGM-UA has had spotty success.
   Its recent film ``Moonstruck'' is a box-office hit and has been
nominated for six Academy Awards.
   Its new film, ``Bright Lights, Big City,'' starring Michael Fox,
ranked third in box-office gross for its debut weekend. Ticket
sales still were being tallied. Last year, the company scored a hit
with the James Bond thriller ``The Living Daylights.''
   But MGM-UA also has had box-office flops, including its
critically acclaimed but poorly attended ``Masquerade,'' as well as
``Fatal Beauty,'' ``Real Men,'' and ``Dead of Winter.''
   For its first quarter ended Nov. 30, earnings dropped 19 percent
to $2.1 million from $2.6 million, although revenue rose 39 percent
to $182 million from $131 million.
   The company cited continuing high start-up costs as well as an
unspecified writedown on the film ``Real Men.''
   For its first fiscal year ended Aug. 31, the company lost $88.1
million on revenue of $427.6 million.
   Davis, who has been seeking to get back into the entertainment
business since selling 20th Century Fox Film Corp. three years ago,
is bidding $770.1 million for Lorimar Telepictures Corp. But that
bid has been given short shrift by Lorimar, which is discussing a
merger with Warner Communications Inc.
   Sugarman, whose holdings range from cement production to the
company that created ``The Dating Game,'' is offering $1.58 billion
for Richmond, Va.,-based Media General Corp., which owns newspapers
and radio stations. But his overtures have been spurned by the
company's founding family, which holds voting control.
</TEXT>
