<DOCNO> AP880405-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ImportStudy     04-05 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Import Study,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Import Automakers' Study Refutes Big Three Dumping Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. auto importers have issued a study
attempting to refute a Big Three review that found Japanese
automakers were dumping compact pickup trucks on the U.S. market.
   The importers' study found Japanese automakers continued earning
profits averaging $1,000 per vehicle sold in the United States
compared with the $100-$125 profit on each vehicle they sold in
Japan.
   Japanese companies were earning an average $2,000 per vehicle
sold here when the yen began appreciating against the dollar in
1985, leaving a cushion that let them raise prices by less than the
yen had appreciated while preserving profits, the study indicated.
   The study was prepared by ICF Inc., a Fairfax, Va., research
firm, for Automobile Importers of America in anticipation of a
Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association study released last week.
   The import association's members include Toyota Motor Corp.,
Honda Motor Co., Mazda Motor Corp., Mitsubishi Motors Corp., Nissan
Motor Co. Ltd., Isuzu Motor Co. Ltd. and Suzuki Motor Co. Ltd.
   The MVMA study, prepared on behalf of General Motors Corp., Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp., was conducted by a Washington law
firm and found that Japanese makers were charging 10 percent to 48
percent less at the factory for small pickups destined for the U.S.
market than for the same vehicles destined for their home market.
   The MVMA study also argued that the Big Three U.S. automakers
were being injured by the dumping because they were not able to
make full use of factories and Japanese undercutting had hurt their
profits.
   The importers' study looked mostly at cars because of the
strength of the domestic truck market, John Reilly, the analyst who
prepared it, said Monday.
   ``One reason we weren't concerned about doing a dumping
calculation on trucks was because the (domestics makers') market
performance was so strong in terms of growth in sales and growth in
market share,'' Reilly said.
   In 1987, sales of small pickups by General Motors Corp., Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. grew by about 10 percent, or 135,000
trucks, while Japanese makers' sales fell by about the same in a
steady market, he said.
   Truck buyers are motivated strongly by price, Reilly said, so if
the Japanese makers were pricing unfairly low they would have held
or gained sales.
   The study, completed March 14, also indicated:
   _About 25 percent of Japanese makers' costs, including
advertising, marketing, distribution and freight, are incurred in
dollars and are not affected by the currency's weakness against the
yen.
   _Japanese companies have countered some of the pressures of the
strong yen by improving productivity and transferring parts
production from Japan to lower-cost countries such as South Korea
and Thailand.
   A U.S. industry charging foreign competitors with dumping, or
selling products in this market for less than in their home market
or for less than the cost of production, must prove it has been
harmed by the practice before the U.S. government will impose
punitive import duties.
   In the study, Reilly stated domestic makers held their share of
the U.S. car and truck market in 1987 despite a 1 million-vehicle
drop in their sales and a 1.15 million-vehicle overall drop in the
market.
   Much of the decline was borne by GM, whose share of the domestic
market fell nearly five percentage points in 1987 as its lost sales
to domestic competitors rather than to foreign makers, the study
found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers     04-05 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Hostile Takeover Bid For Koppers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investor partnership pursuing a hostile
$1.7 billion tender offer to acquire Koppers Co. is appealing a
federal judge's order blocking the takeover attempt.
   Judge Manuel Real in Los Angeles on Monday granted a preliminary
injunction to succeed his March 25 restraining order, which
temporarily halted the $60 a share bid by BNS Inc., a partnership
headed by British industrialist Brian Beazer and the investment
firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Koppers, a construction materials and services company that also
manufactures chemicals, has resisted the takeover attempt and
sought to block it in federal court on antitrust grounds. Beazer is
chairman of Beazer PLC, a general construction and construction
materials company.
   BNS immediately appealed the preliminary injunction to the 9th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Koppers stock declined 50 cents to $57.25 a share Monday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Separately, in Pittsburgh Gov. Robert P. Casey asked a federal
judge to allow his administration to intervene on behalf of Koppers
in another company lawsuit aimed at thwarting the takeover.
   Koppers had filed a federal lawsuit in Pittsburgh accusing the
unwanted suitors of violating securities laws.
   In a brief to U.S. District Judge Maurice Cohill, Casey said the
potential loss of 1,100 Pittsburgh-area employees of Koppers'
chemical businesses would hurt the local economy. It also said the
takeover could jeopardize agreements Koppers entered to reduce
pollution from its facilities.
   ``These environmental obligations could seriously impair the
ability of (the buyers) to obtain financiang for the offer and
impair the sale of the chemical assets,'' Casey's general counsel,
Morey M. Myers, said.
   Koppers also contended the company's stock was worth more than
the $60 a share offered by the Beazer group.
   Beazer attended the Pittsburgh hearing, but declined comment
afterward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
