<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-05 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against most major currencies
in quiet early trading in Europe today when markets reopened after
a four-day shutdown in most centers for the long Easter holiday
weekend.
   Gold prices were mixed after the holiday break.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.58 yen to close at 124.43 yen, compared
with 123.85 on Monday. Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at
124.52 yen.
   In London, the British pound, which hit a six-year high of
$1.8895 for two straight days last Thursday and Friday, eased to
$1.888. However, many dealers expected sterling to push ahead later
in the week.
   One Frankfurt dealer said general market sentiment toward the
dollar appeared cool, despite the rises in early trading.
   ``Few people want to give dollars at this level,'' said the
dealer. ``They are keeping an eye on the central banks and are
holding back. No sudden fall, but the dollar may drift slowly
lower.''
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning today, compared with late
Friday's quotes, included: 1.6585 West German marks, up from
1.6565; 1.3658 Swiss francs, up from 1.3635; 5.6225 French francs,
down from 5.6270; 1.8615 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8595; 1,230.20
Italian lire, up from 1,228.75; and 1.2415 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.2335.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $455.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $454.50. At mid-morning Tuesday, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $456.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $455.75, down from $457.50
late Thursday.
   Bullion dealers said trading was quiet with no new direction
following the Easter holiday.
   In Hong Kong, gold markets were closed because of a public
holiday.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.78 a troy
ounce, compared with Thursday's $6.72.
</TEXT>
