<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     04-05 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises From Three-Month Low, Stocks Fall Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar, recovering from a three-month low
against the Japanese yen, edged upward today in Tokyo. Stock prices
remained little changed in lackluster trading.
   After opening at 124.38 yen, the dollar edged up and ended the
day at 124.43 yen, up 0.58 yen from the Monday's close of 123.85
yen. It ranged between 124.30 yen-124.75 yen. On Monday, the U.S.
currency, opened at 123.70, its lowest opening level since Jan. 5
when it started trading at 123 yen.
   ``The dollar gained ground following an overnight advance at
Wall Street,'' said Ken Iiya of the Bank of Tokyo.
   There was nothing in particular to move market today, and
participants were only ``adjusting their positions'' in trading
currencies, he said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Average of 225 selected
issues, which gained 53.17 points Monday, slipped a modest 19.94
points, or 0.07 percent, today to move to 26,315.35 at the end of
the day's trading.
   ``Market fundamentals are firm,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko
Securities.
   He said the small decline of the stock market's key indicator
was prompted by participants having a wait-and-see attitude and
profit-taking selling after a quick surge in early morning trade.
   The Nikkei Stock Average rose 92 points just 27 minutes into the
seesion.
   Many investors stayed on the sidelines, cautious over what
effect higher U.S. interest rates may have on New York stocks,
another trader said.
   Share prices were mixed with the volume of the first section
trade standing at a light 700 million shares, down from 1.1 billion
shares Monday.
   Popular issues were textiles, foodstuffs and department stores.
Among the losers were steel, shipbuilding, heavy electricals and
some of the financials.
</TEXT>
