<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Off 16.9 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Tuesday, depressed by previous
declines in New York and Tokyo and by the continuing strength of
the British currency.
   Trading volume was light on the first day after the four-day
Easter holiday.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was off 16.9
points, or 1 percent, at 1,725.6 at midday.
   Volume was a low 170.1 million shares, down from 175.0 million
shares at midday Thursday.
   The market opened weaker on the back of previous declines in New
York and Tokyo.
   After recovering a little during the morning, the London market
fell again as the pound resumed its recent rise against the West
German mark. The rise has unsettled the equity market because of
worries about its effect on the major exporting companies' stocks,
which benefit from a weak pound.
</TEXT>
