<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ImportShortfall     04-05 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Import Shortfall,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Journal: Japanese Imports Below Quota for '87 Fiscal Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese automakers will fall short of their
quota for car exports to the United States in the fiscal year ended
March 31, an industry trade journal says.
   Lagging sales by Nissan Motor Co. Ltd. will account for most of
the shortfall, Automotive News predicted Monday.
   The Japanese government limits its automakers' car exports to
the U.S. to 2.3 million a year. Automotive News predicted that a
final tally of shipments will indicate a shortfall of 70,000 to
100,000 cars.
   Nissan shipped about 475,544 cars to the United States for the
1987 fiscal year, about 66,200 below its allocation from the
Japanese government, Automotive News said, citing high inventories
and slow sales of Nissan cars here.
   The Japanese government divides the total quota among exporting
automakers, preventing companies that use their full allocation
from shipping additional cars to take up the slack left by
companies with slow sales.
   Nissan's 1987 U.S. import sales were off 17.2 percent from 1986
and had dropped a further 32.2 percent in 1988 as of February.
Analysts have said Nissan sales have slipped recently because the
automaker has introduced relatively few new products.
   Automotive News said Honda Motor Co., Toyota Motor Corp., Mazda
Motor Corp., Mitsubishi Motors Corp., Chrysler Corp., which imports
Mitsubishi cars, and Fuji Heavy Industries, which makes Subaru
cars, were expected to have used their entire 1987 allocations.
   Robert McCurry, senior vice president for Toyota Motor Sales
U.S.A., has said that his company easily could sell more cars if it
were allowed to use the left-over allocations of companies such as
Nissan.
   While Honda and Toyota had few unsold cars in their inventories,
other makes had more than 50 days' worth, high for Japanese
companies, and Nissan had an estimated 206 days' supply, the trade
journal said.
   The Japanese Ministry of International Trade and Industry, which
sets the quota, is expected to maintain the 2.3 million level for
fiscal 1988 despite pressure from U.S. automakers.
   The Big Three have called for a lower export quota to
incorporate the growing number of Japanese cars built in the United
States. Honda, Toyota, Nissan and Mazda build cars here; Mitsubishi
will begin production this year in Bloomington-Normal, Ill.
   Toyota also will begin production this year at a new factory in
Georgetown, Ky., where it will build the Toyota Camry sedan, while
Subaru and Isuzu Motor Co. Ltd. are building a joint-venture plant
in Lafayette, Ind.
   These plants will have a combined capacity to build up to 2.5
million cars a year by 1990 at a time when the Big Three are
closing plants because they have too much capacity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
