<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ResortsInternational     04-05 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts International,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resorts International Directors To Talk With Griffin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of Resorts International Inc.
spurned the latest takeover offer from entertainer Merv Griffin,
but formed a special panel to meet with Griffin to decide if an
acceptable offer could be made.
   Although the action Monday appeared to open the door slightly to
Griffin, Resorts Chairman Donald Trump, who holds 88 percent of the
company's voting power, also renewed his pledge not to sell his
stock to the entertainer or to terminate a lucrative five-year
management contract with the company.
   Trump also vowed to block efforts by Griffin to get the company
to sell him 1.2 million new shares of Class B stock, which carries
100 votes per share. Such a move would give Griffin more voting
strength than Trump.
   Trump owns 95 percent of the company's current 572,000 Class B
shares.
   The company also has 5.7 million shares of Class A stock, which
carries one vote per share.
   Griffin has said in the past that he wouldn't be interested in
becoming partners with Trump.
   Griffin is offering $36 a share for Resorts' Class A common
shares and for the 1.2 million Class B shares that would be newly
issued.
   Trump's holdings could be sold under the offer only if they were
converted to Class A stock. Trump bought his stock a year ago for
$135 a share, but it has since lost much of its value.
   Last week, Trump abandoned his own tender offer to buy the stock
he doesn't already own for $22 a share.
   Resorts said a special committee comprised of Trump and a Trump
ally plus two outside directors would ``engage in discussions with
The Griffin Co. to explore whether an acceptable offer would be
made.''
   This is the first time that Resorts has indicated any
willingness to hold talks with the entertainer's privately held
investment company.
   Earlier in the day, Griffin said he and the president of his
company are to meet with New Jersey gaming officials next week on
Griffin's takeover bid for Resorts.
   The meetings are the start of a licensing process that usually
lasts a few weeks.
</TEXT>
