<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-DeBartolo-Federated     04-05 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DeBartolo-Federated,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DeBartolo Plans to Take Over Part of Federated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Edward J. DeBartolo says he's
negotiating to acquire part of Federated Department Stores Inc.
from Canadian developer Robert Campeau.
   Campeau Corp. has agreed to pay $6.6 billion for
Cincinnati-based Federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer.
   ``We're going to own a part of Federated, and we'll be in the
development end of Federated,'' DeBartolo said Monday from his
office in Youngstown, Ohio. ``We're going to be joint-venture
partners with Campeau in all new development deals that come out of
Allied Stores and Federated.''
   DeBartolo loaned Campeau about $480 million toward the Federated
acquisition in return for more than 50 percent of the shares of its
U.S. holding company, Campeau Corp. U.S.
   DeBartolo said he is still negotiating the percentage stake
he'll have in Federated, which owns such retailers as
Bloomingdale's, Filene's, Abraham & Straus and Foley's.
   Campeau battled R.H. Macy & Co. in a 10-week bidding war for
Federated. In a compromise, Campeau agreed to sell Federated's I.
Magnin and Bullock's-Bullock's Wilshire divisions to Macy for $1.1
billion.
   ``It was tough,'' DeBartolo said of the bidding war. ``It was a
good battle because both sides won.''
   Two years ago, DeBartolo loaned $150 million to Campeau to help
finance the $3.5 billion purchase of New York-based Allied Stores
Corp. DeBartolo had been an unsuccessful bidder for Allied, which
includes retailers Ann Taylor, Brooks Brothers and Jordan-Marsh.
   DeBartolo said areas where he and Campeau might expand include
the West and East coasts. Mall developers, including DeBartolo and
Campeau, in recent years have acquired retail chains, which give
them enormous leverage in developing malls and drawing other retail
tenants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-DP&L-St.MarysPower     04-05 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-DP&L-St. Marys Power,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Says DP&L Must Deliver Power</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Marys is CQ</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dayton Power & Light Co. must deliver
electricity generated by the non-profit Buckeye Power Inc.
cooperative to the city of St. Marys, a federal appeals court ruled
today.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled in favor of St. Marys, Buckeye Power and the affiliated
American Municipal Power-Ohio Inc. electricity cooperative in a
7-year-old dispute with Dayton Power & Light.
   The appeals court's unanimous decision upholds a Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission ruling that DP&L is bound by terms of a 1968
contract to deliver the Buckeye Power-generated electricity over
DP&L's power network to the city of St. Marys. Dayton Power & Light
had disagreed and appealed the commission's ruling.
   The appeals court said a Jan. 1, 1968, contract between Buckeye
Power and six investor-owned utilities, including Dayton Power &
Light, requires DP&L to ``wheel' the power over its lines from the
Buckeye cooperative to St. Marys. DP&L lawyers argued that the
company did not intend, under terms of the 1968 contract, to
deliver such power.
   St. Marys operates a municipal electric utility and buys
electric power from both DP&L and American Municipal Power-Ohio
Inc., a non-profit Ohio corporation which buys electricity from
Buckeye Power members for resale to AMP-Ohio member municipal
utilities.
   Buckeye Power generates and transmits electricity for 29 member
systems that constitute all of the electric cooperatives selling
power in Ohio.
   The dispute dates to April 1981.
</TEXT>
