<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Tandy Adv09-10   04-05 0986</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Tandy, Adv 09-10,1021</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 9-10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tandy's Moves Into Big Markets Hampered By Image, Network Systems</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALT SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tandy Corp.'s success in retailing home
computers is not carrying over easily into the big-business market.
   The parent company of the Radio Shack chain of electronics
stores announced its big push into the Fortune 1000 last August and
has relatively little to show for it so far.
   General Electric Co. and Wells Fargo Bank are the only big
customers that have so far allowed Tandy to mention them by name.
   The Radio Shack name, a magnet in shopping malls, does not
impress people who run corporate data centers. And some analysts
believe the company lacks the technical and sales savvy to make it
against industry giants like International Business Machines Corp.
   Tandy has about 8 percent of the overall U.S. computer market,
but only 2 to 3 percent of the Fortune 1000, according to Future
Computing Inc., a Dallas-based market researcher.
   ``The old Radio Shack quality issue still hurts them,'' said
John C. McCarthy, an analyst with Forrester Research in Cambridge,
Mass. ``It's one thing to buy a tape deck that doesn't work, but
it's another thing to have the computer that you're running your
company on break down.''
   The knock on quality may be unjustified, based on independent
evaluations. But Tandy still strikes some corporate buyers as a
company for electronics hobbyists.
   Computers made up only about 30 percent of Tandy's business last
year, outweighed by its sales of electronic parts and equipment,
radios, telephones, video equipment, tape recorders, toys and
communication equipment.
   Playing to its strengths, Tandy continues to focus most of its
efforts on selling to small- and medium-sized companies, Ed Juge,
the director of market planning, said in a recent interview.
   ``We have not claimed to have made large inroads into the big
corporate market. What we have said is that our level of
penetration is much greater,'' Juge said. ``It's never been our
intention to unseat IBM.''
   Juge said members of the sales force are told that for every
call they make on a Fortune 1000 company, they should be making
about 70 calls to smaller companies.
   Tandy's push to move in on IBM's established big-business market
began in August 1987. It centered on creating Tandy computer
centers separate from the Radio Shack stores, spending $80 million
to refurbish many of the 8,500 outlets and improving training for
sales people.
   That sales force has encountered some resistance, but most
companies are willing to try Tandy's systems, said Bob Myers, vice
president of Tandy's business products division.
   ``It hasn't proven too difficult to have most of them take a
unit for evaluation,'' Myers said. ``If we can get them to compare
our systems with IBM's, we compare very favorably.''
   Some analysts say there is a perception in corporate America
that Tandy lacks equipment to connect its computers to each other.
   ``In the very large corporate market, connectivity becomes a
very large issue,'' said Joe Cross, an analyst with Future
Computing. ``When you think of networking or office integration,
Tandy is not the first name that pops to mind.''
   Last month Tandy announced plans to license its DeskMate
interface to software developers, hoping to establish the look and
feel of its personal computer screen as an industry standard. It
said its computers can be easily hooked together in networks.
   But Eugene Glazer, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
New York, said he thinks Tandy's problem has more to do with
marketing than technology.
   ``Everything that's available in networking, Tandy has access
to. Tandy has systems as good as any out there, but it needs to
convince the large companies that it has quality products to
offer,'' he said.
   ``Selling connected solutions in the next couple of years will
be our thrust,'' said John Roach, Tandy's chairman and chief
executive, noting the company's sales force has been successful in
other areas.
   Sales at recently refurbished stores have risen about 4 percent
faster than sales at stores that have not been refurbished, the
company reported.
   Overall Tandy sales, meanwhile, improved to $3.66 billion in
calendar year 1987, compared with $3.32 billion in 1986, and net
income in 1987 improved to $289.8 million, compared with $216.4
million in 1986.
   Company executives also believe Fortune 500 companies, concerned
about quality and value, will look at Tandy products on an equal
footing with other computer systems.
   ``The problem is simply one of penetration and presence,''
Future Computing's Cross said. ``IBM, when it came out with a
personal computer, already had contacts with every company in the
country with its mainframes.''
   Industry rumors have it that Tandy plans this month to unveil
the first computer compatible with IBM's Personal System-2
computer, which was introduced in April 1987.
   Juge won't confirm or deny the rumor. The company has called a
news conference for April 21 to introduce two products _ one a
computer product and the other, ``an invention that will have
impact on multiple areas in the electronics field.''
   Roach said Tandy waited to introduce high-end personal computers
rather than put an inferior product on the market.
   ``We have a very broad-based distribution network and many
repeat customers,'' he said. ``Often we will elect not to carry a
product because we feel like some percentage of the market will not
be happy with it.''
   Tandy also has begun fighting for a share of the market in
portable laptop computers that can perform many of the same
functions as an IBM-compatible desk unit.
   To help the company compete in the tough laptop market, Tandy
recently purchased Grid Systems Corp. of Fremont, Calif., for $55
million. Grid, which designs, manufactures and markets rugged,
magnesium-cased portable microcomputers, will become a wholly owned
subsidiary of Tandy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions April 9-10</NOTE>
</DOC>
