<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Mansfield-Toshiba     04-05 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mansfield-Toshiba,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamura Asks U.S. Ambassador to Work Against Toshiba Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade minister told U.S. Ambassador Mike
Mansfield on Tuesday that the Reagan administration should oppose a
bill in Congress that would punish Japan's Toshiba Corp. for its
subsidiary's illegal sale of sensitive machines to the Soviet
Union, an official said.
   Hajime Tamura, minister of international trade and industry,
handed Mansfield a letter to the administration of President Reagan
asking for the elimination of a sanction clause on Toshiba in the
pending trade bill, said the official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Reagan administration officials have said they would recommend
that Reagan veto the trade bill if it includes sanctions on
Toshiba. The bill is working its way through a conference committee
of the House and Senate.
   The official said Tamura expressed concern that the American
sanction would run counter to a basic principle of the Coordinating
Committee for Exports to Communist nations, and that it would hurt
that group's unity.
   Under the rules of COCOM, the Western body that monitors sales
of strategic items to communist nations, effective enforcement of
export controls is the responsibility of each member nation.
   The official quoted Mansfield as saying the U.S. government
opposes using a trade bill to punish a parent company of a business
that violates the agreement.
   Toshiba Machine Co., a subsidiary of Toshiba Corp., Japan's
second largest electronics company, is accused of selling
sophisticated machines to the Soviets illegally between 1982 and
1984. U.S. officials have said the machines might have permitted
Moscow to turn out propellers that could make submarines quieter
and harder to detect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Stevens-Odyssey     04-05 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Stevens-Odyssey,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Odyssey Announces Financing Plans for Stevens Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York investment firm said Tuesday that it
has obtained all the commitments necessary to finance its $1.14
billion bid for the textile giant J.P. Stevens & Co.
   The firm Odyssey Partners has a $64-a-share tender offer in
progress for all of Stevens' 17.8 million shares. The offer expires
April 11.
   Another textile company, West Point-Pepperell Inc. of West
Point, Ga., also has a tender offer underway for all of Stevens'
stock at $62.50 a share.
   Pepperell launched its tender offer March 24, after the Neevens had
reached an agreement with Odyssey on a
