<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Texaco     04-05 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco,0259</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Icahn Files Appeal of Texaco Reorganization Plan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate raider Carl C. Icahn has
filed an appeal of a federal bankruptcy judge's approval of
Texaco's reorganization plan.
   But Texaco attorney Harvey Miller said the filing, done late
Friday in U.S. Bankruptcy Court here, will not stop the $5.6
billion plan, set to begin Thursday.
   Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder, said he still opposed to
two key parts of the plan.
   One was the release from any legal liabilities of all the
participants in Texaco's ill-fated 1984 acquisition of Getty Oil Co.
   He also opposed a default provision in a loan of up to $3
billion which Texaco will use to help fund the reorganization.
   Under a provision of Texaco's agreement with a consortium of
banks providing the money, the loans would be callable if more than
half of its 14-member board is replaced by new directors, or if an
investor obtains 30 percent of the company's stock.
   Two-thirds of the banks must vote to force Texaco to pay back
the money, however.
   Texaco entered Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on April 12 last
year, claiming it was forced to do so to avoid having to pay a
potentially ruinous multibillion-dollar security bond while
appealing a $10.3 billion judgment held against it by Pennzoil Co.
   Houston-based Pennzoil won the judgment when a Houston jury
ruled that Texaco had improperly interfered with a Pennzoil attempt
to acquire part of Getty Oil Co. and bought Getty itself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
