<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Corning     04-05 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Corning,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit Falls in 1st Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORNING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corning Glass Works said Tuesday its profit
fell 17.4 percent in the first quarter compared with results a year
ago that had included a one-time gain stemming from an accounting
change.
   For the quarter ended March 27, Corning reported a profit of
$37.1 million or 83 cents a share, compared with earnings of $44.9
million, or 97 cents a share, for the same quarter in 1987.
   Sales for the quarter rose 3 percent to $462.6 million $448.5
millipon a year earlier.
   The results a year ago included a gain of $14.2 million from a
change in accounting for certain manufacturing costs over a period
of years.
   Without that benefit, Corning said its first-quarter earnings
for 1988 would have risen 21 percent from last year's results.
   Corning manufactures consumer housewares, automobile pollution
control devices, fiber optics and specialty glass and ceramics. It
also operates a network of clinical testing labs.
   It was recently dropped its effort to expand that network by
acquiring International Clinical Laboratories Inc. of Nashville,
Tenn.
   Corning had bid $35 per share, or $360 million, for the
Tennessee company, but wound up selling its stake in the concern to
pharmaceutical giant SmithKline Beckman Corp. which bid $37 a
share, or about $400 million.
</TEXT>
