<2ND_LINE>BC-Parks-Sara Lee,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Sara Lee Buys Interest In Baltimore Sausage Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sara Lee Corp. recently acquired a 45 percent
stake in the privately held Parks Sausage Co., one of Baltimore's
most successful minority-owned businesses, executives of both
companies say.
   The deal was completed about seven weeks ago. Details were not
disclosed.
   Parks had 1987 revenues of more than $25 million with a
workforce of about 200.
   Last year the company agreed to move its plant from the current
downtown site to an industrial park to help make room for the
proposed Camden Yards stadium project.
   According to a city official quoted in Tuesday's Daily Record,
Sara Lee had entered into negotraitions with Parks before the
city's relocation discussions started. Sara Lee will help finance
the relocation, the official said.
   Sara Lee is a Chicago-based consumer goods conglomerate with
1987 sales of $9.15 billion. Its consumer foods division includes
several well-known brands, such as Jimmy Dean Meats and Hillshire
Farm.
   Other Sara Lee divisions include personal and household care
products, vacuum cleaners and food service distribution. Among its
better-known holdings are Hanes Hosiery and The Coach Stores.
   Sara Lee spokesman Steve Savage said the company acquired
several sausage makers in the last year and plans to expand further.
