<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1503EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-JobHunting Bjt   04-05 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Job Hunting, Bjt,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Placement Pro Says It's a Tough Year for College Grads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New college graduates this spring will face a
tight job market, with competition-conscious companies less willing
to offer extended on-the-job training, a veteran placement
professional says.
   ``Employers, especially small- and medium-size companies which
represent the areas of greatest job growth, today have neither the
time nor inclination to `bring somebody along' gradually,'' said
James E. Challenger, president of Chicago-based Challenger, Gray &
Christmas Inc., which descibes itself as the nation's oldest
outplacement firm. ``Now, you either sink or swim, right away.''
   An increasingly competitive marketplace is facing all companies,
Challenger said in an analysis of the 1988 college graduate job
outlook, released Monday.
   ``As a result, many of the larger firms have instituted
corporate downsizing to pare their overhead and operating expenses,
which has not only eliminated or combined many existing jobs but
also prevented the creation of many new entry-level jobs.
   ``The two-year training programs for beginners are among
casualties of world market competition,'' he said. ``Companies want
results now, not in two years.''
   Challenger, 62, founded his firm in 1962 and says it has helped
more than 20,000 people who have lost jobs find employment. The
firm has 14 regional offices in cities including Los Angeles,
Boston, Dallas and Milwaukee.
   Challenger said the job market won't favor most graduates
because companies are more selective. He said early indications
suggest that fewer than the usual one-third of students getting
four-year degrees will have jobs lined up when they receive
diplomas.
   College placement officials say that just 20 percent to 25
percent of students graduating have jobs set, but things could
change by the end of May, Challenger said in a telephone interview.
   The graduates likely to have the most luck finding positions are
``the A students and those with specialty degrees such as
engineering or accounting,'' or those going into sales, Challenger
said.
   ``Companies are always willing to take on sales trainees''
because many sales jobs are low-salary or operate on commission, he
said.
   Some students are taking unpaid internships to obtain good jobs,
Challenger said. Others may have to take part-time work as they
search for permanent positions.
   Some placement experts disagree with Challenger's assessment.
Victor Lindquist, director of placement for Northwestern University
in Evanston, said his survey of employers indicates a better
employment year spring graduates.
   He said in a telephone interview Tuesday that the university's
survey last fall forecast a 10 percent increase in new-graduate
employment over the previous year.
   Lindquist agreed that takeovers and corporate restructurings
have heightened competition for new jobs.
   ``If you were making $35,000 and you're offered $30,000 you
might not like it, but it's better than unemployment,'' said
Lindquist.
   But at the same time, he said, many companies ``are very, very
heavily in the market (for new employees) and have made a big
commitment to training.
   ``Not having a job by commencement is not necessarily the end of
the world,'' Lindquist said. ``There'll be more kids hired in June,
July, August and September than there probably were in the previous
four months. And there's nothing at all unusual about that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880405-0281 </DOCNO>
