<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged higher against major foreign
currencies Tuesday as traders decided Japanese investors were
unlikely to unload dollars.
   Gold prices fell. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
was bid at $452.65 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $455.85
late Monday.
   The dollar climbed about 1 percent against the West German mark,
British pound and Japanese yen.
   The U.S. currency's strength prompted people who had been
betting on a dollar decline to retreat by buying dollars to cover
short positions. That contributed to the dollar's rally.
   The dollar had been depressed in March by fears that Japanese
trust funds and securities firms would lighten their dollar
holdings starting April 1 because they would no longer need to
support it for accounting purposes.
   When Japanese dollar-selling failed to materialize, investors
took courage, said Charles A. Spence, vice president of foreign
exchange at First Interstate Bank of California in Los Angeles.
   Dollar buyers were also encouraged by news reports that Federal
Reserve Governor Wayne Angell expressed a strong desire to lower
inflation, said Peter Gloyne, senior trader at First National Bank
of Chicago.
   If the Fed tried to combat inflation through higher interest
rates, it would raise the yield of dollar-denominated securities
and make foreigners want to buy dollars.
   Interest rates finished Tuesday little changed.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.58 yen to a close at 124.43 yen, compared with 123.85
on Monday. Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at 125.15 yen.
At the end of the trading day in New York, the dollar was quoted at
125.28 yen, up from 124.18 yen late Monday. In London, the British
pound fell to $1.8800 from $1.8895 on Good Friday. Later in New
York, the pound fell to $1.8790 from $1.8857 late Monday.
   There was spotty foreign-exchange trading in Europe on Friday
but no precious metals trading. The European financial markets were
closed on Monday for the Easter holiday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday's
rates, were: 1.6706 West German marks, up from 1.6540; 1.3769 Swiss
francs, up from 1.3639; 1.2418 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2370;
5.6645 French francs, up from 5.6085; and 1,237.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,227.25.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Friday's rates:
1.6690 West German marks, up from 1.6565; 1.3765 Swiss francs, up
from 1.3635; 5.6605 French francs, up from 5.6270; 1.8700 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.8595; 1,234.50 Italian lire, up from 1,228.75;
1.2395 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2335.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery was bid at $453.40 a troy ounce, down from $456.70 late
Monday.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $451.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $454.50. In Zurich, gold fell,
closing at a bid $453.50 an ounce compared with $457.50 late
Thursday.
   In Hong Kong, gold markets were closed because of a public
holiday.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery was bid
at $6.65 an ounce, down from $6.789 an ounce late Monday. Silver
bullion prices fell on the London market, where the metal was
trading at a late bid price of $6.65 a troy ounce, compared with
Thursday's $6.72.
</TEXT>
