<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AirFares Bjt   04-05 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Fares, Bjt,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern, Continental Cut Some Air Fares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two units of fare-wars veteran Texas Air Corp. fired a spring
salvo Tuesday by announcing price cuts on tickets purchased by
April 14.
   The subsidiaries, Eastern Airlines and Continental Airlines, may
touch off a price skirmish only a few weeks after all the major
carriers hiked fares steeply.
   But the cuts _ limited by the purchase-period requirements and
hemmed in by other restrictions _ stop short of a full-fledged
price war. Although observers believe the reductions made by
Miami-based Eastern and Houston-based Continental are likely to be
matched by other major airlines, they don't see a major fare battle
on the horizon.
   ``It's definitely not a fare war; it's barely a skirmish,'' said
Edward Starkman, an airline analyst for investment firm PaineWebber
Inc.
   If anything, the current climate for the industry appears to
favor fare hikes rather than reductions. The major U.S. carriers
have posted an average increase in passenger traffic of 7 percent
to 8 percent since New Year's Day from the same period last year.
   The robust demand prompted the big airlines to raise their
first-class, economy and discount fares in mid-March by 15 percent
to 85 percent, depending on the destination. The carriers also
tightened restrictions on their popular ``MaxSaver'' discount
fares, the cheapest available.
   The big fare hikes came several weeks before they normally do,
as the airlines jumped the gun on the peak travel season that
starts in April.
   Eastern and Continental, the nation's sixth-largest and
fifth-ranked airlines, respectively, said Tuesday they were cutting
some fares in anticipation of a slack period coming up for leisure
travel.
   ``The period between Easter and the start of summer vacations in
mid-June is always a slack travel time, and an early Easter extends
the off-peak period this year,'' said George J. Brennan, vice
president of marketing communications for Eastern.
   ``We hope to give leisure travel a boost with fares so low that
people will take a trip they might not otherwise plan.''
   With the new fares, the airline said, passengers will be able to
fly midweek to more than 80 U.S. cities on Eastern for a maximum of
$99 one way (based on a round-trip tariff of $198). Eastern's
round-trip fare between Miami and New York, for example, will fall
to $178 under the program, compared with the current ``MaxSaver''
fare of $208.
   Although there are some minor differences, Eastern and
Continental introduced similar programs. The non-refundable tickets
must be purchased by April 14 (starting Tuesday for Eastern and
Wednesday for Continental), and used for travel from April 18
through June 15.
   Passengers must travel between noon Monday and noon Thursday.
Round-trip travel and a Saturday night stay are required.
   Those restrictions limit the program to eight travel days in
April, 18 days in May and nine in June.
   And there are still more restrictions. For Eastern, tickets must
be bought within 24 hours after making reservations. Continental is
even stricter: It requires reservations and ticketing to be done at
the same time.
   Both airlines prohibit schedule changes to be made the special
fares and limit the number of available seats on each flight.
   ``It's pretty savvy of Texas Air Corp.,'' said Andrew Geller, a
transportation analyst for Provident National Bank in Philadelphia.
``It very effectively cancels out every businessperson'' from using
the new fares.
   Geller suggested that the reduced tariffs could encourage people
who had planned vacations to take them within the specified time
frames.
</TEXT>
