<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KansasCitySouthern     04-05 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kansas City Southern,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hallmark, KC Southern Buy Out Hostile Suitor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York investor Howard Kaskel has sold
his 11.7 percent stake in Kansas City Southern Industries Inc. for
about $77.6 million, getting a hefty premium to terminate his
eight-month takeover attempt.
   The railroad holding company joined with Hallmark Cards Inc. to
acquire stock controlled by an investor group led by Kaskel for $60
a share on Monday, a premium of more than $10.25 a share _ more
than 20 percent _ over the market price at the time.
   Kansas City Southern shares traded at $49.75 at the time the
buyback was disclosed. The stock fell $1.37{ a share on Monday and
dropped another $3.75 to close at $46.50 a share Tuesday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Kansas City Southern bought 54 percent of Kaskel's stock, or
694,000 shares, for $41.6 million while Hallmark bought the
remaining 600,600 shares for $36 million.
   Kaskel had proposed a friendly buyout of the Kansas City
Southern shares that his group didn't own for $587.6 million, or
$60 a share. After the company spurned the offer, Kaskel threatened
a proxy battle to name two of his group to the board of directors
at Kansas City Southern's annual meeting May 3.
   Fred Spar, a spokesman for Kaskel, said the investor agreed to
sell because he could not convince Kansas City Southern to accept
his plans for gaining control of the company.
   ``There were several discussions with management, but we came to
the conclusion that we would not be able to go forward on a
friendly basis,'' he said.
   Hallmark's purchase will make it Kansas City Southern's largest
stockholder, with 1.04 million shares, or 9.4 percent of those
outstanding. The Kansas City-based greeting card giant said it
liked Kansas City Southern's long-term prospects and did not plan
to take control.
   Hallmark previously owned 4 percent of Kansas City Southern's
stock. Irvine O. Hockaday Jr., president and chief executive
officer of Hallmark, held a smiliar post at Kansas City Southern
from 1981 until 1983.
   Jim Wineland, a stock analyst with Waddell & Reed Inc., said the
premium price paid to Kaskel reflected the threat he posed to the
company.
   ``It's called greenmail. Just on the face, you'd have to say it
was worth that much to get Kaskel out of the way,'' Wineland said.
   Jeffrey Perry, of the investment firm C.J. Lawrence, Morgan
Grenfell Inc. in New York, called the deal ``the most blatant case
of greenmail I've seen in a long time.'' He said the price Hallmark
paid for the stock was not justified by Kansas City Southern's
expected earnings.
   KCSI's main holding is the Kansas City Southern Lines, the
nation's 14th largest railroad. It also owns 87.3 percent of DST
Systems, Inc., a financial record keeper based in Kansas City,
where it and affiliated operations employ about 2,000 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
