<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mexico-Oil     04-05 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Oil,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Arabian Oil Minister to Visit Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia's oil minister will visit Mexico
this week to discuss the international market situation, the
government announced Tuesday.
   A statement from the Energy and Mines Department said the visit
of Hisham Nazer of Saudi Arabia ``responds to the traditional and
active Mexican policy of dialogue and cooperation with other
producing nations of petroleum, members or not members of OPEC, as
well as with consuming nations.''
   It said such communication ``has the purpose of reconciling
national interests with the development of a stable internaitonal
market with profitable prices, that might allow a more predictable
and consistent evolution of the international market situation.''
   The statement said Nazer would arrive Wednesday and meet
Thursday with President Miguel de la Madrid after first holding
discussions with Energy and Mines Secretary Fernando Hiriart and
with Francisco Rojas, director of the state oil monopoly Pemex.
   Mexico is not a member of the Organization of Oil Exporting
Countries but closely monitors its price and production guidelines.
It was the world's fourth largest oil producer in 1985 but since
has slipped to sixth place behind the Soviet Union, the United
States, Saudi Arabia, Iran and China.
   On Monday night, Pemex announced that it lowered the price of
its light Isthums crude by $1.62 a barrel to Japanese customers in
March.
   Pemex said in a statement that the price of the light oil was
$13.86 a barrel in March, down from $15.48 a barrel in February.
   Japan buys 180,000 barrels a day of crude, accounting for 11
percent of Mexico's total oil exports in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
